<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PlaneCrashes 1stLd-Writethru a0799 04-04 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Plane Crashes, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0799,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seven Die, One Injured in Four Plane Crashes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lead to UPDATE with another small-plane crash in
California bringing toll to seven. SUBS 6th graf pvs, `West of...',
with 2 grafs to add detail on 2nd California crash; CORRECT that
bodies of victims of glider crash had been thrown from glider, sted
found in wreckage. Picks up 7th graf, `The glider...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   At least seven people died in small-plane crashes in Colorado
and California, including three killed Sunday when a single-engine
plane smashed into the ground after taking off from the Colorado
Springs Municipal Airport.
   A fourth person aboard the Beechcraft Bonanza, an 18-year-old
man, suffered serious burns and was listed in ``very critical
condition'' at Saint Francis Hospital in Colorado Springs, nursing
supervisor Donna Skovgaard said. He was transferred later to a burn
unit at Penrose Hospital.
   Names of the victims were being withheld pending notification of
relatives.
   The plane had just taken off when it crashed and burned at about
3:45 p.m. in a sparsely populated area about one mile north of the
airport, said Sgt. Dean Kelsey of the El Paso County sheriff's
office.
   In Calpella, Calif., about 120 miles north of San Francisco, the
only occupant of a single-engine plane was killed Sunday when the
aircraft crashed. The victim was not immediately identified, said a
dispatcher for the Mendocino County sheriff's office who declined
to give his name.
   Sunday evening, at least one person died when a twin-engine
aircraft crashed and burned on a hillside in Orinda, 15 miles east
of San Francisco. A second person was believed to be aboard the the
plane, said dispatcher Angela Hutch, but she didn't know if that
person had survived or not.
   West of Boulder, Colo., authorities on Sunday found the bodies
of two people who died in the crash of a glider in the mountains
Saturday. The wreckage was also found some distance away,
authorities said. The two were identified as James Lesley Clayton,
30, of Boulder, the pilot; and Loren M. Swisher, 40, of Green
River, Wyo.
   The glider had been released over Twin Sisters Peak at 12:15
p.m. Saturday and was reported missing at about 3 p.m. when it
failed to return to Cloud Base, a Boulder aircraft school where
Clayton worked as an instructor.
   Searchers found the wreckage Sunday morning in steep,
snow-covered terrain east of the Green Mountain summit in the
Flatirons.
</TEXT>
