<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     04-04 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0594</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARROLLTON, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lowell Anderson doesn't know what to do
with his first vacation in nearly 30 years, but a check for more
than $150,000 for all the time off he missed should broaden his
choices.
   ``It was like winning the lottery,'' said Anderson, the general
manager of Carrollton Municipal Utilities. ``But I pretty much knew
it was there. I figured I'd retire a little early.''
   Anderson, 60, earns about $56,000 a year running the utilities
in this a town of 4,700 residents 70 miles northeast of Kansas
City. He said he took his last vacation after he moved into the
general manager's job in 1959.
   After his promotion, the City Council allowed him to carry his
vacation time forward if he chose.
   ``Things just got busy, and I didn't figure I could take any
time off away from the job,'' he said. ``But they're going to make
me take some time this year. I still don't know what I'll do with
it.''
   Mayor Jack Mathis said the city-owned utility didn't see
compensatory time off as a realistic option and issued a check for
$153,400, throwing in a few weeks' vacation.
   ``We didn't think we'd do very well without him for 2{ years,''
Mathis said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GULFPORT, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Since a pair of rabbits arrived 30
Easters ago, owners of the Happy Chick Farm north of Gulfport have
been forced into the fish-bait business by necessity.
   Evolved from a 4-H Club project outgrown by the children of
Marie and Howard Mays, the farm has produced thousands of bunnies
and billions of worms and crickets.
   ``But I'm not directly into Easter business,'' Howard Mays said
Friday. ``Everything I have is breeder stock. But we've had pet
shops calling all afternoon.''
   The rabbits live in cages suspended above worm beds. Gravity
fertilizes the earthworm habitat with bunny byproducts _ an
innovation sprung from necessity.
   ``The odor got bad, so we got into the worm business,'' Mrs.
Mays said.
   With the help of eight employees, the Mays market 2{ million
wigglers per week. After a worm harvest, the leftover bedding dirt
is sold to gardeners. Profits from the highly-prized potting soil
keep Mrs. Mays driving a new car.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ELIZABETHTON, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A one-time rivalry between residents
over whose chickens produced the hardest eggs has turned into a
homecoming for this eastern Tennessee community.
   Natives from as far away as California and Iowa visited Sunday
to tap colored Easter eggs together in a 165-year-old contest to
see whose withstands the blows best.
   The event, dubbed the Peters Hollow Egg Fight, began in 1823
when the folks of Rome Hollow claimed the shells of their eggs were
harder than those laid in Peters Hollow down the creek.
   The eggs are tapped small end to small end while the contestants
stand in a circle until only the hardest one is left.
   Some families keep carefully guarded secrets about the way their
eggs are boiled and colored and what they feed their chickens.
   Gebe Ritchie, who has been chief judge and master of ceremonies
for 27 years, said every shell-hardening trick in the book has been
tried.
   ``One year I disqualified someone who put his eggs in the
freezer for a year,'' he said.
   About 300 people showed up for this year's contest. The top four
finishers in the junior and adult competitions received trophies.
</TEXT>
