<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Reagan     04-04 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Attending Library Luncheon</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: likely to stand; closed luncheon to begin about 3 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan turned his
attention to his own presidential library today after spending a
quiet Easter out of public view.
   Reagan, in the fourth day of a holiday vacation, was being
accompanied by his wife, Nancy, to the home of Gen. William Lyon in
Cota de Caza in Orange County for a reception and luncheon with
some 75 Reagan Library Foundation supporters.
   The Reagans did not venture from their 688-acre ranch on Sunday,
with the president taking care of routine paperwork and the first
couple going horseback riding under a brilliant sun.
   Planners of the Ronald Reagan Presidential Library were forced
to abandon a site at Stanford University after widespread protests
on the Palo Alto campus, and they have encountered skepticism over
a proposal to build the facility on a 100-acre site near Simi
Valley.
   The site, donated by the real estate firm of Blakeley-Swartz,
impinges on a greenbelt area that is protected from large-scale
development by a decade-old, non-binding agreement among Simi
Valley, Moorpark and Thousand Oaks.
   White House aides said that during his vacation stay in the
Santa Ynez Mountains, Reagan was being kept abreast of events in
troubled Panama and elsewhere around the world.
   White House aides also hoped to use this week away from
Washington to work on plans for Reagan's May 26-June 2 summit in
Moscow with Kremlin leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   The Reagans arrived in California on Friday and will vacation
until Sunday, when they return to the White House.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
