<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Boston,0119</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Boston Mayor Says Beantown Is Changing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Mayor Kevin White says yuppies and a
booming economy are stripping the city of its legendary love of
politics.
   ``There's no real bite in the neighborhoods, no real interest in
politics,'' said White, mayor for 16 years. ``The city's changing.
There are no deep political ties.''
   White, 58, now a part-time professor at Boston University,
points to the presidential candidacy of Gov. Michael S. Dukakis to
back up his point.
   ``It's not even good cocktail talk, when 20 years ago, to have a
presidential candidate from your state, everybody would be
buzzing,'' White said in an interview with The Boston Sunday Globe.
</TEXT>
