<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 0101EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Mexico-Candidates     04-04 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexico-Candidates,0388</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Five Candidates Oppose Governing Party Nominee In Mexico</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Mexico-Politics, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a list of the candidates running
against the nominee for the governing Institutional Revolutionary
Party, Carlos Salinas de Gortari, in presidential elections
scheduled for July 6:
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>National Democratic Front</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Cuauhtemoc Cardenas</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A former governor of Michoacan in central Mexico, Cardenas, 53,
was a leader of the Democratic Current, a dissident movement in the
governing party fighting for reforms. After the party refused to
consider him as a candidate, he mounted his own candidacy in the
coalition National Democratic Front.
   He is the son of the late President Lazaro Cardenas, whose
expropriation of foreign oil holdings and defense of workers and
peasants made him one of the country's most popular presidents.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Mexican Socialist Party</HEAD>
<HEAD>Heberto Castillo</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The party was formed in 1987 with the merger of several leftist
parties, among them one that includes the Communist Party.
Castillo, a National University professor and leader of the 1968
student movement, was jailed for 2{ years for his activities.
Castillo, 59, was chosen as the party's presidential candidate when
it held the country's first presidential primary.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>National Action Party</HEAD>
<HEAD>Manuel Clouthier</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The 53-year-old candidate, a well-to-do business leader and
rancher from the northwestern state of Sinaloa, supports private
enterprise, more government cutbacks, greater foreign investment
and allowing peasants to own land they currently can use and pass
on to their children, but not sell.
   National Action, known as PAN, is the largest opposition party
and for years was the only significant opposition.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Revolutionary Workers Party</HEAD>
<HEAD>Rosario Ibarra de Piedra</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Ibarra de Piedra is a candidate for a second time of the party,
the most radical opposition group. But the 61-year-old candidate is
not a party member. She became politically active and formed an
organization to defend political prisoners after her son
disappeared following his arrest in 1975.
   The party refused to agree to a primary of all leftist parties
to choose a single candidate.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Mexican Democratic Party</HEAD>
<HEAD>Gumersindo Magana Negrete</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The party describes itself as inspired by a social Christian
philosophy that supports neither communism nor capitalism ``without
a social dimension.''
   Magana, a 48-year-old lawyer, was long active in the
conservative Catholic Sinarquista movement, a predecessor of the
Mexican Democratic Party.
</TEXT>
