<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PoliticalBriefs     04-04 0875</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Briefs,880</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poll: Dukakis Holds Small Lead Over Jackson In Wisconsin</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis held a
narrow lead over Jesse Jackson in the week leading up to Tuesday's
Wisconsin presidential primary, according to a newspaper poll.
   Dukakis held a 43 percent to 35 percent lead over Jackson among
voters who said they would vote for, or leaned toward, a Democratic
candidate if the primary had been held at the time of the poll, The
Milwaukee Journal reported in its Sunday editions.
   On the Republican side, the poll showed Vice President George
Bush would easily defeat his remaining primary challenger, former
television evangelist Pat Robertson but might have a difficult time
winning Wisconsin in the general election if Dukakis were the
Democratic nominee.
   Bush held an 80 percent to 7 percent lead over Robertson, the
poll showed.
   However, Bush and Dukakis ended in a virtual tie among voters
who were asked which of the two they would likely vote for in the
general election in November.
   The poll was conducted Wednesday and Thursday and was based on
interviews with 845 randomly-selected Wisconsin adults who said
they were absolutely or fairly certain to vote in the primary, the
newspaper said. The margin of error was plus or minus 5 percentage
points.
   The Wisconsin primary is expected to draw a large voter turnout
with as many as 1.6 million voters or 45 percent of the eligible
voters participating, state Elections Board officials said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Jackson Should Get Nomination If He Gets Most Delegates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A majority of Democrats and voters leaning
toward the party say Jesse Jackson should get the Democratic
nomination if he leads in delegates at the time of the convention,
according to a Newsweek poll.
   Sixty-six percent of those polled said that if Jackson had more
delegates and more of the popular vote than the other Democratic
candidates _ but not enough to win the Democratic nomination
outright _ the party's other candidates should rally behind him.
   A total of 20 percent said the other candidates should not rally
behind him, according to Sunday's poll.
   And Jackson's negative ratings remain high, with Massachusetts
Gov. Michael Dukakis running stronger against Vice President George
Bush than he does.
   Thirteen percent of the respondents in Sunday's survey described
their opinion of Jackson as ``very favorable'' and 40 percent said
their view of him was ``mostly favorable.'' Twenty-four percent
said their opinion of him was ``mostly unfavorable,'' with 14
percent saying it was ``very unfavorable.''
   The Gallup Organization's survey of 757 registered Democratic
and Republican voters telephoned March 30 and 31 showed Bush
leading Dukakis 49 percent to 44 percent; Bush was favored over
Jackson 58 percent to 32 percent, according to Newsweek.
   The margin of error was plus or minus 4 percentage points for
Democrats and for questions directed at Democrats and Republicans,
the margin of error was 4 percentage points.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Poll Shows Dukakis With Large Lead Among Democrats in Ohio</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachussetts Gov. Michael Dukakis holds
a 2-1 lead over Jesse Jackson in Ohio with one month left before
the state's primary election, according to two recent polls.
   In a mail poll conducted by The Columbus Dispatch, Dukakis was
chosen by 50 percent of the 1,628 Ohio Democrats surveyed who said
they planned to vote in the May 3 primary. Jackson was second with
23 percent.
   The spread was less dramatic in a University of Akron poll
conducted for the Akron Beacon Journal and WCMH-TV in Columbus and
WKYC-TV in Cleveland.
   Dukakis was the choice of 42 percent of the respondents while 22
percent favored Jackson following the March 26 Michigan primary.
The results from both polls were released Sunday.
   Gerald Austin, Jackson's campaign manager and a former political
adviser to Gov. Richard Celeste, told the Akron Beacon Journal
``Ohio is a tough state. But this is April 1. You'll see a
difference May 3.''
   The margin of error in The Dispatch Poll was plus or minus 3
percent on each result.
   The Akron poll has a margin of error of plus or minus 2.75
percent.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Republicans Aim for Bigger Share of Women's Vote in '88</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Indiana's Republicans are taking a new look
at the party's strategy in 1988, with a focus on women.
   ``It's a universal problem for Republicans,'' admits GOP state
Chairman Gordon K. Durnil about the search for support among women
voters. ``We talk about it at (Republican) National Committee
meetings, we talk about it at state committee meetings and we talk
about it with television consultants.
   ``Society has changed and we now have a majority of women in the
work force,'' he said. ``We need to deal with their concerns.''
   The conservative rhetoric that served Indiana's GOP so well in
the early 1980s is giving way to talk of ``family issues'' and of
support for government-sponsored programs to reduce infant
mortality or provide tax breaks for day care.
   ``Women tend to think more than men do that these are the type
of things that should involve some governmental activism,'' Durnil
said.
   Ten years ago, just over half of all voters in Indiana were men,
according to U.S. Census Bureau estimates. Today, more than half
are women.
</TEXT>
