<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--France-Prisoner,0138</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Diplomat Visits Journalist Imprisoned in Afghanistan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A French journalist who was convicted of spying in
Afghanistan and sentenced to 10 years in prison was allowed to meet
with a French diplomat who gave him letters from home, the Foreign
Ministry announced.
   Alain Guillo, a free-lance journalist who regularly worked for
the Sygma photo agency, was captured in March 1987, while reporting
on the fighting between Afghan rebels and Soviet and government
troops.
   He was convicted Jan. 4 and sentenced to 10 years in prison in
Afghanistan for ``espionage and subversive activities.'' He denied
the charges.
   The Foreign Ministry announced Sunday that Charge d'Affaires
Christian Lambert had visited Guillo in an Afghan prison Saturday,
given the prisoner letters and packages from home and determined
that he was in good health.
