<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 0152EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Chad-Meningitis     04-04 0130</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Chad-Meningitis,0135</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>France Sending Military Medical Unit To Combat Meningitis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   France is sending a special military medical team
to Chad to fight an outbreak of spinal meningitis, the Defense
Ministry said.
   The epidemic has hit the N'Djamena region and several areas in
the south of the country during the past three months, the minister
statement said Sunday.
   The team is from the Institute for Tropical Medicine in
Marseille and was to depart for Chad today, the ministry said.
   The team will be carrying 200,000 doses of vaccine, a laboratory
and high-pressure injectors for mass inoculations.
   The team is part of the Rapid Military Humanitarian Intervention
Force. Since 1968, the unit has worked in Biafra, Jordan, Peru,
Nicaragua, the Comoros, Somalia, Chad, Madagascar, Mali and Guinea.
</TEXT>
