<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     04-04 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington In Brief,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FCC Says It's Running Out of Viable Dial-A-Porn Complaints to
Investigate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission has
begun investigating two more California dial-a-porn services, but
the agency says it is running out of complaints it can act on.
   ``I keep beating the bushes for new, specific complaints, but we
just don't have a lot of them,'' though the agency gets plenty of
general complaints about dial-a-porn, said Greg Vogt, chief of the
FCC's telephone enforcement division.
   The FCC sent letters last week to two California adult-message
services, Ramrod Enterprises Inc. of Redding, Calif., and 2001
Enterprises of Reseda, Calif., advising them of ``apparent''
violations. They were given 30 days to respond.
   If violations are found, the FCC could levy fines of up to
$50,000 per day for each day a violation occurred. Neither company
was listed with telephone directory assistance and the FCC said it
was unable to obtain phone numbers for the companies or their
owners.
   For the FCC to investigate possible violations of a federal law
prohibiting transmission of sexually explicit messages to children,
the agency needs information such as a phone bill and a statement
that someone under 18 has reached the service without using a
credit card, an access code or a descrambler, Vogt said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Liberals, Conservatives Unite for Children's Programs That Work,
Save Money</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Liberals and conservatives, often at
loggerheads on social programs, are in rare agreement on expanding
eight children's programs, citing independent research that shows
the programs work well and save the government money.
   A report released this weekend by the House Select Committee on
Children, Youth and Families cites specific costs and benefits of
each program as determined by independent research and analysis.
   The findings have convinced liberals and conservatives that they
can be both compassionate and cost-conscious, said Indiana Rep. Dan
Coates, the senior Republican on the committee.
   ``We're working toward a consensus here,'' Coates said. ``I've
seen a decided change in attitude ... on the Republican side about
how we should approach the process of spending.''
   Whereas there was wholesale ``spare-no-program'' cutting in the
early years of the Reagan presidency, Coates said, members are more
discriminating now and willing to spend money on programs that work.
   The largest child-program increases in the House budget
resolution _ a non-binding spending blueprint _ include $210
million for the compensatory education program for children at
academic risk and $170 million for handicapped education. Other
substantial hikes would go to the Women, Infants and Children
program ($150 million) and Head Start ($77 million).
</TEXT>
