<1ST_LINE>r p PM-KennedyChallenger     04-04 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kennedy Challenger,0384</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Republican Mounts Long-Shot Challenge to Kennedy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WALTHAM, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joe Malone concedes he is letting his
instincts overrule common sense by launching a longshot Republican
challenge to a political institution, Sen. Edward M. Kennedy.
   But Malone, a state Republican Party official, offers few
apologies.
   ``There are some people who are analysts in this world and they
sit down and they look at every single number and different factor
involved in deciding whether they want to run,'' Malone said in an
interview last week. ``But I'm the type of person who moves on
instinct.''
   The former Harvard football player on Tuesday will formally
announce his first bid for political office, a run against the
26-year Senate veteran.
   Malone, 33, has served as executive director of the
Massachusetts Republican Party for the past year, working the
telephones and political functions trying to breathe new life into
a party that claims no statewide offices and is an overwhelming
minority in both chambers of the Legislature.
   Malone has won high praise for loyalty, a trait Democrats and
Republicans alike say brought him into the race against Kennedy at
a time when the state GOP is hard-pressed to find strong
challengers to Democratic incumbents.
   Kennedy has not faced a tough re-election challenge since the
Massachusetts Democrat was first elected to the Senate in 1962 in
his maiden run for office.
   Malone was a field organizer in Massachusetts for Repubublican
presidential candidate John Connally in 1980 and worked on current
state GOP Chairman Ray Shamie's two unsuccessful Senate runs, in
1982 against Kennedy and in 1984 against John Kerry.
   When Shamie ruled out another run against Kennedy, Malone
stepped forward.
   Most state political observers believe Malone's goal is to gain
the name recognition needed for a successful statewide run in 1990,
when the possible departure of Gov. Michael Dukakis from the state
political scene could result in a tumultuous shakeup in state
government.
   The national GOP has pledged $400,000 to Malone, and he hopes to
raise $600,000 on his own. Republicans make no secret of the fact
that they want to force Kennedy to campaign at home to limit the
time he can work for the party's presidential nominee.
</TEXT>
