<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis     04-04 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis To Iacocca: Reconsider Kenosha Plant Closings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential candidate Michael
Dukakis, two days before Wisconsin's primary, is challenging
Chrysler Corp. Chairman Lee Iacocca's planned closing of a Kenosha
plant that would eliminate 5,500 jobs.
   In a letter sent to Iacocca, Dukakis told the automaker
executive he had supported government financial help for Chrysler
in 1979 when the company was struggling.
   ``In fact, I felt so strongly about it that I purchased one of
your automobiles,'' he added. ``I admired what labor and management
did to save and rebuild the company, and I considered you a fair
and concerned employer.
   ``The recent events at the Kenosha plant here in Wisconsin have
changed my mind about your fairness and your concern,'' he wrote.
   ``A good manager does not promise or guarantee some 5,000 people
jobs and then change his or her mind,'' Dukakis wrote. ``Workers
must be treated as partners, not as replacement parts in some
obsolete machine. Communities and the people in them cannot be cast
aside when no longer needed....''
   He asked that Iacocca ``keep your promise to the workers and
community and reconsider your decision to close the Kenosha plant.''
   The letter was released by the campaign staff of the
Massachusetts governor Sunday night _ two days before the Wisconsin
presidential primary election in which Dukakis and Jesse Jackson
are considered the front-runners.
   Will Robinson of the Dukakis campaign staff said the idea for
the letter developed out of a meeting the governor had with local
labor officials in Kenosha Saturday.
   Chrysler announced Jan. 27 it would shut down auto assembly and
metal stamping facilities in Kenosha by Sept. 30. State officials
have contended Chrysler officials promised last year that car
production would continue there for five years.
   Jackson, who has been endorsed by Local 72 of the United Auto
Workers Union _ the local at the Kenosha plant, traveled to Kenosha
to address workers shortly after Chrysler announced the plant would
be shut down in mid-summer.
   Last week, another Democratic presidential candidate, Tennessee
Sen. Albert Gore Jr., ran a television ad that attacked the Kenosha
shutdown by Chrysler.
   That ad prompted Chrysler to issue a statement, released
Thursday by spokeswoman Karen Stewart, saying the public would be
better served by candidates ``addressing real issues such as trade
and the budget deficit rather than exploiting unfortunate
situations like plant closings.''
</TEXT>
