<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ShuttleAstronaut     04-04 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shuttle Astronaut,0498</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shuttle Astronaut Savoring Chance To Finally Fly</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   His mother sometimes wishes he had picked a
different profession, but Jim Bagian has waited seven years to fly
on a space shuttle and he's not about to let the Challenger tragedy
dash his dream.
   ``Commercial airliners crash, too,'' Bagian said. ``That doesn't
stop you from doing things. We want to get going.
   ``One of these days if we keep flying the shuttle, we'll
probably have another accident. That's just life, the way it goes.
You knew the job was dangerous when you took it,'' he said.
   Bagian, 36, a physician and engineer who became an astronaut in
1981, learned two weeks ago that he has been selected for one of
the shuttle crews that hope to put the space program back on its
feet. The program has been grounded since seven astronauts died
when the Challenger exploded as it lifted off from Kennedy Space
Center on Jan. 28, 1986.
   Bagian's mother, Rose, realized her worst fears about her son's
profession during the Challenger disaster.
   ``It brought home that it can happen,'' she said. Still, she
said she knows better than to try to talk her son out of it.
   Karl Scherzberg, a longtime friend from high school and Drexel
University, said he never heard Bagian reconsider his commitment to
the shuttle program. ``I'm sure after the accident he's been
thinking about the reliability of systems and equipment,''
Scherzberg said. ``But there hasn't really been a difference in him
because the accident only confirmed what he knew already about
risk.''
   Bagian said he may have inherited his coolheadedness and love of
aviation from his father, Philip, a World War II fighter pilot.
   Philip Bagian said his son is someone who ``was always at the
top of his class in everything'' and ``may have traded security for
the uniqueness of being an astronaut.''
   Bagian had worked with five of the Challenger crew members. He
also had been assigned to fly on the Challenger in other 1986
missions before all manned U.S. space flights were put on hold.
   If anything, Bagian said the Challenger disaster may have given
him more confidence ``because we've looked at everything again.''
   The accident was blamed on a flawed joint in the side of the
solid rocket booster. The side joints have been redesigned, along
with parts of the rocket booster nozzle.
   Bagian, who is stationed at the Johnson Space Center in Houston,
has been working on the escape system and astronauts' pressure
suits.
   The first of the shuttle flights, on the Discovery, is set for
Aug. 4, followed by an all-military crew flight on the Atlantis on
Oct. 27.
   Bagian's flight, also on the Discovery, is scheduled to launch
Jan. 19. The flight's misson is to release the third in a series of
tracking and data relay satellites for communications.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
