<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880404-0027 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 0347EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Caniff     04-04 0807</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Caniff,0832</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Milton A. Caniff, Creator of `Terry and the Pirates' and `Steve
Canyon'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Milton A. Caniff, who for half a century took
Americans on daring adventures through the comic pages with ``Terry
and the Pirates'' and ``Steve Canyon,'' has died of lung cancer. He
was 81.
   Caniff, who had entered Beth Israel Hospital on Feb. 29, died
Sunday at his home, according to a spokesman for King Features,
which syndicated the strips.
   Caniff set a standard for realistic drawing and quickly
enthralled Depression-era readers with tales of danger in the Far
East in ``Terry and the Pirates,'' which debuted in 1934 in the
Daily News.
   He left the paper to join Marshall Field and the Chicago Sun
Syndicate in 1946 with a new hero, ``Steve Canyon,'' a fictional
Air Force colonel who proved so popular he was eventually given his
own file at the Pentagon.
   Always attuned to what sells newspapers, Caniff liked to quote
his high school art teacher in Dayton, Ohio: ``Unless a piece of
art inspired the viewer to part with cash money to acquire it, then
the drawing was not worth a hoot.''
   But his technique was among the very best, and he was honored as
the ``Rembrandt of comic strips'' at an exhibition at the Museum of
Cartoon Art in 1985. He said he belonged to the ``every wrinkle
must show'' school of art.
   At the Dayton Daily News, Pulitzer Prize-winning cartoonist Mike
Peters described Caniff as ``the grandaddy of cartoonists.''
   ``He was in the inner circle with Rube Goldberg, Al Capp, Walt
Kelly and those guys,'' Peters said. ``He was revered by all of us.
He had some of the best drafted strips ever done.''
   Ted Hannah, a spokesman for King Features, said Caniff continued
to work until very near his death, with his longtime assistant,
Shel Dorf of California. Hannah said a decision on the future of
``Steve Canyon'' would be made this week.
   Caniff's cartooning career began with ``Dickie Dare'' and ``The
Gay Thirties'' for The Associated Press.
   He was soon approached by Capt. Joseph M. Patterson, publisher
of the News, who asked for an adventure strip packed with comedy,
romance and adventure and set in the Orient, which Patterson
regarded as the last outpost of adventure.
   By 1946, ``Terry and the Pirates'' was in more than 300
newspapers and Caniff was making $75,000 per year. But he wanted to
own a cartoon, and he developed ``Steve Canyon,'' for which he was
paid $2,000 a week and owned the rights.
   Despite occasional complaints about violence, ``Steve Canyon''
kept flying and fighting, and early this year it was in more than
500 newspapers around the world, according to King Features.
   Caniff was awarded the Air Force Exceptional Service Award, its
highest civilian honor.
   Caniff was a meticulous researcher, and some of the plots in
``Terry and the Pirates'' anticipated actual events in World War
II, such as the Japanese attack on the United States. One of his
memorable creations was the Dragon Lady, who was inspired by Joan
Crawford.
   When a ``Terry'' character named Raven Sherman was killed in
1941, Caniff received thousands of cards, letters and flowers, and
he recalled that an elevator operator called him a murderer.
   ``Terry and the Pirates'' was continued by George Wunder until
the strip ended in 1973. Wunder died last December.
   Caniff was born Feb. 28, 1907, in Hillsboro, Ohio, and by
kindergarten was drawing recognizable human figures on scrap paper
brought home by his father, a printer.
   His first job was drawing cartoons for the Boy Scout page in the
Dayton Journal Herald when he was 13. He also worked for the
Columbus Dispatch while at Ohio State University, where he earned a
fine arts degree.
   Phlebitis prevented Caniff from joining the military.
   ``It was something I always wanted to do. It was like a small
boy who dreams of catching the game-winning touchdown or rescuing
the heroine from the villain. Fortunately, the strips have allowed
me to have a close association with the military,'' Caniff once
said.
   Many of his strips had touches of autobiography and his Ohio
boyhood, and friends often were prototypes for characters in the
strip. Recently Caniff drew several weeks of strips based on his
courtship of his future wife, Ester Parsons, at Stivers High
School. They were married in 1930.
   He donated most of his original material to Ohio State's Milton
Caniff Library for Communications and Graphic Arts, according to
Walter K. Bunge, director of the university's School of Journalism.
   Caniff received at least three honorary doctorates, including
one from the University of Dayton, and numerous other awards. He
also was a founder of the National Cartoonists Society.
   He is survived by his wife, Ester.
   Funeral services were to be announced by the Frank E. Campbell
funeral home in Manhattan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880404-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 0351EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Nicaragua-Peace     04-04 0765</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua-Peace,0796</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Isolated Hamlets Hope Sandinistas And Contras Achieve Peace</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WIWILI, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Juan Gonzalez passed another bottle of
beer to a waitress, smiled and noted it was a good sign that 15 or
so patrons were getting uproariously drunk in the dimly lit bar of
his shabby riverside inn.
   ``It hasn't been like this,'' Gonzalez said, shaking his head.
``This shows that peace is coming, that we need peace, that the
people believe it will happen. Nowhere has the war had such an
impact.''
   He said residents of this northern village have been rejoicing
since the March 23 signing of the cease-fire agreement between the
Soviet-financed Sandinistas and the U.S.-supplied Contras.
   ``The people have been afraid for years,'' he said, offering a
grin that showed off his two gold-capped front teeth. ``We all got
happy when we heard.'' Gonzalez's rundown guest house, which
doesn't have a name, is located on the banks of the winding Coco
River in the village of Wiwili in Nuevo Segovia, about 150 miles
northeast of Managua.
   The hamlet, located among steep hills parched from the lack of
rain, became a government fortress a few years ago as battles
heated up.
   ``We were well protected,'' Gonzalez said. ``But we couldn't
leave.''
   The village hosts military bases and many government supporters.
Soviet-made cannons and anti-aircraft guns sit atop the hillsides.
East German troop trucks stand ready. Almost all of the men,
civilians and soldiers, tote AK-47 automatic rifles.
   The surrounding mountains, not far from the Honduran border to
the north, have been rife with Contra activity since the rebels
began fighting in 1981 to overthrow the Sandinistas.
   ``No To Communism,'' says graffiti painted on a nearby building.
   The so-called Pantasma Highway, the only route from the south,
was said to be so dangerous that even truck drivers bringing food
and supplies feared to enter. The battered hulks of army troop
trucks mined or ambushed lie along the dirt road.
   To the west, the narrow mountain road from Quilali offered equal
danger of attack. A plaque on the side of the road at one point
listed the names of civilians killed when a mine blew up under
their truck.
   The only other access is by foot, which offers little protection
from ambush, or by the Coco River. But this time of year the water
levels are too low for river travel.
   ``People used to whisper when they had to go to Jinotega (to the
south) or to Quilali,'' Gonzalez said. ``They'd make the sign of
the cross. It was terrible. But just last week I started to see the
difference.''
   The inn owner recalled battles in the outlying hills a few
months ago. He said the bodies of government soldiers would pass
through daily.
   ``I know other parts have suffered, but I can't believe it's as
much as we have,'' he said. ``We can't stand any more.''
   Gonzalez's teen-age son has served eight months of his mandatory
two-year stretch.
   ``He still has more than a year to go,'' Gonzalez signed.
``Maybe if there is peace...''
   But one customer, Ariel Antonio Garcia, said: ``We want peace
but the Contras have to surrender.''
   The 24-year-old recounted how the National Guard that operated
under the late President Anastasio Somoza killed his parents and
how he believed all the Contras were related to the guards.
   The Sandinista revolution ousted Somoza in July 1979. The
Contras, with the backing of the United States, began fighting 1{
years later.
   About 25 miles southeast of Wiwili, a group of Contras roamed
freely last week under the command of a 24-year-old leader.
Comandante Ernesto, as he is known, echoed Garcia's words about the
desire for peace but maintained the Sandinistas should have fully
established democracy.
   The young men served as an example of the deep wounds left from
years of propaganda and battles that have killed or wounded more
than 50,000.
   There have been reports by the Contras that renegades among
their troops have staged attacks in violation of the truce enacted
March 21, at the start of the talks produced the cease-fire
agreement.
   Gonzalez said there were rifle and mortar fire exchanges outside
Wiwili last week. Hours before the official 60-day cease-fire
started Friday, the only sounds along the river were of barking
dogs, crickets and roosters.
   But a little more than an hour after midnight, the sound of an
AK rifle was heard. It came again about a half-hour later.
   ``It was probably just someone who had too much to drink,'' a
resident said the next morning.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
