<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson 1stLd-Writethru a0458 04-04 0769</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0458,780</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS pvs 3rd graf bgng ``Jackson also ...'' to include first
reference to Panama.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Jackson Looks to Turn Crowd Response into Caucus Results</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLORADO SPRINGS, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After evoking emotional responses
from large crowds across much of Colorado, Jesse Jackson is hoping
to ``translate this commitment to massive turnout'' in statewide
caucuses today and Wisconsin's important primary a day later.
   The Democratic presidential hopeful flew back to Milwaukee late
Sunday to resume his Wisconsin campaigning after two days in
Colorado where he drew crowds that numbered in the thousands _ so
large they spilled out of churches, hotel rooms and even an airport
hangar where he spoke.
   Jackson also said he hoped soon to have a full report from a
friend whom he had sent to meet with Panama's military strongman,
Manuel Antonio Noriega. Jackson had sent a message to Noriega last
month calling for him to leave the Central American country.
   Jackson said he was willing to do what he could to encourage
Noriega to leave but that he had not offered to mediate the
dispute. ``That's too strong a word,'' he said.
   He said he had sent a friend, Cirilo McSween of Chicago, who
once lived in Panama, to meet with Noriega. ``I do not have an
official response yet,'' Jackson said.
   Jackson's big crowds came as his campaign reported its biggest
fund-raising success ever _ $2.1 million during March, three times
the amount of his best previous month.
   He capped his Easter weekend campaign with a rally at the
Colorado Springs airport. He was greeted by some 1,500 people
crowded into a large hangar, where some climbed on steel beams
along the walls, children sat on three small planes lining the
rear, and scores more stood outside unable to get in.
   They shrieked when he entered, shouted his name in unison, and
pressed to touch him when he was finished. Jackson seemed touched
by the outpouring.
   ``This excitement in this place today _ and in Greeley, Pueblo
and Aspen yesterday, Denver and now Colorado Springs today _
wherever we go, hope is speaking across our nation,'' Jackson said,
looking at the mix of white, black and Hispanic faces. ``Your
presence is a source of inspiration.''
   Jackson, the black civil rights leader and minister, preached
Easter sermons at a predominantly white Baptist church in Denver.
He invoked the memory of Martin Luther King Jr. on the eve of the
20th anniversary of his death, and used the symbolism of Easter and
the renewal of hope in describing the end of President Reagan's
administration.
   Some 1,500 people jammed inside the church, and another 1,500 to
2,000 were outside. Jackson then was greeted by another 1,000 to
1,500 people inside and outside a jammed Catholic church in a
predominantly Hispanic neighborhood, where people lined the street
for a block. Later, he spoke to 3,000 or more people in Denver
Auditorium Arena, mixing calls for compassion for the poor with
criticism of Reagan.
   A day earlier Jackson had drawn large crowds too, including some
2,000 for an outdoor rally in Pueblo, the same city where rival
Michael Dukakis drew a crowd estimated at 300.
   ``We must translate this commitment to massive turnout at the
caucuses tomorrow night,'' Jackson told the arena crowd.
   Sitting in the congregation for his sermons were former
presidential candidate Gary Hart and his wife Lee, and Denver's
politically embattled Hispanic mayor, Federico Pena.
   Support from Hispanics is considered important in Colorado's
caucuses, as they make up at least 12 percent of the Democratic
vote and their neighborhoods often have high turnouts. Jackson
pursued their vote with his trip to the Our Lady of Guadalupe
Catholic Church.
   Jackson has met strikingly large and emotional crowds since he
campaigned in Michigan a week and a half ago and won there in a
landslide. While he has drawn big crowds in Wisconsin, too, a
weekend Milwaukee Journal poll had him trailing Dukakis by 8
percentage points.
   At each event in Colorado, Jackson displayed a showman's flare
for evoking poignant scenes, even as he spoke in generalities and
avoided specifics. At every stop he picked up babies or toddlers,
and at Denver's arena he gathered scores of young children around
him for cheers and chants.
   He called forward a 102-year-old black woman, Ada March, to
speak to the crowd.
   ``I never thought I'd live to see this day _ when one of our own
would be running for president: Jesse Jackson'' she said. ``It's
wonderful. You never know what will happen to you in life.''
</TEXT>
