<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     04-04 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar And Stocks Down In Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell briefly to a three-month low
against the Japanese yen before recovering slightly today, while
stock prices slipped after moderate gains to close higher in Tokyo
trading.
   The dollar closed at 123.85 yen, down 0.25 yen from Friday's
close of 124.10 yen. The closing figure was up from today's opening
of 123.70 yen, its lowest opening level since Jan. 5 when it
started trading at 123 yen.
   ``There was nothing to motivate the market particularly, though
the market sentiment was not to buy dollars,'' said Hiraki Abe, an
analyst with the Bank of Tokyo. ``With Japanese economic growth in
the past few months, foreign and institutional investors have been
buying a lot in Tokyo, driving the yen higher.''
   Abe said the Bank of Japan was believed to have stepped into the
market to a moderate degree to prop up the dollar, which at one
point fell to 123.45 yen.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which gained 177.90 points during Saturday's
half-day of trading, today gained another 53.17 points, or 0.2
percent, to move to 26,335.29 at the end of the day's trading.
   The market had risen more than 130 yen but fell back shortly
before the end of closing.
   ``Prices were going up, and that made investors wary and move to
the sidelines,'' another analyst at a major Japanese bank said.
   Traders said investors moved aside out of concern over how New
York Stocks might react to a sharp decline for U.S. treasuries in
Tokyo trading.
   Volume on the first section was estimated at 1.1 billion shares,
down from 1.3 billion shares during Friday's session, the last
full-day of trading. An estimated 520 million shares changed hands
during Saturday's morning session.
</TEXT>
