<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0507</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Snow for Pacific Northwest, Flooding in the Midwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Moisture from the Pacific Ocean combined with icy winds to bring
snow to the Cascades of Washington state while some coastal areas
were pelted by sleet.
   Up to a foot of new snow was expected today at the 2,000-foot
level and a heavy snow warning was posted for the Cascades and
Olympic ranges of Washington.
   Meanwhile, severe flooding was expected from southeast Kansas to
northeast Oklahoma along the Neosho River. The river was to crest
about 6 feet above flood stage today, with low-lying areas of
Miami, Okla., expecting damage.
   But after several days of very active weather in the midsection
of the nation, with severe thunderstorms and tornadoes over Indiana
and Michigan on Sunday, few storms were reported this morning.
   Scattered showers and thunderstorms extended from New York
across parts of Pennsylvania and the upper Ohio Valley and the
mid-Atlantic states to the southern Appalachians.
   Clear skies were widespread from the lower Ohio Valley across
the central and lower Mississippi Valley, the central and southern
Plains and the southern Rockies to southern California.
   Temperatures were on the mild side. The East Coast states were
especially mild with early morning readings in the 60s from
southern Pennsylvania to northern Florida.
   The forecast for today called for showers and thunderstorms from
the central Gulf coast region and Florida across the East Coast
states to New England; scattered showers from northern Michigan to
Minnesota; rain and mountain snow from the Pacific Northwest across
Idaho and northern Utah to the northern and central Rockies; and
windy conditions near the Rocky Mountains.
   Highs were expected in the 70s or 80s across much of the nation;
the 40s over Washington state; the 50s or 60s from Oregon and
northern California to the northern and central Rockies; the 50s or
60s from North Dakota across the upper Mississippi Valley and the
Great Lakes region to the north Atlantic states; and the lower 90s
in southwest Texas and the desert southwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 29
degrees at Baker, Ore., to 76 degrees at Key West, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 63 partly cloudy; Boston 51 foggy; Buffalo 54
showers; Charleston, S.C. 67 cloudy; Cincinnati 45 fair; Cleveland
50 fair; Detroit 47 fair; Miami 75 partly cloudy; New York 50
foggy; Philadelphia 63 cloudy; Pittsburgh 56 showers; Portland,
Maine 43 foggy; Washington 65 showers.
   _Central: Bismarck 57 cloudy; Chicago 49 partly cloudy;
Dallas-Fort Worth 61 fair; Denver 52 cloudy; Des Moines 45 fair;
Indianapolis 44 fair; Kansas City 48 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 46
cloudy; Nashville 59 fair; New Orleans 60 foggy; St. Louis 49 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 52 fair; Anchorage 30 cloudy; Las Vegas 62
partly cloudy; Los Angeles 58 fair; Phoenix 69 partly cloudy; Salt
Lake City 51 cloudy; San Diego 60 cloudy; San Francisco 53 windy;
Seattle 39 partly cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 50 rain; Toronto 52 fair.
</TEXT>
