<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Tibet     04-04 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Tibet,0585</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panchen Lama Says More Than 200 Arrested In Tibetan Protest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 200 people were arrested following a
bloody March 5 independence protest in Tibet, but most have been
released, the Panchen Lama, Tibetan Buddhism's No. 2 leader, said
today.
   It was the first time an official figure has been given for the
number of arrests linked to the demonstration, during which
thousands of Tibetans stoned Chinese armed police and burned
vehicles to protest more than 37 years of Chinese Communist rule.
   Foreign reporters have not been allowed into Tibet's capital,
Lhasa, since the protest, but Western travelers there have reported
widespread arrests with estimates ranging up to 1,000.
   The Panchen Lama, speaking at a televised news conference, also
said five people died during the violence, including one policeman,
a Tibetan monk hit by stones, two lay Tibetans shot by police ``in
self-defense,'' and a layman who later died in the hospital of
injuries.
   The Western travelers quoted Tibetans as saying 21 Tibetans and
three Chinese were killed. Official reports mentioned only the dead
policeman, and the Panchen Lama last week told reporters only of
the four immediate deaths.
   The Panchen Lama, second only to the exiled Dalai Lama in the
Tibetan Buddhist hierarchy, supports Chinese rule in Tibet and is
vice-chairman of the Standing Committee of the National People's
Congress, China's legislature.
   Although his account of events March 5 spoke of fewer
protesters, casualties and arrests than the unofficial Western
accounts, it showed larger scale unrest and a heavier crackdown
than the official media.
   He confirmed that several thousand Tibetans took part in the
protest, compared to earlier official accounts of only ``a few
separatists.''
   The Panchen Lama said more than 200 people were detained during
and after the protest for interrogation, and that most had been
released. He did not give specific figures.
   He said only three were formally charged, although he did not
specify what charges.
   ``They will be sentenced according to their crimes and according
to the law,'' he said, speaking in Tibetan in the Great Hall of the
People.
   The Panchen Lama also said several people were detained on
suspicion of involvement in the slaying of the policeman, who was
beaten and pushed from a window.
   The March 5 protest was the fourth against Chinese rule in Lhasa
in five months. On Oct. 1, thousands of Tibetans led by Buddhist
monks stormed and set fire to a police station in Lhasa. At least
14 people died.
   Smaller groups of monks protested Sept. 26 and Oct. 6.
   The government has said more than 80 people were arrested in
connection with the three earlier protests, and 15 remain jailed.
   All the protests have been led by Tibetan Buddhist monks loyal
to the Dalai Lama, who was both religious and civil ruler in Tibet
before the Chinese Communist takeover in 1950. The Dalai Lama fled
to exile in India in 1959 following a failed anti-Chinese uprising.
   China maintains it has held sovereignty over Tibet since the
13th century. Tibetan independence advocates say the remote
Himalayan region enjoyed de facto independence for most of that
time.
   The Panchen Lama, while upholding China's claim to sovereignty,
has called in recent months for greater regional autonomy and an
end to policies under which religion, the center of Tibetan daily
life, was virtually banned during the 1960s and 1970s.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
