<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 0532EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HogHammock     04-04 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hog Hammock,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Simple Life, Marine Research, Co-Exist on Barrier Island</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLIOTT MINOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DARIEN, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On Sapelo Island, one of the least-developed
barrier islands along the Atlantic Coast, residents drive a fleet
of battered old cars with no licenses, tags or insurance _ or
police.
   There's no need for patrolmen because community leaders keep the
peace and resolve disputes; they once banished a man to the
mainland for fighting.
   ``It's kind of a self-disciplining community. They help resolve
their own problems without having a police force,'' said C.V.
Waters, regional supervisor for the state Department of Natural
Resources, which manages the island.
   But the quiet lifestyle that thrives among the stands of oak,
pine and salt marshes may be threatened by a state plan to boost
tourism.
   The resources department plans to buy a 50-passenger tram to
bring tourists from the mainland this summer to see the shabby
remains of an old plantation and learn about the history of the
island and the value of marshes and dunes.
   The department, however, says it will keep visitors away from
Hog Hammock, whose 75 residents live in a cluster of wooden houses
set amid stands of oak, pine and palmettos. Most are descendants of
slaves.
   Sapelo, the fourth-largest of the 12 barrier islands along the
Georgia coast, lies about halfway between South Carolina and
Florida. Ten miles long and nearly three miles wide, its 16,000
acres include 10,600 acres of high ground and 5,400 acres of salt
marsh.
   The state owns the island, except for 434 acres that make up Hog
Hammock. According to legend, Hog Hammock was named for Sampson
Hog, an early resident. A hammock is a piece of elevated ground in
a swampy area.
   The island's 50 other residents either work for the University
of Georgia's Marine Institute, a leader in marine and estuarian
research, or the state resources department.
   Hog Hammock residents prize their simple lifestyle.
   ``It's a beautiful place. It's quiet and peaceful,'' Viola
Johnson said in a recent interview at her back steps, where a group
of stray cats were sunning themselves.
   The average age of island residents is 61, so many are retired.
Most of those who continue to work have island jobs with the
resources department or the university.
   Tourists won't change life on Sapelo Island, said Waters of the
Natural Resources Department.
   ``Most of the time they'll see shore birds, deer and turkey,''
he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
