<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HelicopterUnit     04-04 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Helicopter Unit,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Troops Prepare For Mission To Panama</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT ORD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Only days after some of their fellow
soldiers returned from Honduras, men and women from a combat
aviation brigade prepared to leave for Panama as part of a step-up
in security for Americans there.
   ``I'm looking forward to it,'' said pilot Debra Proffitt, a
23-year-old warrant officer. ``I'm a little excited. It'll be a
good experience and good training.''
   Proffitt and about 200 other members of the brigade from the 7th
Light Infantry Division loaded weapons and supplies onto
helicopters to ready for their deployment, starting today, to the
troubled Central American nation.
   The Pentagon says the soldiers, along with 26 helicopters
including seven armed gunships, are being sent to increase security
for Americans and U.S. facilities in Panama, where Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega continues to resist U.S. pressure for him to step
down.
   On Sunday, a Panamanian military vehicle with its siren blaring
chased the car of U.S. Ambassador Arthur Davis for two miles in an
incident the U.S. Embassy termed ``serious.''
   About 10,000 troops are stationed at the U.S. Southern Command
in Panama, according to the Pentagon.
   The army has said it does not expect the troops heading south to
enter combat, and the soldiers believe the American people support
their mission, in contrast to the recent Honduran deployment, which
sparked widespread protests.
   ``I think it's very appropriate that public opinion is with
us,'' said Lt. Col. Rick Dodge, commander of the unit dubbed ``Task
Force Hawk.''
   The unit is scheduled to fly today from its base outside
Monterey to Travis Air Force Base, 150 miles to the northeast.
Later, it will join about 1,100 other Army soldiers and Marines who
will arrive in Panama from Tuesday through Friday, although no
arrival date has been disclosed for the Fort Ord group.
   Army spokesman Paul Boyce said the troops are taking all the
types of helicopters they normally fly and train with. He called
the action ``a normal troop movement,'' not an emergency deployment
like the recent Honduran mission.
   Dodge said his pilots, ground crews and air crewmen are armed
and prepared for any of a number of missions they have trained for,
including transporting troops, evacuating civilians and other
military operations.
   ``We normally deploy with what we'd go to war with,'' he said.
</TEXT>
