<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SriLanka-Payoffs     04-04 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sri Lanka-Payoffs,0424</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>India Confirms It Paid Money to Tamil Rebel Leader</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Indian government paid Sri Lanka's
top Tamil separatist leader to ensure his cooperation in an accord
intended to end the rebels' war against the dominant Sinhalese, the
Indian ambassador said today.
   Ambassador J.N. Dixit said said Velupillai Prabhakaran, leader
of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, requested the money at
meetings in New Delhi last July.
   Prabhakaran said the money would make up for ``taxes'' that had
been paid to the militia by people in Jaffna, the Tigers' main
stronghold in northern Sri Lanka, Dixit reported.
   ``India agreed to it and some money was paid,'' said Dixit.
   The Tigers since then have rejected the peace accord, signed by
Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi of India and President Junius R.
Jayewardene of Sri Lanka last July 29.
   Indian forces sent to enforce the accord have been fighting the
Tamil rebel militia in the island nation since last October. More
than 400 Indian soldiers and more than 1,000 militiamen have been
reported killed.
   The Indian Post newspaper reported the payments on Sunday, and
Dixit confirmed the story. He said he did not know the amount but
added, ``Enough money was given him to take care of his requests at
that point in time.''
   The Post quoted an unidentified Tiger spokesman as saying the
agreement with India was for $384,600 a month but that no payment
was made after the first month, when the Tigers already were
criticizing the peace accord.
   Gandhi signed the accord after trying for nearly three years to
mediate a peace settlement between the Tamils and the government.
   Dixit said Prabhakaran and Gandhi met in New Delhi before the
signing of the accord. Dixit said Prabhakaran then asked for the
money and for allowing his men to keep some arms to ensure his
security.
   The Tigers did not sign the accord but agreed to give up almost
all their arms. The accord calls for disarming the rebels in
exchange for Sri Lanka granting more autonomy to Tamils.
   The rebels have been fighting since 1983 for a separate Tamil
nation in Sri Lanka's north and east. Tamils, who make up 18
percent of the island's 16 million population, say they suffer
discrimination from the Sinhalese, who control the government.
   Most Tamils are Hindu and most Sinhalese are Buddhists. India, a
majority Hindu nation, became involved at the request of its own
large Tamil minority.
</TEXT>
