<2ND_LINE>PM-Moundsville Escape, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0528,0599</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Convicted Murderers Break Out of Prison</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with prison lockdown, explanation of how
men escaped, some roadblocks being lifted, details on their
records.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOUNDSVILLE, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State police today expanded into Ohio
and Pennsylvania a manhunt for three convicted murderers who
escaped from the maximum-security West Virginia Penitentiary.
   The three inmates were serving life sentences without
possibility for parole and were housed separately in cells in the
same prison wing, said Jerrie Clutter, secretary to Warden Jerry
Hedrick. Two of them had records of escape attempts.
   The inmates were noticed missing during a 10:15 p.m. Sunday cell
check, Clutter said. They were still at large at mid-morning.
   A heavy rain hampered the search effort as state police in West
Virginia, Ohio and Pennsylvania, as well as Marshall County
Sheriff's deputies and local authorities, combed the rural northern
West Virginia countryside for the inmates, Clutter said.
   But authorities this morning started lifting some of the
roadblocks set up throughout Marshall and neighboring counties,
including on bridges over the Ohio River just west of the prison,
and on roads into Pennsylvania, which borders the county to the
east, she said.
   One of the inmates was believed spotted in Yorkville, Ohio,
about 20 miles north of the prison, Clutter said.
   The men apparently slipped out through an unused portion of the
aging prison, said West Virginia Corrections Commissioner A.V.
Dodrill.
   Prison clothing was found in the building, and the outside gate
in front of the wing was cut open, Clutter said.
   ``The old administration building has been closed several years.
We don't use that building, and they somehow got into there, we're
not sure exactly how,'' Dodrill said.
   ``It obviously was well-planned. Therefore we have got to assume
plans were also made for the outside once they got out,'' he said.
   The prison was locked down following the escape, said Deputy
Corrections Commissioner Bill Whyte.
   ``The prisoners are being retained in their cells until such
time as the warden is comfortable that there are no other inmates
involved assisting these prisoners in their escape,'' he said.
   The escapees were identified as Bobby Stacy, 35, David Williams,
28, and Tommie Mollohan, 45, Clutter said. They were considered
dangerous, but were not known to be carrying weapons, Clutter said.
   Stacy, formerly of Columbus, Ohio, was convicted in 1982 for the
murder of Huntington Police Officer Paul Harmon, who was shot five
times with his own service revolver. At the time of the killing,
Stacy was on bond after being charged with shooting a Huber
Heights, Ohio, police officer with a sawed-off shotgun.
   Stacy once vowed to kill a Cabell County Circuit Judge and
prosecutor who handled his case, Huntington police Lt. Joe Walker
said
   Following the escape, a guard was posted at the home of a
Columbus woman who testified against Stacy, police there said.
   Mollohan was convicted of robbing and then killing a Brounland
grocer in 1973. Mollohan at the time had escaped from a Florida
prison and also was wanted in Georgia and North Carolina on armed
robbery charges.
   Williams was convicted of the December 1980 murder of a Marytown
resident, found bludgeoned to death in his burned home. He was
caught trying to scale a prison wall at Moundsville in 1983 after
learning that his mother was seriously ill.
   The massive, stone block penitentiary houses maximum security
inmates and was the site of a bloody New Years' Day 1986 riot in
which three inmates were killed.
</TEXT>
