<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 0914EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-JapaneseDeaths     04-04 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japanese Deaths,0424</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mother Sets House Fire That Kills Self, Two Daughters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Japanese mother and her two young
daughters died in a house fire the woman apparently set because she
was distressed by marital problems, police said.
   The body of Mitsue Sakai, 28, was found early Sunday in a
bedroom along with those of her daughters, Seira Candy Sakai, 5,
and Rina Stephanie Sakai, 4.
   The three are believed to have died from smoke inhalation from
the fire, which was set in the living room, Sgt. Larry Kurtz said.
   ``Based on physical evidence found at the scene and interviews
with witnesses, it is believed the suspect (Mrs. Sakai)
intentionally set fire to the house. She was extremely distraught
over marital and family problems,'' Kurtz said.
   Some friends of the family speculated that the apparent
murder-suicide may be a case of ``oyaku shinju,'' a Japanese
tradition in which parents planning suicide believe they also must
kill their children so they will not be orphans.
   Mrs. Sakai, who moved to the United States from Japan about
eight years ago, and her husband, Hideo, were described by
acquaintances as quiet and hard-working people.
   ``With her husband, they were like ships in the night,'' said
neighbor Barry Rivard. ``They'd kind of pass.''
   Mrs. Sakai worked at the Mitsuyoshi Japanese restaurant in
Anaheim, and her husband is head chef at the Amagi Japanese
restaurant in Buena Park.
   Yoshikazu Suzuki, owner of the Amagi restaurant, said the couple
had met at his restaurant about seven years ago when Mitsue worked
there as a waitress.
   She worked until 10:30 p.m. and Sakai arrived at the home about
2:30 a.m. and was questioned by police, neighbors said.
   ``If she lost hope or something, she cannot let the children
live,'' Suzuki said. ``I know of many cases in Japan like that.''
   An estimated 300 cases of oyako shinju are reported each year in
Japan, authorities said. Although the practice is illegal in Japan,
it's considered an honorable way to die and lingers in the culture,
according to Mamoru Iga, a professor of sociology at California
State University, Northridge.
   The tragedy recalls the case of Fumiko Kimura, a Japanese-born
woman whose two young children died after she walked into the sea
with them at Santa Monica beach in 1985. Her mother-child suicide
attempt was carried out in shame over her husband's adultery. Mrs.
Kimura pleaded guilty to voluntary manslaughter and was placed on
five years' probation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
