<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-EqualVoting     04-04 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Equal Voting,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Will Review NYC Board of Estimate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to decide
whether New York City's powerful Board of Estimate must be
reapportioned to meet equal-voting standards.
   The court said it will hear an appeal by city officials who said
applying the one-person, one-vote rule to the governing body will
undermine its ability to balance regional and local interests.
   The 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals last October said city
officials should set a one-year deadline for revamping the board to
comply with the principle of balanced representation. The appeals
court urged the city to come up with a plan within six months.
   The board was allowed to function with its current composition
in the interim.
   Mayor Edward I. Koch has named a commission to propose changes
in the city charter. Those changes will be put to the voters in a
binding referendum in November.
   The Board of Estimate is composed of the mayor, the city council
president and the city comptroller. Each city-wide official has two
votes on the board.
   In addition, the presidents of the city's five boroughs are
members of the board with one vote apiece.
   The city's population is more than 7 million, with wide
disparities in the size of the boroughs.
   Brooklyn's population is about 2.2 million, Queens 1.9 million,
Manhattan 1.4 million, the Bronx 1.2 million and Staten Island,
350,000.
   The board's responsibilities include determining the use,
development and improvement of city property, negotiating city
contracts, awarding franchises and leasing property, setting water
and sewer rates, zoning decisions and tax abatements.
   An example of the board's power cited by the 2nd Circuit court
is determining whether and where a toxic waste dump can be located
in the city. Other examples range from deciding where skyscrapers
are built and awarding cable television franchises to granting
permits to sidewalk cafes.
   The board also may make changes in the city budget with the
consent of the city council.
   The composition of the board was challenged by three Brooklyn
residents who said their borough is underrepresented. They filed a
lawsuit in 1981 that said the board's make-up violated their
constitutional right to equal representation.
   Richard D. Emery, a lawyer representing them, said the board is
``a vestige of a system of power in New York that benefited the
moneyed interests, the real estate interests.''
   But city officials said the board should be exempt from the
one-person, one-vote standard because it is ``an innovative form of
regional government exercising local powers.''
   They said there is no evidence the board is ``unresponsive to
the popular will or the hostage of a narrow minority of the city's
populace.'' There is ``no evidence of arbitrary whim, or of
gerrymander or of racial mischief'' in the composition, the
officials added.
   They also said most key decisions of the board are reached
through consensus, and that revamping the composition will
undermine home rule.
   But the 2nd Circuit court said the principle of voting
apportionment based on population equality applies to local
elections _ including those for members of the board.
   The current board members beside Koch are city Controller
Harrison J. Goldin, Council President Andrew J. Stein, and borough
presidents Fernando Ferrer of the Bronx, David Dinkins of
Manhattan, Claire Shulman of Queens, Howard Golden of Brooklyn and
Ralph J. Lamberti of Staten Island.
   The case is Board of Estimate vs. Morris, 87-1022.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880404-0051 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 0934EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Birds     04-04 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Birds,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Rejects Appeal by Alaska Natives on Bird-Hunting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today rejected an appeal by
Alaska natives who want to hunt migratory birds in the spring and
summer.
   The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that treaties
between the United States and other nations generally ban the
hunting between March 10 and Sept. 1.
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals last October ruled in
favor of conservationists who challenged the right of the Alaska
natives to kill migratory waterfowl for food during the offseason.
   The appeals court said the federal Migratory Bird Treaty Act of
1918 limits hunting of the birds to those periods approved in
related treaties between the United States and other nations.
   The government has entered treaties with Canada, Mexico, Japan
and the Soviet Union.
   The Canada treaty imposes the strictest limits, essentially
permitting hunting only from Sept. 1 to Dec. 15.
   The Alaska natives, particularly Eskimos living near the
Yukon-Kuskokwim Delta, say the birds are an important part of their
diet.
   A sharp decline in the population of Cackling Canada Geese,
White Fronted Geese, Pacific Black Brant and Emperor Geese has
caused conservationists to be concerned about their survival.
   The birds nest and raise their young in the delta during the
spring and summer months and then migrate south in early September.
   The Alaska natives said a 1925 federal law authorizes them to
hunt the birds when needed for food, superseding the earlier
Migratory Bird Treaty Act.
   But the 9th Circuit court said the earlier law still governs the
hunting season. Generally, the season may be extended only if
treaties related to the act are amended to relax the restrictions,
the appeals court said.
   However, the appeals court stopped short of banning all
off-season hunting of the waterfowl. Instead, it ordered a federal
judge to conduct further study to determine whether agreements
between the Alaska natives and the U.S. Wildlife Service violate
the treaty act.
   The most recent agreement, called the 1985 Goose Management
Plan, limits hunting of the birds for food but does not prohibit it
entirely.
   The Reagan administration supported the 9th Circuit court ruling.
   The appeal acted on today was filed by lawyers for the Alaska
natives.
   The case is Alaska Federation of Natives vs. Alaska Fish and
Wildlife Federation, 87-1157.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880404-0052 </DOCNO>
