<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MormonConference     04-04 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mormon Conference,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mormon Leaders Expound Basic Doctrines Of Resurrection, Atonement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mormon Church leaders say followers should
examine their lives and consider whether they are following the
basic tenets of their faith.
   The challenge to renew their dedication to the teachings of
Jesus was issued to members Sunday at the close of the 158th Annual
General Session of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints.
   ``While we still feel the spirit of this great conference and
the words ring in our ears, let us determine how each of us can be
doers of the word and not hearers only,'' said church President
Ezra Taft Benson in a sermon that was read by an associate.
   Benson, 88, attended the conference's closing session, but asked
Gordon B. Hinckley, a counselor in the governing First Presidency,
to read the sermon.
   Benson, who suffered a heart attack last year and delivered two
addresses on Saturday, said he was too tired to speak Sunday, a
church spokesman said.
   With the closing day falling on Easter Sunday, sermons focused
on the divinity of Jesus Christ and the promise that his
resurrection and atonement offer eternal life to all who accept him
and adhere to the church's teachings.
   Mormons believe that theirs is the one true church, and that
church leaders receive revelations from Jesus. In his sermon,
Benson said conference messages are as important as scripture
because they contain communications from God.
   More than 6,000 church members attended the proceedings in the
Tabernacle on Temple Square, and thousands more watched by live
satellite transmission in nearly 2,000 meetinghouses throughout the
United States, Canada and Puerto Rico.
   The church was founded by Joseph Smith, a 19th century religious
figure who said he found gold plates near Palmyra, N.Y., that
described a visit to America by Jesus after the crucifixion and
contained the true word of God. He wrote what he said was a
translation of the plates, which were returned to the heavenly
messenger who led Smith to them.
   On Saturday, leaders announced that a record 227,284 converts
joined the church during 1987, bringing total membership to 6.5
million.
</TEXT>
