<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BoudoirBrouhaha     04-04 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Boudoir Brouhaha,0284</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Photographer Ordered to Not Display `Boudoir' Photos of
Chancellor's Wife</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has ordered a photographer to
stop showing potential customers ``boudoir'' photos that a college
chancellor's wife had made as a sexy Christmas gift for her husband.
   The order issued Friday put an end to photographer Ray
Westbrook's use of the photographs of Tricia Kellerman, one a
semi-nude picture, in a display in his studio's ``boudoir'' sample
album.
   Mrs. Kellerman, wife of James Kellerman, chancellor of the North
Orange County Community College District, learned last month from
the wife of a college district employee that someone had seen the
pictures.
   Kellerman went to the studio that same day and pulled the
photographs out of the sample book. Westbrook called the police and
accused Kellerman of stealing the pictures. The police dropped the
case but the Kellermans didn't.
   They filed a lawsuit claiming their privacy had been violated.
   ``These photographs have cost me far more than money. ... I have
never felt so embarrassed and humiliated,'' Mrs. Kellerman said in
a sworn statement filed in Orange County Superior Court. ``I have
been on an emotional roller coaster.''
   Westbrook countered in his defense Thursday that he had a
witness who could say that Mrs. Kellerman had given him verbal
permission to display the pictures. The photographer said it was
necessary to display such pictures in order to get work.
   He also said he would have destroyed the photos if the
Kellermans had called him to convey their concern.
   Westbrook said Friday he had cut up the disputed pictures and
given them to his attorney. ``They basically don't exist,'' he said.
</TEXT>
