<2ND_LINE>PM-Plane Crashes, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0512,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nine Die in Four Plane Crashes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 9th graf, `Also killed ...,' to insert that father was
plane's pilot. Also subs 11th graf, `In Orinda ...,' to CORRECT
title of Dasher.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Small plane crashes in California and Colorado left nine people
dead over the weekend, while two died when a glider slammed into a
mountain.
   A single-engine Beechcraft Bonanza crashed in flames after
taking off Sunday from the Colorado Springs Municipal Airport,
narrowly missing homes in the area, officials said.
   The crash killed three members of a Cedar Rapids, Iowa, family
returning from a ski trip, as well as an 18-year-old family friend.
   Andrew Richard Andrews, 20, emerged from the wreckage in flames,
unaware that his parents and the classmate were dead. He was
critically burned and later died.
   ``He never lost consciousness,'' said paramedic Faye McElroy.
``He said, `What happened?' I said, `You were in a plane crash.' He
said, `Oh, my God, my family.'''
   Andrews remained conscious until after he arrived at the burn
treatment center at Penrose Hospital, but he died at 12:35 a.m.
today, nursing supervisor Lee Shreffler said.
   ``I put him out. He was totally on fire,'' said Russell Shaw, 20.
   ``I told him to roll on the pavement and that didn't work. I
told him to roll in the grass and that didn't work,'' Shaw said.
``I put him out with my shirt. He told us there were three others
in the plane.''
   Also killed were the young man's father, Merle Robert Andrews,
49, the plane's pilot; his mother, Roberta Ann, 48; and Jamie
Harter, 18, all of Cedar Rapids, said El Paso County Deputy Coroner
Michael Stewart.
   West of Boulder, Colo., authorities on Sunday found the bodies
of two people who died Saturday when a glider crashed into the
mountains. The wreckage was found some distance away, authorities
said. The two were identified as James Lesley Clayton, 30, of
Boulder, the pilot; and Loren M. Swisher, 40, of Green River, Wyo.
   In Orinda, Calif., four people died Sunday after a twin-engine
Piper Navajo slammed into a hillside about 15 miles east of San
Francisco. There were no survivors, police chief John Dasher said.
The victims' names were withheld.
   In Calpella, Calif., about 120 miles north of San Francisco, the
pilot of a single-engine Piper died Sunday when the aircraft
crashed in a Mendocino County vineyard after takeoff. The victim,
who was alone, was not immediately identified, said sheriff's Lt.
James Tuso, the chief deputy coroner.
</TEXT>
