<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Ireland 2ndLd-Writethru a0492 04-04 0844</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ireland, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0492,0865</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protestants March In Northern Ireland</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede BELFAST</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to update on today's marches. Picks up 4th
graf pvs ``Austin Currie...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANBRIDGE, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Protestant
marchers waving British flags marched across Northern Ireland today
to commemorate Protestant resistance to the 1689 siege of
Londonderry ordered by Catholic King James II.
   The marches, of which there were at least six, were peaceful, as
were the dozen marches by Roman Catholics on Sunday commemorating
the 1916 Easter Rising against British rule in what is now the
Irish Republic.
   The largest Protestant march took place in Banbridge, about 25
miles south of Belfast, where about 40 fife-and-drum bands and 60
local clubs of the Apprentice Boys of Derry paraded.
   The marchers _ some wearing bowler hats, pin-striped suits and
carrying furled umbrellas, others sporting the red, white and blue
of the British flag _ filled the normally quiet streets with a
mixture of British marching songs and old favorites like ``Waltzing
Matilda'' and ``Johnny Comes Marching Home.''
   Smaller parades were held in Belfast, Rathfriland, Gilford,
Dromara and Castlederg.
   The fiercely pro-British Apprentice Boys order takes its name
from 12 apprentices who are said to have slammed Londonderry's
gates on King James' army at the start of the unsuccessful 105-day
siege.
   During the main address of the Banbridge parade, the Rev. Hugh
Ross denounced the 1985 Anglo-Irish agreement giving the Irish
Republic a consultative role in the affairs of Northern Ireland. He
called for the independence of the province from both Britain and
the republic.
   ``We must take the initiative and support a policy that will
establish Ulster as a free independent state ... which will forever
reject a united Ireland,'' the Presbyterian minister said.
   On Sunday, the Irish Republican Army dashed any hopes of a
cease-fire, vowing to continue guerrilla attacks on British
security forces until it ``saps the political will of the British
government.'' The IRA statement was read aloud in Belfast at
Milltown Cemetery.
   Austin Currie, a prominent leader of the Social Democratic and
Labor Party, expressed hope Sunday that talks between his moderate
Catholic party and Sinn Fein, the legal political wing of the
outlawed IRA, would lead to ``a permanent end of military and
violent activity.''
   In an Irish Radio interview, Currie said draft documents were
exchanged at the March 23 Sinn Fein-Social Democratic and Labor
Party meeting which could lead to a round-table conference that
would also include Protestant parties and the Irish government.
   But Martin McGuinness, vice president of Sinn Fein, the IRA's
legal political arm, told a 5,000-strong crowd at Milltown Cemetery
that cease-fires weren't even discussed at the talks.
   ``The IRA position on cease-fires has been on record for a long
time: No more cease-fires,'' he said, ``talk (can) take place but
the war will go on.''
   Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams told 1,500 people at a march in
Londonderry that the talks with the Social Democratic and Labor
Party ``are about exploring whether there can be an agreement in
principle to an overall strategy for justice and peace.''
   However, he said the two parties were far apart.
   Adams and McGuinness said they strongly opposed any solution to
the nearly 20 years of sectarian strife in Northern Ireland based
on self-government for the province. The only solution, they
insisted, is for Britain to pull out of the province, where
Protestants outnumber Catholics by 3-to-2.
   If Britain refuses to leave, the IRA statement read by
McGuinness said, it will have ``a price to pay ... a price so
overwhelming as to force them to withdraw and leave us in
peace....''
   The IRA said it had a message for the British government:
   ``We will demoralize you. We will make your six counties (of
Northern Ireland) into a millstone which will strangle you.
   ``We will eventually defeat you. Our strategy is clear. It is to
sap the political will of the British government and British people
to remain in Ireland. The means are by limited guerrilla warfare
against crown forces.''
   In the Creggan area of Londonderry, security forces on Sunday
defused a bomb that the IRA said in a statement to Belfast media it
planted but decided not to detonate when an army patrol passed
because children were in the area.
   There was a heavy police and army presence at all the marches as
security forces abandoned their short-lived policy of staying away
from events attended by IRA sympathizers.
   The Sinn Fein march through west Belfast was led and tailed by
armored police Land Rovers with soldiers riding shotgun, their
rifles cocked. Police followed the marchers into Milltown Cemetery
and encircled them, with a number of soldiers hiding behind
tombstones.
   The Milltown ceremony took place 25 yards from the spot where a
Protestant extremist killed three people at an unpoliced IRA
funeral on March 16.
   The no-policing policy ended after two British soldiers who
drove into an IRA funeral on March 19 were dragged from their car
and killed by the IRA.
</TEXT>
