<HEAD>Lightning Knocks Out Skyway Bridge Warning System</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lightning damaged the Sunshine
Skyway Bridge's motorist warning system just days before it was to
begin operating, a state transportation official said.
   The $2.2 million network of blinking lights and flashing message
boards is designed to warn motorists of emergencies on the bridge.
   Lightning hit two closed-circuit television cameras and a
transformer during a heavy storm last week, Doug Moore, district
construction engineer for the Department of Transportation, said.
The lightning melted the cameras and caused some of the system's
circuits to overload.
   Transportation officials had hoped to activate the system by
this Friday, but officials have given the contractor a further 45
days to make repairs, Moore said.
   The 432-foot high bridge is a replacement of the old Sunshine
Skyway Bridge, which lost a 1,300-foot section when it was struck
by a ship during a squall in 1980. The disaster killed 39 people
whose vehicles fell into Tampa Bay.
</TEXT>
