<HEAD>Dodge Heir Begins Jail Term For Probation Violations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Auto heir John Dodge, who began a
one-year prison sentence for violating his probation on drug
charges this weekend, says he doesn't consider himself a criminal.
   Dodge turned himself in to the Palm Beach County Jail late
Friday just before the court-ordered deadline.
   The 34-year-old Palm Beach man said prison ``is something I have
to go through and I choose to look at it positively.''
   The youngest grandson of auto tycoon Horace Dodge Sr. was first
arrested in March 1985 and charged with 10 counts of forging
prescriptions to buy Dilaudid, a synthetic drug similar to heroin.
   He was placed on probation but was arrested again in September
1986 after police watched him take drugs from a safe-deposit box he
shared with his pharmacist girlfriend.
   In January, a judge sentenced Dodge to one year in prison but
postponed the sentence until April 1 so Dodge could attend custody
hearings over his 6-year-old son, John Dodge Jr.
   On March 23, Dodge agreed to give up custody of his son.
   Dodge could be out in five months, possibly earlier, if he
qualifies for a work-release program.
