<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 1009EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Hospitals     04-04 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Hospitals,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Reinforces Hospital Right to Challenge Medicare Regulations
in Ohio Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today reinforced the right
of hospitals to challenge federal regulations limiting the amount
of money they are reimbursed for treating Medicare patients.
   Justice Anthony M. Kennedy wrote the unanimous opinion, his
first since joining the court Feb. 18.
   Kennedy, in a case from Ohio, upheld the right of hospitals to
contest unfavorable rules to a governmental agency called the
Provider Reimbursement Review Board.
   The board must hear the hospitals' challenge to regulations even
if the hospitals previously abided by the rules in their own cost
reports, Kennedy said.
   He said the board's required review of such challenges assures
that Medicare providers will then have the right to take their case
to federal court if the board rules against them.
   ``By objecting to the regulation in the first instance in
proceedings before the board, the (hospitals) protected their right
to judicial review,'' Kennedy said. The board's decision on
reimbursement ``triggers the right of judicial review'' for the
hospitals, he said.
   The regulation challenged by the hospitals limited their
reimbursement for malpractice insurance premiums.
   The hospitals filed cost reports for 1980 with what is known as
a ``fiscal intermediary'' _ normally a private insurance company _
that accepted the government's limitations on malpractice
reimbursement.
   The hospitals then appealed to the Provider Reimbursement Review
Board for more money. But the board said it lacked authority to
review the case because the hospitals had not challenged the
regulation before the fiscal intermediary.
   The 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled that the board acted
properly.
   Kennedy said today that the appeals court ruling could deny the
hospitals the right to a federal court hearing when they challenged
governmental regulations.
   Today's decision was a victory for the Bethesda Hospital
Association in Ohio and the Deaconess Hospital Association of
Cincinnati.
   The Department of Health and Human Services since has revised
the formula to allow hospitals more money for malpractice costs.
   The case is Bethesda Hospital Association vs. Bowen, 86-1764.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880404-0063 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 1012EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Lebanon-Hostages     04-04 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Hostages,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Magazine Says Iran Wants Cleric Deported In Return for French
Hostages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran said it would help release French
hostages in Lebanon if France deports a Shiite Moslem cleric who
opposes Iranian leader Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, Ash-Shiraa
magazine reported.
   The cleric, Ayatollah Mahdi Rouhani, said in Paris on Saturday
he was unaware of any such demands by Iran, but said he was ready
to go if necessary.
   Shiite militants loyal to Iran are believed to hold most of the
22 foreign hostages in Lebanon, including nine Americans and at
least three Frenchmen.
   Ash-Shiraa, the same weekly that disclosed U.S. arms sales to
Iran in 1986, said Saturday that negotiations between Paris and
Tehran for the release of French hostages ``have made big
progress'' and that France likely would deport Rouhani.
   In Paris, Rouhani, the leader of Shiites in Europe, said: ``I am
ready to leave before they ask me. It is my duty as a human being.''
   Rouhani, an Iranian, said he has lived in France for the past 25
years. He said he opposes Khomeini but supports the Islamic
Republic.
   Omran Adham, a French businessman of Syrian descent who has
worked to free French hostages, arrived Saturday in Beirut from
Paris, said Beirut airport officials who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   The French Embassy in Beirut declined comment and it could not
be determined whether Adham had come to the Lebanese capital to
seek the release of hostages.
   In London, the Daily Mail, quoting unidentified French
intelligence sources, reported today that Iran and France are close
to sealing a deal to release the foreign hostages.
   The newspaper said Iran is demanding that France deport Rouhani
and ousted Iranian president Abolhassan Bani-Sadr in return. It
quoted the sources as saying both men agreed to leave France.
   The French hostages are diplomats Marcel Carton and Marcel
Fontaine and journalist Jean-Paul Kauffman. Moslem militants
claimed in March 1985 that they killed a fourth French hostage,
researcher Michel Seurat, but no body has been found.
   The longest held hostage is American Terry Anderson, chief
Middle East correspondent for The Associated Press. He was
kidnapped March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
