<HEAD>Brother Of Lansing Murder Suspect Found Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The brother of a man accused of killing a
police officer was found stabbed to death in the home they once
shared, authorities said today.
   An autopsy was to be performed today on the body of Peter
Laboda, 57, which was found by relatives in the family's home
Sunday afternoon, said Ingham County Prosecutor Donald Martin.
   ``This is not a suicide. This appears to be a homicide. There
appears to be evidence of a break-in. The body may have been there
as long as early Friday,'' Martin said.
   Authorities said they didn't have any suspects in the death of
Laboda, a local renting agent and firewood supplier.
   In February, Lansing Parks Police Officer Julie Englehardt was
gunned down outside the Laboda home. Peter's brother John, 46, is
accused in that slaying.
   ``To have two homicides at the same address is rather bizarre to
say the least,'' Martin said.
   John Laboda is in Ingham County Jail pending psychiatric tests
and court hearings. The brothers had lived with their sister at the
home.
