<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Poison     04-04 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Poison,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poisoned Chocolates Found Near Playground</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A passer-by found three pieces of poisoned
chocolate near a shrine and playground, but police said today that
no one was hurt in the latest of a series of poisoned candy
incidents since September.
   ``A poison reaction was detected'' in police checks on three
individually wrapped pieces of chocolate found Sunday in the grassy
compound of a shrine in Itano, in Tokushima Prefecture about 320
miles southwest of Tokyo, said Tokushima Prefectural Police
spokesman Sumio Okuyama.
   He said a passer-by found the chocolates and called police. A
section of the shrine compound is used as a playground, Okuyama
said.
   He did not say what poison was in the candies and said police
would not disclose who had manufactured them.
   Police suspect the same group or same person was responsible for
a string of incidents in which poisoned chocolates were left on the
ground near a playground and schools, he said.
   Okuyama said on March 24, police found 21 chocolates tainted
with potassium cyanide in the compound of a kindergarten in a town
near Itano.
   He said poisoned chocolates were discovered in two kindergartens
in neighboring Kagawa Prefecture last Sept. 8, and similar
incidents were reported that month in at least three other
Tokushima schools.
   Okuyama would not confirm a news report that a threatening
letter was sent last month to Lotte Co., a candy maker based in
Tokyo, demanding $320,000.
   In 1984, a group calling itself the ``Man With 21 Faces''
planted poisoned candy on store shelves in a bid to extort money
from the manufacturers. No one was reported hurt.
   The group also kidnapped Katsuhisa Ezaki, president of the
confectionery firm Ezaki Glico, and demanded a ransom of $4 million
and 220 pounds of gold.
   Ezaki escaped unharmed three days later. But a series of
extortion threats against Ezaki Glico and at least 30 other food
companies ensued, including a demand for $800,000 from Glico's
rival, Morinaga and Co.
   ``The Man With 21 Faces'' apparently stopped planting poisoned
candy about two years ago, although police insist no payoffs were
made. There were no arrests.
   Another police official of Tokushima Prefecture who spoke on
condition of anonymity said investigators did not know if the
latest plantings of poisoned candy were connected to the 1984
incidents.
</TEXT>
