<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 1039EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-FLRA     04-04 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-FLRA,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Gives Federal Agencies More Leeway in Dealing with Labor
Unions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today gave federal agencies
more leeway in dealing with labor unions representing their
employees.
   The justices, in a unanimous and unsigned opinion, said a
federal employer's rules or regulations may not be challenged as
unfair labor practices until found to have been imposed without any
``compelling need.''
   The decision whittles the power of the Federal Labor Relations
Authority, the agency created to handle disputes between federal
employers and unionized employees, in such circumstances.
   The case stems from a decision by the Army in 1981 to shut down
operations at the Aberdeen Proving Ground for three days after
Thanksgiving to conserve energy.
   Workers there were required to claim the time off as vacation
days that they might have preferred to use some other time.
   The International Association of Machinists and Aerospace
Workers accused the Army of an unfair labor practice for refusing
to bargain over the decision.
   The FLRA ruled that the Army failed to prove there was ``a
compelling need'' for its vacation-days rule and ordered the Army
to negotiate with the union.
   But the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals overturned the FLRA
ruling, stating that the burden is on the FLRA to show there is no
compelling need for a government agency's rules before it orders
agency bargaining with a union.
   Another federal appeals court had upheld the FLRA in a similar
case, and today's decision upholding the 4th Circuit court's ruling
resolves the conflict in a way unfavorable to the authority.
   The justices said federal law clearly states ``that where a
matter is covered by regulation, no duty to bargain arises until
the (FLRA) has first determined that no compelling need justifies
adherence to the regulation.''
   The court said the ``compelling need'' finding by the FLRA
cannot be combined with an unfair labor practices proceeding.
   The case is FLRA vs. Aberdeen Proving Ground, 86-1715.
</TEXT>
