<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ColemanRetrial     04-04 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Coleman Retrial,0379</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Selection Begins in Coleman Retrial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DECATUR, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jury selection began today for the murder
retrial of a man once sentenced to death for the slayings of six
members of a farm family 15 years ago.
   A federal appeals court in 1985 threw out death sentences
against Wayne Carl Coleman, his half-brother Carl Isaacs and George
Dungee and ordered new trials.
   A barrage of pretrial publicity in the rural, southwest Georgia
county of Seminole, site of the 1973 killings of the Alday family,
made a fair trial there impossible, the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals ruled.
   Isaacs, accused mastermind of one of the state's most notorious
killing sprees, was convicted again in a retrial in January in
Perry, a small town 30 miles south of Macon, and given a new death
sentence.
   Coleman is being retried in DeKalb County Superior Court in this
Atlanta suburb and Dungee will be retried later this year in
Columbus. Prosecuting attorney Charles Ferguson has said he will
seek the death penalty for them also.
   A DeKalb County jury last month ruled Coleman, now 41, competent
to stand trial, despite his attorneys' contention that the last 15
years behind bars have rendered him in need of mental treatment.
   Superior Court Judge Hugh Lawson of Hawkinsville, who is
presiding over all three retrials, last month refused to approve
public funds to hire an expert to help defense attorneys during
jury selection. He also rejected defense motions to prohibit
prosecutors from using Coleman's lack of remorse against him in a
sentencing trial, if he is convicted.
   A confession by Coleman was presented as evidence in the first
trial.
   The three defendants, escapees from a Maryland prison farm, were
convicted in 1973 for the deaths of Ned Alday, 62; his brother
Aubrey, 57; Ned's sons, Jerry, 35, Chester, 30, and Jimmy, 25; and
Jerry's wife Mary, 26.
   Five of the six were shot to death as they arrived at Jerry
Alday's rural mobile home on May 14, 1973, as Isaacs and his
companions were burglarizing it, according to previous trial
testimony. Mary Alday was taken to a wooded area, raped and shot to
death.
</TEXT>
