<HEAD>Parent Sues For Better Biology Course For Daughter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WELLESLEY, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman is suing the city school system
in an effort to see that her daughter gets a full education, in
spite of her allergies to chemicals that would be found in a
biology class.
   Her mother, Mary Ann Hickey, wants a closed circuit television
monitor so her daughter Laura can take the science class without
leaving home. The town cable antenna company has offered to install
it free.
   The school system has offered a correspondence course instead.
   Laura tried the alternative course, but withdrew after six weeks.
   ``The correspondence course may have given my daughter the same
credit, but not the same education,'' said Mrs. Hickey. ``There
were no lab experiments, no lectures and no teacher interaction.
That's not an equal education.''
   No date has been set for a court hearing. Last week, a hearing
officer for the Massachusetts Board of Education, Lindsay Byrne,
ruled for Wellesley High School in the dispute.
