<HEAD>Strike By 505,000 Teachers Enters Fourth Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nationwide strike over wages by
505,000 public school teachers entered its fourth week Monday,
affecting 7.2 million students aged 3 to 18.
   Primary and secondary school teachers in every province except
northeastern Corrientes have been on strike since the school year
began March 14, demanding a minimum salary of about $117 a month.
Corrientes' teachers reached a separate accord in March.
   The government in this economically pressed nation has admitted
that teachers' salaries are low but says it cannot afford to pay
more than $85 a month.
   The teachers' union has rejected the offer as insufficient,
saying many teachers are forced to work a second job because some
instructors in the poorer provinces outside Buenos Aires are paid
as little as $54 a month.
   Most private schools have been unaffected by the strike.
</TEXT>
