<HEAD>Marchers Pledge To Carry On Dreams of Slain Leaders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERICA JOHNSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUMBERTON, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 600 people, mostly Lumbee Indians,
rallied today at a recreation center where slain Indian leader
Julian Pierce recently kicked off his campaign for a state
judgeship.
   The marchers carried signs reading ``Gov. Martin: We need that
special session'' and marched quietly down several city blocks,
singing ``Amazing Grace'' and ``We Shall Not Be Moved.''
   Pierce, a Lumbee, was shot to death at his home on March 26 in
what authorities said was a domestic dispute.
   Several elected and religious leaders from across the state
attended the rally, which was not endorsed by local officials.
   The seat Pierce was seeking was created by the General Assembly
to improve the chances of minorities in superior court elections in
racially troubled Robeson County. Blacks and I8
percent of Rondians make up 5beson County's population.
   The lone candidate remaining in the race, white District
Attorney Joe Freeman Britt, will be declared the winner of the
judgeship without special action by the Legislature to allow
another candidate.
   ``Julian Pierce and (the late Lumbee leader) John Godwin are not
dead,'' said Judy Brooks, a white woman who is married to a Lumbee.
``They live on together in our hearts, and we're going to continue
their struggle.''
   Godwin, a found a cause.''
   Besides Michaux, state Rep. Sidney Locks, who represents Robeson
County, and Dan Bell, a Democratic candidate for secretary of
state, attended the rally.
   Presidential candidate Jesse Jackson sent the group a telegram
urging Robeson County citizens to ``keep up the fight.''
