<HEAD>Police Raid Red Light District For Second Time in a Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police swooped down on bars in
Manila's notorious Ermita district Monday night and hauled away
dancing girls, bartenders and scores of foreign patrons.
   It was the second raid on the city's red light district in a
week as part of a drive by Manila Police Chief Brig. Gen. Alfredo
Lim to clean up what was once the capital's most fashionable
neighborhood.
   Police refused to say how many clubs had been raided or how many
people had been taken into custody because the operation was
continuing. One policeman said they were concentrating on clubs
believed owned by foreigners.
   One French tourist, who refused to give his name, said police
asked foreign patrons to produce passports and visas.
   On March 28, police raided dozens of nightclubs in Ermita and
rounded up more than 1,000 dancers and ``hospitality girls.''
Police released those who could produce work permits following
medical examinations, and officials later said about a third of the
women were suffering from venereal disease.
   The crackdown followed a proposal by Lim to phase out bars and
nightclubs, which he said were fronts for prostitution. Bar owners
protested that their businesses pumped millions of dollars into the
country's laggard economy.
