<1ST_LINE>u i PM-India-USFire 2ndLd-Writethru   04-04 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-US Fire, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0570,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire Damages American Cultural Center</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: INSERTS graf after 6th pvs, `About 150...' to UPDATE with
damage estimate. Pick up 7th pvs, `The building...' DELETES
outdated 9th pvs, `The extent...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sparks from workmen's torches started a
fire at the American cultural center today, damaging the building
but causing no injuries, U.S. and fire officials said.
   The fire was an accident that had ``absolutely no connection''
with the visit of Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci, said Douglas
Rose, deputy director of the U.S. Information Service in New Delhi.
   Carlucci arrived in New Delhi today and held two rounds of talks
with Indian officials on defense cooperation and the peace process
in Afghanistan.
   The fire began on the fifth floor, the building's top story, at
about 3:45 p.m. after sparks ignited flammable gas canisters stored
there, said S.K. Dheri, the city's chief fire officer.
   He said the sparks came from men repairing or cutting an
air-conditioning duct with acetylene torches.
   About 150 firefighters battled the blaze for an hour at the
American Center, which houses U.S. Information Service offices, a
library, theater, meeting rooms and a media center, Dheri said. The
computer center on the fifth floor was safe, he said.
   Damage was estimated at between $100,000 and $300,000, said
State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley in Washington. Rose
said the damage was largely confined to the air-conditioning room.
   The building is on a main street close to the central Connaught
Circle shopping arcade. The street was closed to traffic.
   Four cooking gas and oxy-acetylene cylinders stored on the fifth
floor exploded in the fire, Dheri said. Firefighters wore gas masks
when they entered the building.
   James McGinley, director of the U.S. Information Service in New
Delhi, said the building was evacuated within five minutes.
   ``The important thing is that everyone is safe,'' he said.
</TEXT>
