<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 1156EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Afghanistan     04-04 0636</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Afghanistan,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Preparing To Withdraw Some Afghan Troops, But No Timetable
Set</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviets have begun preparations to remove
the first of their 115,000 soldiers from Afghanistan although no
date has been set for the withdrawal and U.N. peace talks are at an
impasse, administration sources say.
   The Soviet foreign minister, Eduard A. Shevardnadze, made an
unexpected trip to Kabul on Sunday to discuss ``serious
difficulties'' caused by the U.S. and Pakistani demands that Moscow
halt aid to the Afghan government at the same Washington stops the
flow of covert arms to guerrilla forces.
   Shevardnadze has said the Soviets will withdraw even if the
talks collapse.
   And a U.S. government analyst said ``the intelligence community
is unanimous in reporting that preparations for a withdrawal have
commenced.''
   But the analyst, speaking on condition of anonymity, stressed
that the exact time, duration and manner of the Soviet withdrawal
remained unclear.
   Shevardnadze, in an interview with the official Tass news
agency, said he was going to Kabul ``to discuss and coordinate with
the Afghan leadership the various options for action, in all their
aspects, in the event that the Geneva process fails to bring about
the desired results.''
   U.S. sources declined to provide details about Soviet
preparations to withdraw the Red Army, which first entered
Afghanistan in 1979. In the past, the Soviets have removed some
peripheral units, such as anti-aircraft batteries, but replaced
them with others. The current preparations are of a different
character, the sources said.
   Whether or not an agreement is reached, the Soviets are expected
to start a withdrawal by pulling units of their 40th Army from
garrisons south of Gardez and from Kandahar, Shinand and Herat in
the West, according to administration officials.
   These units are the most exposed to attack from a Mujahedeen
force estimated by administration analysts to number about 200,000.
   Soviet diplomats have indicated a willingness to withdraw
between 30 percent and 50 percent of their forces within the first
90 days of an agreement, pulling out the remainder within 10 months
after a pact is signed.
   Afghan guerrillas, as well as Pakistani and U.S. diplomats, say
a 10-month withdrawal timetable would allow the Soviets and their
allies to destroy the Mujahedeen if the flow of U.S. arms were cut.
   But some U.S. analysts believe an initial withdrawal of up to 50
percent of Soviet forces would include tactical air units operating
over south and west Afghanistan, leaving garrisons manned by the
army of the Kremlin-backed government open to Mujahedeen attack.
   Morale is already poor among the 40,000 Afghan government
forces, according to the guerrillas. And U.S. analysts believe the
confidence of the government has been shaken badly by the Soviet
announcement that the Red Army will leave.
   If the U.N. talks produce an agreement, the Soviets are thought
likely to leave elite special purpose forces to provide a security
shield for the Kabul regime, while moving the bulk of their
departing forces to the Soviet Union, possibly to an area just
north of the border.
   If the U.N. talks collapse, and the Soviets decide on a
unilateral withdrawal, ``all bets are off,'' one analyst said.
   One likely option, however, would be for the Soviets to
concentrate forces around Kabul and within a recently created
province in the far north, along the Soviet border.
   The new province of Sari Pull was created from parts of Balkh
and Juzjan provinces, which are separated from the Soviet republics
of Uzbekistan and Tadzhikistan by the Amu Darya River. The
Mujahedeen have staged a number of raids, none very destructive,
across the remote border, according to Afghan and Soviet reports.
   The largest town in the new province is Mazar-i-Sharif, which
U.S. analysts have long considered a likely final staging area for
a Soviet withdrawal.
</TEXT>
