<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Jackson-Noriega 3rdLd-Writethru a0562 04-04 0528</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson-Noriega, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0562,550</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDs: Inserts new grafs 4-5 with State Dept comment bgng ``At
the...''; Picks up 4th graf pvs ``The Jackson...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential hopeful Jesse Jackson
today renewed his call for Panamanian strongman Manuel Antonio
Noriega to leave Panama and released a letter in which Noriega
rejected ``any political and economic program that will be dictated
from Washington D.C.''
   Jackson, who had sent a letter to Noriega on March 22 urging him
to leave his troubled country, said he would forward Noriega's
response to the State Department and Congress.
   ``I remain convinced that it is in the best interests of the
Panamanian people for Gen. Noriega to leave. Today I reiterate my
public moral appeal for him to depart,'' Jackson said.
   At the State Department, deputy spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley
indicated displeasure over Jackson's communications with Noriega.
   ``In our view proliferation of channels is a tactic that Noriega
likes to use to buy time,'' Ms. Oakley said. ``We have available
channels of communication with Noriega if and when they are needed.
We think it would be best to continue to use these channels
exclusively.''
   The Jackson campaign released an unofficial translation of a
letter from Noriega.
   Noriega said the Panamanian ``defense forces ... reject any
imposition and any political and economic program that will be
dictated from Washington, D.C.''
   ``My duration as commander and chief of the defense forces is
governed by the Panamanian constitution and law of the defense
forces,'' he said.
   In a postscript, Noriega wrote, ``I have been lied about! I have
been villified! I have been humiliated internationally! I consider
myself to be been persecuted by illegal action by so-called
justice, by political interests of your nation. I, as a Christian
before you, denounce this untrue (sic).''
   Early today, Jackson told National Public Radio he would not
play a mediating role between the U.S. government and Noriega. ``I
see no direct role in the relationship myself.''
   ``My appeal to him was to leave,'' Jackson said Sunday in an
interview with The Associated Press during his Colorado swing.
Jackson said that in his letter to Noriega, he offered to do
whatever he could ``to facilitate his exit'' from that country.
   Jackson said a friend of his, Cirilo McSween of Chicago, had
gone to Panama at his request to meet with Noriega. Jackson
described McSween as a friend of 20 years who was originally from
Panama.
   Using rhetoric from his recent speeches, Jackson said U.S.
policy has been misguided:
   ``We've set the forest on fire to smoke one person out,'' he
said.
   The civil rights leader, who has made international trips in the
past to try to negotiate solutions to complicated crises, said he
did not think he would go to Panama.
   ``I doubt that,'' Jackson said.
   Later, at a Colorado Springs news conference, Jackson gave this
response:
   ``No, I'm not prepared to go right now,'' he said.
   Jackson said the current situation is full of danger for the
United States in the critical Central American region.
   `Unless the present crisis ends, we could lose by having
tremendous anti-Americanism in Panama,'' Jackson said.
</TEXT>
