<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--DoctorsStrike     04-04 0159</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Doctors Strike,0164</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Doctors Strike in Bangladesh</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 8,000 doctors at government
hospitals and health clinics went on strike Monday to press demands
for hiring recent medical school graduates.
   The walkout will continue through Wednesday at the country's
eight state-run hospitals and its more than 500 health centers,
according to a doctor known only as Mohibullah who spoke for the
Bangladesh Medical Association.
   Special teams of doctors stayed on duty to treat emergency
patients.
   A government spokesman condemned the strike, which he said was
depriving the poor of medical treatment.
   The government doctors' main demands include jobs for about 800
newly graduated interns and promotion of government doctors at the
country's rural health centers.
   The government spokesman said officials were negotiating with
strike leaders.
   Mohibullah said nearly 3,000 more private doctors would join the
strike for its final day Wednesday. He said doctors may walk out
indefinitely unless the government grants their demands.
</TEXT>
