<DOCNO> AP880404-0091 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 1213EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Church-Crisis Bjt   04-04 0825</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Church-Crisis, Bjt,0850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Roman Catholic Leaders Mediate Many Crises in Region</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Roman Catholic church, shepherd
of Latin America's soul for centuries, often minds its politics as
well and is a component of life: mediator, pacifier, giver of
praise and criticism by turns.
   Latin Americans often turn to the church in times of crisis, and
have done so in this troubled country.
   Archbishop Marcos McGrath of Panama has been asked to mediate
the political dispute that began in June over the leadership of
Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, who commands the Defense Forces and
controls the civilian government.
   It is a role the church has filled in nearby nations, most
notably El Salvador and Nicaragua.
   Panama's Catholic church has become increasingly critical of
Noriega's rule, but there are those who say McGrath and the
nation's priests and bishops have not taken a firm enough stand
against him.
   The church often is criticized in Latin America but is an
imposing presence, rich in tradition, with the confidence of a
large share of the population and the grudging respect of
politicians and the military.
   Through nearly two millennia, the Roman Catholic church has been
the Inquisition but also propagator of the faith, preserver of
literature and translator of the classics.
   It is a priest blessing military leaders, another doing
community work in slums or among poor peasants, one performing a
society wedding while his brother takes up the guerrilla cause,
demanding social justice.
   It is a reclusive conservative bishop rejecting new ideas, and
Archbishop Oscar Arnulfo Romero of El Salvador speaking from his
church through loudspeakers so those in the government palace could
hear him complain about military violations of human rights. He was
assassinated in March 1980.
   Some say wryly that Latin Americans will do anything for the
church except go inside one, but as an institution it generally is
trusted more than governments or the military.
   ``People perceive the church as an impartial institution capable
of settling disputes,'' said Fidel Chavez Mena, a leader of the
Christian Democratic Party in El Salvador. ``The culture and
religious sentiment of our people make them believe in the church.''
   As political and armed strife increased in the countries of
Central America in the past decade, the church has become involved
more frequently, to mediate or criticize regimes it sees as
violators of human rights.
   McGrath has publicly demanded that the military submit to
civilian rule, but churchgoers who want him to be more critical of
Noriega held a public protest outside his cathedral last week.
   The archbishop has not been an outspoken critic in the past.
Those close to him describe McGrath as a diplomatic negotiator who
would rather avoid a direct confrontation with the military.
   Many of his priests are foreigners and the government forces
them to have their residency visas stamped each three months no
matter how long they have spent in Panama.
   McGrath has acknowledged holding several meetings with Noriega
in search of a solution to Panama's political conflict.
   ``The church has tried to build a silver bridge for Noriega to
leave,'' the Rev. Fernando Guardia, vicar of the Panama City
diocese, said in an interview.
   Mediation by the church was agreed upon by the parties involved
and was made through President Oscar Arias of Costa Rica, Prime
Minister Felipe Gonzalez of Spain, and Carlos Andres Perez and
Daniel Oduber, former presidents of Venezuela and Costa Rica
respectively.
   Another Latin American archbishop, Cardinal Obando y Bravo of
Nicaragua, has been a thorn in the side of the leftist Sandinista
government. But it also turned to him as mediator when it first
agreed to talks with the U.S.-supported rebels.
   In 1974 and 1978, Obando y Bravo had acted as go-between for the
Sandinista National Liberation Front, then outlawed, and the
right-wing government of President Anastasio Somoza to obtain the
freedom of future President Daniel Ortega and other top leaders.
The Sandinistas won the civil war in July 1979.
   Obando y Bravo served as a witness earlier this month when the
Sandinistas and the rebels, known as Contras, signed a preliminary
cease-fire agreement.
   ``It is not easy to mediate, but the church always is ready to
contribute to national reconciliation,'' he said in a recent
interview.
   In El Salvador, Archbishop Arturo Rivera Damas is involved in
stalemated talks between leftist rebels and the U.S.-backed
government of President Jose Napoleon Duarte.
   Archbishop Prospero Penados del Barrio of Guatemala has agreed
to mediate between leftist rebels and the government, which has yet
to return to the negotiating table after a first round in October.
   In Honduras, the church is part of the ``national reconciliation
commission'' set up under the Central American peace plan of Aug. 7
to seek political solutions to internal conflicts.
   ``The church has the moral authority and credibility to act as
mediator,'' said Adan Fletes, leader of Nicaragua's Social
Christian Party.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
