<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MissingMarshal     04-04 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Missing Marshal,0405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Town Marshal Faked Own Abduction Due To Marital Problems,
Stepmother Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLUE MOUNTAIN, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The town marshal who claimed to have
escaped from kidnappers who intended to kill him actually faked the
episode to gain attention from his estranged wife, the officer's
stepmother says.
   ``It pushed him to the deepest end to do such a horrible
thing,'' said Mary Stokes. ``It's a sad situation.''
   Authorities said Sunday that the abduction Thursday of Gary
Stokes, who was the object of a large manhunt until he turned up
the next day, had been staged.
   Highway Patrol Investigator Sammy Pickens said he would turn
over to the district attorney's office information showing the
abduction was faked. No charges have been filed.
   Mrs. Stokes said Sunday that her stepson and his wife were
having marital problems, and that Stokes made up the abduction
story up to get his wife's attention.
   ``It hurts us,'' she said. ```We're relieved we know about it
and can get him some help.''
   Stokes, the town's only full-time policeman, said Sunday he
would have no comment.
   Stokes disappeared early Thursday after calling for back-up
units while investigating what he said was the attempted burglary
of a store in this town of 860 residents.
   Police found Stoke's car with the engine still running, the
lights on and his radio microphone hanging outside the door. His
police revolver and billfold were found nearby.
   Stokes reappeared Friday morning claiming to have escaped from
his captors. He told authorities he was abducted at gunpoint by
four men after he confronted them during a burglary at the store.
   ``It was manufactured,'' Pickens said. ``He was not kidnapped.''
   Mayor Robert Godwin said Blue Mountain's board of aldermen would
meet to discuss Stokes' future as marshal, a position he's held for
four months.
   ``I really can't tell you anything for sure until after Tuesday
night when the board meets,'' Godwin said Sunday when asked about
possible disciplinary action.
   Stoke's stepmother she didn't feel residents would be angry at
him, saying most residents were just glad he returned unharmed.
   But Brenda Hunter, an employee at the convenience story where
Stokes claimed he was abducted, said people in town ``are mad
because they had a snow job pulled on them. Everybody thought `This
is a good man here. This is who we need as marshal.'''
</TEXT>
