<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines     04-04 0559</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines,0576</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Troops Seek Coup Attempt Leader; Four More Plotters Missing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By YASMIN ARQUIZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troops stopped vehicles and blocked
escape routes to Malaysia during a nationwide search Monday for the
leader of the Aug. 28 coup attempt.
   The military said four more soldiers jailed in plots against
President Corazon Aquino also were missing.
   The government told foreign and Philippine reporters not to
publish or broadcast interviews with former Lt. Col. Gregorio
``Gringo'' Honasan, who fled a prison ship in Manila Bay before
dawn Saturday with 14 of his navy guards.
   Honasan's coup attempt left at least 53 people dead and hundreds
wounded. He had been confined in the prison ship since his arrest
Dec. 9.
   Chief military spokesman Col. Oscar Florendo said the armed
forces had received reports that Honasan, 39, had been seen in
Manila, rural Luzon and Mindanao island, about 500 miles south of
the capital.
   ``The search for ex-Col. Honasan continues,'' Florendo told
reporters. ``However, right now, we don't have any concrete lead to
follow.''
   Florendo denied allegations by opposition Sen. Juan Ponce Enrile
that troops raided Enrile's vacation house in Batangas province
Sunday during the search.
   Honasan was Defense Ministry security chief when Enrile was
minister of national defense. Enrile was fired in November 1986
after the government said it prevented a coup attempt by his
followers.
   Florendo said three officers and an enlisted man jailed for
involvement in the 1987 coup attempts were missing from the
detention center at Villamor Air Base. But he said the four fled
because of ``pressing family problems'' and their escape was not
related to Honasan's breakout.
   Armed troops seeking Honasan manned checkpoints around Manila
and searched private vehicles. The Philippine Constabulary
strengthened security in southern provinces to prevent Honasan from
slipping out of the country by boat to Malaysia, a traditional
escape route for fugitives and political dissidents.
   Share prices on the Manila Stock Exchange closed 2.28 per cent
lower Monday after trading resumed following the Easter break.
Traders blamed the decline on fears of instability in the wake of
Honasan's escape.
   Florendo said the military found no evidence that foreigners
were involved in the escape. Leftist Rep. Venancio Garduce had said
Americans may have helped Honasan escape to pressure the government
as it begins talks Tuesday with the United States on the status of
its military bases here.
   Justice Secretary Sedfrey Ordonez told Philippine radio and
television stations they may lose their licenses if they broadcast
interviews with Honasan, who gave many interviews before his arrest.
   Ordonez issued the warning after the private radio station DZXL
sought permission to air a statement from Honasan hours after he
escaped. A DZXL official confirmed it had a taped statement from
Honasan but would not say what it contained.
   Ordonez said the rights of free speech and press were the
hallmarks of Philippine democracy, restored after Mrs. Aquino was
swept to power in the February 1986 civilian-military uprising that
toppled President Ferdinand Marcos.
   ``However, like all other freedoms, these rights cannot be
permitted by the duly constituted government to be employed to
destroy the very government which guarantees these protections,''
he said.
   He said the policy also applied to foreign correspondents and
Philippine print media. But he gave no legal basis for including
newspapers, which do not need a license to operate.
</TEXT>
