<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AbandonedGirl     04-04 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Abandoned Girl,0308</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Father Says Gary Girl To Live With Great-Grandmother</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WAYNE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 9-year-old girl whose lower legs were
amputated after she was found severely frostbitten in a Gary
apartment will live with her great-grandmother after she leaves a
rehabilitation center, her father says.
   James E. Carlisle, of Fort Wayne, said he had hoped to regain
custody of his daughter, Darlwin Carlisle, but decided that he had
little chance of persuading the courts because he and his wife,
Alice, already have two small children.
   ``This is the best thing,'' Carlisle said Sunday.
   The girl's mother, Darlwin Britt, is in Lake County Jail
awaiting trial for felony child neglect.
   Carlisle said caseworkers had been working with his grandmother,
Katie M. Carlisle of Gary, the past several weeks to make sure
everything is ready for Darlwin's arrival.
   It still will be some time before Darlwin leaves La Rabida
Children's Hospital in Chicago, where she has been undergoing
rehabiliation and therapy to help her adjust to her artificial legs.
   The hospital said Saturday that a foster family had been found,
but refused to identify the family except to say they were known to
Carlisle.
   Both of her legs were amputated below the knee soon after she
was found Jan. 17, frostbitten inside a barricaded, unheated attic
apartment.
   Since Darlwin's hospitalization, Carlisle said he has tried to
visit her once a week. He has asked her several times if she wants
to see her mother.
   ``She says, `Yeah, I want to see her, but I don't want to stay
with her,''' Carlisle said. ``She says, `Next time I could lose my
arms.'''
   Ms. Britt and Carlisle were teen-agers when Darlwin was born. He
said Ms. Britt's family discouraged him from seeing his daughter
when she was young.
</TEXT>
