<DOCNO> AP880404-0100 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 1249EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-KingAnniversary 3rdLd-Writethru a0571 04-04 0847</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-King Anniversary, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0571,0865</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>King Followers Must Renew Commitment, Colleagues Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Nonviolent Cop, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 5th graf, `At King's ...,' with comment
from Memphis mayor at service.
^By WOODY BAIRD</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty years after the assassination of
Martin Luther King Jr. unleashed riots in America's black ghettos,
blacks and whites recommitted themselves to his dream of a better
life for the oppressed.
   King, gunned down as he stood on the balcony of the Lorraine
Motel here, was remembered around the country in services and
speeches that urged people to carry on King's work.
   ``We've got to be concerned about one another,'' said King's
son, Martin Luther King III. ``We've got to be concerned about
helping one another.''
   A memorial service this morning at the Orpheum Theater, a
downtown landmark, was the first sponsored by the city on the
anniversary of the assassination. It was to be followed by a march
to the Lorraine Motel, where a ceremony was planned, and the start
of a three-week Southern Christian Leadership Conference march
through Alabama, Mississippi and Georgia.
   At King's tomb in Atlanta, a simple wreath-laying ceremony was
scheduled this afternoon.
   Mayor Richard Hackett, who appointed a commission to organize
Memphis' first memorial for the slain civil rights leader, said it
is time for the city where he died to better organize its efforts
to help the poor.
   ``Twenty years ago, Dr. King spoke of a dream. Today, this city
recognizes the necessity for that dream to become a reality,''
Hackett said at the memorial service. ``It is right. It is just,
and it is in the best interest of us all.''
   The memorial service included gospel singing, songs by a group
of schoolchildren and a dance, titled ``Love Has No Color,'' by
five teen-age girls dressed in gray ballet outfits.
   Nine-year-old Brian Harris, waiting to go on stage with other
schoolchildren at the Orpheum, said he was proud to take part in
the service.
   ``We should celebrate because he left us his dream,'' the
youngster said. ``He gave black people a chance to be free.''
   The day he was assassinated, King was in Memphis organizing a
strike by sanitation workers. He was shot the day after delivering
his famous ``Mountain Top'' speech at the Mason Temple.
   ``I've been to the mountain top ... and I've seen the promised
land,'' he said in his last public address. ``I may not get there
with you, but I want you to know tonight, that we as a people will
get to the promised land.''
   Atlanta Mayor Andrew Young, asked on NBC's ``Today'' show about
the presidential campaign of Jesse Jackson, said: ``I think we see
the American people responding to a message and not to skin color.
That's what Martin lived and died for, that a man would be judged
by the content of his character, rather than the color of his
skin.''
   The search for the promised land that King talked about must
continue, Benjamin Hooks, president of the National Association for
the Advancement of Colored People, told 500 people gathered Sunday
night at the same Mason Temple.
   ``So Dr. King, we haven't made it yet ... but we are determined
from this day, we are going to march forward and ain't nobody going
to turn us around,'' Hooks said.
   But on the anniversary of King's death, civil rights leaders
said the nation's poor are as bad off now as they were 20 years
ago, and his struggles for the racial equality and social justice
are also in need of new life.
   ``Twenty years later, everything has changed and nothing has
changed,'' said Joseph Lowery, president of the Southern Christian
Leadership Conference, a civil rights organization formed by King.
   ``We are too satisfied. We must learn some lessons from the
`60s. We must go back to some basics,'' said Ralph Abernathy, one
of King's top assistants and closest friends.
   Although progress has been made toward social equality for
blacks, the number of poor people in the nation continues to grow,
King's son said.
   ``Today, we see there are better than 36 million people living
below the level of poverty in America. In 1968, there were 26
million,'' King said.
   ``Individually we are better off, but masses of people still
suffer,'' King said. ``Daddy talked about `the least of these our
brothers and sisters' and that `least of these' continues to grow.
We have homeless people in every major city in America.''
   Meanwhile, in Portland, Ore., nearly 100 people marched Saturday
to mark King's assassination.
   ``When people gather together there is hope,'' said Ron Herndon,
co-director of Portland's Black United Front. ``The message is
there still are those who will stand up against racism.''
   King's death on April 4, 1968, sparked riots in several American
cities, including Washington, D.C., where four days of burning,
looting and violence left six people dead, 1,097 injured, 900 fires
and 6,124 arrests. The riots ended after President Johnson ordered
federal troops and 1,750 members of the D.C. National Guard into
the city.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
