<HEAD>USDA Preparing Instructional Program on Commodity Futures Markets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guidelines for operating a pilot program to
teach farmers about commodity futures markets have been sent to
agency offices in 40 counties of 22 states, the Agriculture
Department said Monday.
   Participation in the Futures and Options Marketing Pilot Program
will be limited to farmers who participate in the 1988 or 1989 USDA
programs for corn, wheat or cotton, and to producers of 1988 or
1989 soybeans.
   ``Participants must attend at least one futures and options
marketing seminar presented by the Cooperative Extension Service,''
the announcement said.
   Although most of the seminars will begin this month, a few have
begun already, according to agency officials.
   The pilot program was ordered by Congress in the 1985 farm law
``to educate farmers in the use of agricultural commodity futures
and options markets as risk managment tools,'' the announcement
said.
   Guidelines for the program were sent last week to state and
county offices for release locally. Additional information will be
available in May from county offices of the department's
Agricultural Stabilization and Conservation Service, and the
Cooperative Extension Service.
   The states and counties previously designated for the pilot
program, include:
   ARIZONA _ Maricopa.
   CALIFORNIA _ Fresno, Tulare.
   GEORGIA _ Washington.
   IDAHO _ Latah.
   ILLINOIS _ Champaign, McLean, Morgan, Stark.
   INDIANA _ Clinton, Knox.
   IOWA _ Benton, Hardin, Monona, Washington.
   KANSAS _ Meade, Sumner.
   LOUISIANA _ Morehouse.
   MICHIGAN _ Gratiot, Huron.
   MINNESOTA _ Polk, Swift.
   MISSISSIPPI _ Leflore, Sunflower.
   MISSOURI _ Lafayette, New Madrid.
   MONTANA, Chouteau.
   NEBRASKA _ Lincoln, Saunders.
   NORTH DAKOTA _ Cass.
   OHIO _ Allen, Darke.
   OKLAHOMA _ Garfield.
   SOUTH DAKOTA _ McCook.
   TEXAS _ Hansford, Hidalgo, Lubbock, Lynn.
   VIRGINIA _ Southampton.
   WISCONSIN _ Dane.
