<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis-Image Bjt   04-04 0770</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Image, Bjt,760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Candidate Warms Up a Cool Style</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CADOTT, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis stood in the muddy farmyard,
showing a group of children how to play the traditional Greek game
``cracking of eggs'' on Easter Sunday.
   ``You hold the egg up like this,'' the Massachusetts governor
told one child and then turned to another and said, ``And then you
hold your egg and tap hers. The one whose egg isn't broken at the
end is the winner.''
   Dukakis, the Democratic presidential candidate with a reputation
as a technocrat, is trying to warm his cool image as he struggles
to win Wisconsin's primary Tuesday and get back on track for the
nomination.
   ``I'm a guy who is passionate about cheese,'' Dukakis cracked as
he was presented with a big chunk of Wisconsin cheese at the
Danielson farm here on Sunday.
   Jesse Jackson stunned Dukakis with a sweeping 2-to-1 win in the
Michigan caucuses on March 26, rocking a campaign that was trying
to build momentum and a sense that he was the inevitable nominee.
Riding the wave out of Michigan, Jackson has drawn big crowds in
Wisconsin ahead of that state's primary on Tuesday.
   To counter Jackson _ by far the campaign's best orator _ Dukakis
has unveiled a new speech, a sharpened message of his own and a
more relaxed style on the stump.
   Emphasizing his strength as a decision-making state executive,
Dukakis in his new speech declares that he wants to be known as the
``great builder,'' not the ``great communicator'' _ a phrase often
applied to Ronald Reagan.
   ``After seven years of charisma, maybe a little competence is in
order in the White House,'' is one of Dukakis' new applause lines.
   There is also a new television ad that condemns Reagan's
economic policies and closes with Dukakis, sitting coatless in his
office, talking about what he wants to do for people.
   ``He's spent 25 years in public service making a difference in
people's lives,'' Dukakis spokesman Leslie Dach said in explaining
the current emphasis of the campaign.
   Jackson's major pitch _ that he has stood with the workers and
the farmers in their hours of crisis _ has been a compelling one.
   Dukakis has tried to counter that in both public and private
meetings by explaining his use of a Massachusetts plant-closing law
to save jobs and his efforts to save a big General Motors plant in
Massachusetts. Chrysler's decision to close a plant in Kenosha has
been a target for all the Democratic candidates.
   But substance is not the only way to woo voters. Image and style
are key elements that the Dukakis campaign has not ignored.
   In recent days, Dukakis has donned an apron to serve food to
senior citizens and at an Easter supper at a Greek Orthodox church.
He went to the Danielson's barn to be photographed watching as cows
were milked in this state with a big dairy industry.
   ``It's also about rolling up your sleeves and working hard for
votes,'' Dach added.
   Dukakis has his own explanation for the change. After a long day
of campaigning Sunday, he mused on the chartered plane that
``spending so much time in Iowa, talking to small groups of people
who are passionately interested in this one issue'' made him aware
that retail politics ``are at heart of what we are doing.''
   The Massachusetts governor opens his stump speeches with digs at
Wisconsin Gov. Tommy Thompson, who said last week he would vote for
Jackson if he were a Democrat.
   The Dukakis campaign is deeply worried about such a crossover
vote in this open-primary state. But Dukakis makes light of that,
saying he sent the Republican governor a note thanking him for
making it clear that George Bush does not want to run against
Dukakis in the fall. Then he adds:
   ``Tommy really got excited the other day, according to the
newspapers. He was introducing the vice president in Waukesha and
he said, `It's time for the Bush pregnancy to begin.'
   ``I'll drink to that,'' Dukakis says. ``I'll drink to that.''
   Several times before union or blue-collar crowds, Dukakis has
used a mild expletive. That is something friends say the candidate
does occasionally in private, but it has rarely been heard before
in the carefully watched appearances on the campaign trail.
   ``Hell, I'm the only candidate in this race who has ever
balanced a budget,'' he said at one point.
   Boasting about the benefits of full employment, Dukakis added:
``Hell, they are paying six bucks an hour in McDonalds in my state,
because they can't get people.''
</TEXT>
