<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People     04-04 0834</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People,0863</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Superconductivity expert C.W. Paul Chu said
Monday he will remain at the University of Houston after rejecting
an offer to move to the University of California at Berkeley.
   Chu called the decision one of the most difficult of his life
and said he had been torn between his loyalty to Houston and his
desire to be at Berkeley, ``as it has been a personal goal to join
the Berkeley faculty.''
   In a statement, Chu said ``developing the superconductivity
effort at UH is a great responsibility. One that has been made
easier thanks to the support of the university, foundations,
industry and city, state and federal government.''
   Berkeley's effort to land Chu highlighted the pressure on
developers of higher-termperature superconductors, which transmit
electricity without resistance.
   Previously, superconductors worked only at temperatures near
absolute zero, or about minus 460 degrees Fahrenheit.
Higher-temperature devices could revolutionize electrical
transmission, computers, trains and many other electrical devices,
scientists say.
   Chu ``has built up a group there (in Houston) and he feels
responsible to them,'' said Berkeley physicist Marvin L. Cohen. Chu
also may have considered the career of his wife Mary, a vice
president of a Houston bank, he added.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HEREFORD, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Princess Anne got a bloody nose Monday
when the horse she was riding in a steeplechase race made a mistake
at the first fence and conked her face with its head.
   ``The princess took a knock when her horse made a hash of the
first, but there is nothing wrong,'' said trainer David Nicholson.
``It was a good performance and the horse ran on well.''
   The 37-year-old daughter of Queen Elizabeth II and her horse
finished fourth in the National Hunt race at Hereford, 45 miles
southwest of Birmingham in western England.
   Anne, an accomplished horsewoman, was thrown from her mount but
not injured at an Australian racecourse Friday when the horse
apparently shied at some running water at the side of the track.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kenneth O'Dowd, cousin of pop singer Boy George,
appeared in court Monday accused of trying to kill a man with a
shotgun.
   A magistrate ordered the 41-year-old O'Dowd, who sported a black
eye, to be held without bail until a hearing Tuesday.
   O'Dowd, an interior decorator, was arrested and charged Sunday
with attempted murder relating to a shooting incident March 23 in
