<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-KALCrash 1stLd-Writethru a0544 04-04 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-KAL Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0544,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justices Will Review Limits on Airline's Liability</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs graf 4, One of the, to CORRECT McDonald's party.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to review
rulings limiting Korean Air Lines' financial liability for a 1983
disaster in which 269 people died _ the shooting down of a KAL
passenger jet over Soviet airspace.
   The justices said they will study arguments that the airline
should have to face more than $75,000 in damages for each death.
   KAL Flight 7, en route from New York City to Seoul, Korea, was
shot down by a Soviet military airplane Sept. 1, 1983 after flying
more than 300 miles off course and entering Soviet airspace over
the Sea of Japan.
   One of the 61 Americans killed was Democratic Rep. Lawrence
McDonald of Georgia.
   Many of the victims' families, including McDonald's widow, sued
KAL in various federal courts. The wrongful-death lawsuits were
consolidated and presented to a federal trial judge here.
   Lawyers for the victims' families in 1984 asked U.S. District
Judge Aubrey E. Robinson Jr. to declare that KAL was not eligible
for the $75,000-per-death liability cap imposed by the Warsaw
Convention and the Montreal Agreement, treaties covering
international airline travel.
   The treaties specify that passenger tickets must tell of the
$75,000 limit warning in lettering no smaller than 10-point print.
The KAL tickets told of the liability limit in slightly smaller,
8-point print.
   Judge Robinson ruled that the $75,000 limit applied to the KAL
disaster, and his decision was upheld by the U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals here last Sept. 25.
   The appeals court ruling conflicts with a decision by the 5th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals stemming from a 1982 airline crash in
Kenner, La., that killed 154 people.
   The 5th Circuit court upheld $720,000 in wrongful-death awards
won by the families of five Uruguayans who were among the victims
on Pan Am Flight 759, which crashed outside New Orleans shortly
after takeoff July 9, 1982.
   Pan Am was barred from benefiting from the $75,000-per-death
limit because the limit was discussed on its tickets in 9-point
rather than 10-point print.
   The case is In Re KAL Disaster, 87-1055.
</TEXT>
