<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Irish     04-04 0620</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Irish,0639</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protestants March, Vow to Fight United Ireland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANBRIDGE, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Protestants
waving British flags marched Monday to mark a 299-year-old victory
over Roman Catholics and vowed to oppose forever a
Catholic-dominated united Ireland.
   The Protestant parades followed Sunday's peaceful marches across
the province by Catholics commemorating the 1916 Easter Rising
against British rule in what is now the Republic of Ireland.
   Led by 40 fife-and-drum bands, the pro-British Apprentice Boys
parades marched peacefully in a carnival-like atmosphere to
commemorate Protestant resistance to the 1689 siege of Londonderry
ordered by England's Catholic King James II.
   The Apprentice Boys take their name from 12 apprentices said to
have slammed Londonderry's gates on James' army at the start of the
unsuccessful 105-day siege.
   Hardline Protestant lawmaker Peter Robinson told several hundred
marchers at Dundonald on the outskirts of Belfast that the Irish
Republican Army was planning an all-out war against Protestants.
   The outlawed IRA is fighting to drive the British from Northern
Ireland and unite it with the overwhelmingly Catholic Irish
Republic.
   Robinson said that over the past few months the IRA has brought
into Ireland arms ``more powerful and sophisticated'' than ever
used before.
   ``However, the loyalist (Protestant) community will band itself
together and make it clear to the IRA that while it may be
victorious in the atrocities it carries out, the final victory will
go to those who have endured the most,'' he said.
   Leaders of Sinn Fein, the legal political wing of the IRA,
dashed any hopes Sunday of a cease-fire.
   Sinn Fein President Gerry Adams said he expected talks to
continue with the moderate Catholic Social Democratic and Labor
Party on an overall strategy ``for justice and peace'' in the
strife-torn province, where Protestants outnumber Catholics 3-2.
   But Sinn Fein Vice President Martin McGuinness stressed the IRA
has gone on record as saying there will be no more cease-fires.
``Talk (can) take place but the war will go on,'' he said.
   John Hume, leader of the Social Democrats, said he intends to
pursue his party's dialogue with Sinn Fein despite their opposition
to any cease-fire until Britain announces its withdrawal from the
province.
   ``Nobody should be surprised that Sinn Fein have a very
different approach from us at the beginning, because if we had the
same approach, there would be no need for dialogue,'' Hume was
quoted Monday as telling The Irish Times.
   Party Chairman Alban Maginness told BBC Radio Ulster the talks
are concerned with much broader issues than arranging a cease-fire.
   ``We are concerned with establishing the conditions whereby
there will be a total, permanent end of all violence,'' he said.
   The meetings have sparked speculation that talks including
Protestants as well as Catholics might be the next step.
   But Robinson, a key figure in Rev. Ian Paisley's Democratic
Unionist Party, one of the province's two main Protestant parties,
ruled out participation in such talks. He said he remained
vehemently opposed to any formula to solve Northern Ireland's
problems based on the Anglo-Irish agreement.
   The 1985 accord gives the Irish Republic a consultative role in
the administration of Northern Ireland, which Robinson and many
Protestants view as the first step to a united, Catholic-run
Ireland.
   ``No way will unionist (Protestant) leaders sit down and talk to
the mouthpiece of the IRA, Gerry Adams,'' Robinson said.
   At the largest Protestant march in Banbridge, 25 miles southwest
of Belfast, several thousand people stood in silence for one minute
in memory of members of the security forces killed in the sectarian
violence, the 11 people who died in a November IRA bombing at a war
memorial in Enniskillen, and two British soldiers killed March 19.
</TEXT>
