<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     04-04 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0613</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SLIDELL, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cockroaches from these parts are setting
race records at a small Quaker college in Indiana.
   For the past two years, Louisiana contenders have taken two of
the top three places in the Bundy 500 race, named for the Earlham
College dormitory where it takes place and the Indianapolis car
race.
   The roaches started moving north from this southeastern Lousiana
area in 1986 when a local dentist began shipping them to his
daughter, Marcy Wood, 19, then a freshman at the Richmond, Ind.,
college.
   ``We have steam tunnels that run all under the campus. That's
where most people catch their roaches,'' said Wood, 19, of the
Slidell area.
   Egged on by a friend who had raced the local steam-tunnel
variety, Wood called her father about importing a few ringers.
   ``She said, `These are little, tiny roaches. They're nothing
like we have in Louisiana,''' recalled William H. Wood.
   He used peppermint candy to lure roaches onto the deck of his
home, which backs up to swampland. He packed them with leaves,
grass and straw in a plastic wine jug with air holes and mailed it
to his daughter.
   Shipments for her friends for next year's race may not be
necessary, Miss Wood said.
   ``One of them this year let a roach go down in the steam
tunnel,'' she said. ``So we're breeding Louisiana roaches in
Indiana.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The jump in postal rates brought bargain hunters
out in force to take advantage of their last chance at mailing
22-cent first-class letters.
   Officials said letters that show up Monday with 22 cent stamps
will probably get a day of amnesty because of the cost of returning
them all to senders.
   ``It's just not feasible to do something like that,'' said
Central Square Superintendent Edmund Powers.
   On Saturday, Barbara Lillie of Newton Corner brought 15 letters
to the Newtonville post office.
   ``That's why all my mail is going out today, even a few things
that can wait until later,'' she said.
   Lillie said the small-scale thrift while paying her bills made
her feel good, like ``going to the supermarket with your coupons
and saving 20 cents, or whatever.''
   There also were plenty of people buying the new 25 cent stamps
or 3 centers to supplement leftover stocks of the old 22s.
   ``It was really busy,'' said Carolyn LaFee, a clerk at the
Central Square post office in Cambridge.
 
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BELMONT, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three years ago, Marilyn Doane knew little
about a business that has made her overseer of 42,000 fish.
   The 38-year-old woman is raising trout and selling about 3,000 a
month. She supplies the fish to 35 commercial customers, including
area supermarkets, restaurants, country clubs and fish stores.
   ``It's potential is almost beyond what I can imagine,'' said
Doane, who worked as a carpenter before turning to fish. She
started out with 1,000 fingerlings a couple of years ago on the
30-acre farm she and her husband own just north of Grand Rapids.
   She had a big setback shortly after she began. Torrential rains
in September 1986 caused a dam to burst a mile upstream on the
Rogue River and flooded the ponds.
   ``We lost 6,000 fish,'' she said, and the survivors mingled with
other fish. ``It took me three weeks to sort them all out.''
   Doane is putting in more ponds and building an addition to her
house for more efficient fish processing.
   ``It turned around in January; I made $6,'' Doane said proudly.
</TEXT>
