<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 1418EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lyubimov     04-04 0632</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lyubimov,0650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Exiled Stage Director Invited to Return and Open Production</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exiled stage director Yuri Lyubimov will return in
May to the Taganka Theater he founded to preside over the opening
of a production he was working on before he was fired and
dishonored four years ago.
   The Taganka's deputy director, Alexander M. Yefimovich,
confirmed the 70-year-old impresario had accepted an invitation
from the theater to come to Moscow and open ``Boris Godunov,'' his
drama about the troubled eight-year reign of the Russian czar who
died in 1605.
   Yefimovich said he did not know how long Lyubimov would be in
Moscow to put the final touches on the play before opening night,
but he made clear that the popular director would be coming for a
working visit rather than returning for permanent residence.
   ``As far as I know it won't be a long visit,'' Yefimovich said.
   Lyubimov, 70, was working in Europe and could not immediately be
reached for comment on his reported plans to return to his native
country for the first time in almost five years.
   He became an Israeli citizen this year and lives with his wife,
Katalin, and son, Peter, in Jerusalem. He has been staging
productions around the world since his departure from Moscow in
July 1983.
   When Lyubimov departed to bring Fyodor Dostoyevsky's ``Crime and
Punishment'' to London, cultural figures speculated he would not be
allowed to return. That he was allowed to take his family with him
on the trip indicated he was not expected to return.
   Under Lyubimov, the Taganka Theater became famous for its
avant-garde productions and controversial themes, and he battled
with censors throughout much of his career in Moscow.
   Lyubimov extended his stay in London, demanding assurances that
he would be allowed artistic freedom once back in the Soviet Union.
In March 1984, he was fired from the Taganka and expelled from the
Communist Party.
   His name was rarely mentioned in the Soviet press until last
week, when the government daily newspaper Izvestia carried an
interview with him in Madrid, where the Taganka company was staging
Maxim Gorky's ``Mother.''
   Izvestia quoted Lyubimov as saying he would like to return to
work in the Soviet Union if conditions were favorable, but said he
was making no political demands.
   ``In order to once again gain strength, survive, one needs to
stand on his native land, on which he was raised, where his fathers
and grandfathers lived,'' he was quoted as saying.
   The director praised the more open literature that is being
published under Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policy of glasnost, and
said, ``it is necessary to come, to see, and to work in the
theater.''
   In March 1987, Lyubimov and a group of other exiled scientists
and artists wrote an open letter expressing their doubts about
Gorbachev's reform program and calling the Soviet Union a ``gravely
sick country.''
   The letter was printed by the Moscow News, and the writers were
criticized bitterly in the official media, which accused them of
wishing evil on their native land.
   Lyubimov denied having ill motives and has said in interviews
while working abroad that he concentrated on productions that would
acquaint the world with the best of Russian culture. He staged
``Crime and Punishment'' at Washington's Arena Stage last year.
   This week's edition of Moscow News also carried an article about
the Taganka and the company's meeting with Lyubimov in Madrid,
where he viewed ``Mother'' four times.
   Moscow News said Lyubimov planned to visit Moscow for the
opening of ``Boris Godunov'' in May, but gave no details.
   Referring to the freer hand allowed in the arts under Gorbachev,
the newspaper commented, ``Now we can afford to be generous and
noble'' in overcoming the excesses of the past.
</TEXT>
