<DOCNO> AP880404-0108 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 1443EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Carlucci     04-04 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Carlucci,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carlucci Meets With Indians on Defense, Afghanistan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci
held talks Monday with Indian officials on Afghanistan and on
expanding U.S.-Indian defense cooperation, a Defense Ministry
official said.
   ``The general focus was on bilateral cooperation in matters of
defense _ research, production and development,'' said the
official, who briefed reporters on condition of anonymity.
   Carlucci met with Defense Minister K.S. Pant and the chiefs of
the Indian army, air force and navy. Foreign Secretary K.P.S. Menon
attended one session, the official said.
   India is seeking U.S. technology for a light combat aircraft it
is developing. It also has been seeking some specialized military
equipment, such as radar systems.
   As Carlucci's meetings were going on, a fire broke out several
miles away at the American cultural center in New Delhi. There were
no injuries.
   The fire was an accident that had ``absolutely no connection''
with Carlucci's visit, said Douglas Rose, deputy director of the
U.S. Information Service in New Delhi.
   The fire began on the fifth floor, the building's top story,
after sparks from a welder's torch ignited flammable gas canisters
stored there, said S.K. Dheri, the city's chief fire officer.
   About 150 firefighters battled the blaze for an hour at the
American Center, which houses U.S. Information Service offices, a
library, theater, meeting rooms and a media center, Dheri said.
   Damage was estimated at between $100,000 and $300,000, said
State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley in Washington.
   It was Carlucci's first visit to India. He was scheduled to
visit military installations near Bombay on Tuesday before meeting
with Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi. He was to leave Wednesday for
Pakistan.
   The United News of India said that during Carlucci's talks,
``the question of the United States reducing its arms supplies to
Pakistan following the Soviet withdrawal from Afghanistan also came
up for a review.'' It did not elaborate.
</TEXT>
