<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Politics-Ads 1stLd-Writethru a0636 04-04 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Politics-Ads, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0636,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gore Blasts Corporations; Simon Speaks On Behalf Of Underdogs</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs final graf pvs and adds one graf to update with Dukakis
running two ads, not one</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr. attacked corporations and
touted newspaper endorsements while Sen. Paul Simon spoke on behalf
of underdogs, including himself, in television ads aimed at those
who will vote Tuesday in Wisconsin's Democratic presidential
primary.
   The airwaves also carried ads placed by Massachusetts Gov.
Michael Dukakis and Jesse Jackson, but Gore of Tennessee and Simon
of Illinois, with much at stake in Wisconsin, appeared to be the
big spenders.
   Gore's campaign refused to disclose the size of his media
campaign but others estimated it at more than $250,000. A Simon
spokesman said the Illinois senator bought $150,000 of media time.
   Dukakis, with a slight edge over Jackson in recent polls in
Wisconsin, was investing about $115,000, a spokesman said. Jackson
had spent $50,000 on media, including $9,000 for radio, his
campaign said.
   Gore ran six TV spots in Wisconsin including five new ones. Many
of the ads were highly critical of corporate America.
   One of the spots being aired Monday night quoted from editorials
in which Gore was endorsed by The Milwaukee Journal and The
Milwaukee Sentinel.
   In another ad, a shirt-sleeved Gore tells a town meeting in
Wisconsin, ``We should encourage American companies to invest more
here in the United States and create more jobs here for a change.''
A narrator says: ``He's always stood up for working people and
against the rich and powerful.''
   Gore, like most of the other candidates, took on the Chrysler
Corp., which has announced it plans to close its automaking plant
in Kenosha, Wis. In an ad, he says the company was leaving
employees ``without jobs or hope. And it's happening all over, not
just in Wisconsin. I'll make the corporations pay their share of
taxes. ... Let's make them put people over profits.''
   Simon ran two new TV ads in Wisconsin, including one he wrote in
which he recalls his grandparents' Wisconsin dairy farm and talks
about the problems of workers, senior citizens and children.
   ``We're in this together, one family,'' Simon says. ``When any
of us hurt, all of us hurt. Tuesday you can launch an underdog who
fights for underdogs.''
   The second ad for Simon, a member of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, cites his experience on foreign policy matters.
   Jackson ran three spots in Wisconsin _ two new ones plus an
earlier one containing an endorsement by entertainer Bill Cosby.
The ads showed Jackson at a rally with workers at the Kenosha
Chrysler plant and a farmer saying Jackson saved his farm.
   Dukakis used a total of five ads in Wisconsin, including a
biography and an endorsement by former House Speaker Thomas P.
``Tip'' O'Neill Jr., D-Mass. As primary day neared, he was running
two ads, one of them an attack on ``Republican indifference'' to
the plight of the homeless and the unemployed. The newly produced
spot began Friday on Wisconsin television stations.
   The other Dukakis ad, which has been used elsewhere, stresses
the governor's experience as a chief executive balancing budgets
and making decisions.
</TEXT>
