<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Ethiopia-Somalia 1stLd-Writethru a0627 04-04 0533</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ethiopia-Somalia, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0627,0544</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ethiopia & Somalia Agree to Restore Relations</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 1st graf to raise reference to war; SUBS 9th graf, ``In
1977-78 ...'' to conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ABEBE ANDUALEM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ethiopia and Somalia, which fought
a full-scale war 11 years ago, agreed to restore diplomatic
relations and discuss border disputes dating back more than a
century, Ethiopia's foreign minister said Monday.
   Berhanu Bahiy released details of a 10-point agreement worked
out between the East African neighbors during the weekend by an
Ethiopian delegation he led and a Somali delegation led by Deputy
Prime Minister Ahmed Mohamoud Farah.
   Under the agreement, the two sides will ``refrain from the use
of threat or use of force against the territorial integrity or
political independence'' of the other.
   The two sides also would move their forces back at least six to
nine miles from the border. The withdrawal is to begin by April 15
and to be completed by May 15 under the supervision of a joint
military committee.
   Both sides agreed to exchange prisoners of war within four
months and ``to prevent all acts of destabilization and subversive
activities against each other.'' Somalia and Ethiopia have
supported and harbored rebels opposed to the other's government.
   Ethiopia's central government has fought long wars with
separatists in its northernmost regions of Eritrea and Tigray.
Rebels in both regions last week claimed major victories, prompting
President Mengistu Haile Mairiam to comment publicly on the
problems for the first time in his 13-year rule.
   Somali President Mohamed Siad Barre's government also is
fighting insurgencies.
   Any lessening of tension between Ethiopia and Somalia would free
troops from the border for redeployment to areas of rebel activity.
   In 1977-78, Ethiopia and Somalia went to war after Somalia
invaded the Ogaden, a semi-arid region of eastern Ethiopia
populated by ethnic Somalis.
   Previously, Ethiopia had insisted that the border question be
included in the agenda, but Somalia proposed that the two sides
first restore relations and take other steps before tackling the
question separately.
   Berhanu said the boundary question would be discussed later, but
said no date had been set.
   The agreement was signed after talks Friday and Saturday in
Mogadishu, the Somali capital. It is based on a March 30, 1964,
pact known as the Khartoum Agreement.
   The 1964 agreement, which took its name from the Sudanese
capital where it was signed, was never honored by either side.
   The 1977 invasion by Somalia, then backed by Moscow, sparked a
war that ended a year later when Ethiopia's Marxist government
routed the invaders and pushed them back across the border. By
then, Ethiopia had millions of dollars in weapons from its new
backer, the Soviet Union, and help from Cuban troops.
   Ethiopia had been one of the West's staunchest African friends
before Emperor Haile Selassie was overthrown in a 1974 revolution.
But Moscow's switch put Addis Ababa firmly in the Soviet camp.
   Somalia then sought and received U.S. backing.
   Ethiopia has the largest military force in black Africa, but the
conflict with Somalia has been a stalemate since the 1977 war
despite a technical state of war and some border clashes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880404-0116 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 1952EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Colombia-Drugs     04-04 0592</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia-Drugs,0611</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Colombians Propose Truce With Drug Traffickers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leading Colombians are proposing that
the government negotiate a truce with drug traffickers who have
killed 21 judges and scores of other people in the last four years.
   So far, the government of President Virgilio Barco, a close
friend of the United States, has vowed to keep on fighting the drug
traffickers.
   But many Colombians, including the attorney general and two
Roman Catholic bishops, have called for a truce because the United
States is not doing enough to help stop the illicit trade.
   The U.S. government gave $14 million to Colombia last year to
fight drug trafficking.
   In addition to the judges, drug traffickers have killed two
newspaper editors, a justice minister, an attorney general and
scores of policemen and soldiers.
   After traffickers killed Attorney General Carlos Mauro Hoyos in
February for his battle against drug trafficking, Barco said his
government would not be intimidated by the gangsters.
   Two bishops, Dario Castrillon of Pereira and Samuel Silverio
Buitrago of Popayan said in February that the Colombian government
should start talks with the drug traffickers.
   ``Recalling the words of President Nixon, all war is
political,'' Castrillon said. ``We have to look for ... dialogue in
order to avoid war.''
   Silverio said drug money could be used to help the poor. ``You
might as well try to cover up the sun with your hands as deny that
the economy has not been helped by drug trafficking,'' Silverio
said.
   Attorney General Alfredo Gutierrez Marquez reiterated in a
broadcast interview Monday that he would not object if the
government opened talks with drug traffickers.
   Gutierrez turned in his resignation last week after a news
report that showed his brother had bought a farm and an airstrip
from a drug trafficker and that a drug trafficker's plane had
landed there.
   The president accepted the resignation. Gutierrez will stay in
office until his replacement is appointed. There have been no
reports linking Gutierrez himself with drugs.
   The mayor-elect of Medellin, Juan Gomez Martinez, said last week
the government should ask for talks with the drug traffickers. He
said the country finds itself at war with the traffickers and ``in
a war situation you don't wait for the earth to be scorched to look
for a way out of the problem.''
   Gomez is the owner of the Medellin newspaper El Colombiano. Drug
traffickers have killed his chief of security, shot up his house
and tried to bomb his newspaper.
   Colombians have long pointed out that they do not have the
resources that the United States has for fighting drug trafficking.
   Colombian anti-drug agents often are armed with outdated weapons
and communications equipment and have only a dozen helicopters.
   An air force pilot flying operations against coca plantations in
the eastern jungles once said the air force doesn't have spraying
planes able to carry enough fuel and insecticide to reach the
remote areas.
   A U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration agent in Colombia said
Colombian agents often had to beg U.S. agents for gas for their
cars to go on raids.
   Drug traffickers, on the other hand, have massive amounts of
funds, fleets of helicopters, jets and other planes, private armies
with the latest in submachine guns and other equipment, bulletproof
cars and hundreds of fast boats.
   Fortune magazine last year reported that two Colombian alleged
drug traffickers are among the richest men in the world. It said
Pablo Escobar Gaviria and Jorge Luis Ochoa each have between $2
billion and $3 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
