<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Nuclear     04-04 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Nuclear,0229</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anti-Nuclear Campaigners Demonstrate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALDERMASTON, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 10,000 demonstrators gathered
outside the government's nuclear weapons research center Monday on
the 30th anniversary of Britain's first ``Ban the Bomb'' march,
police said.
   Thames Valley Police Chief Inspector Laurie Fray said it was ``a
mostly quiet and peaceful demonstration,'' although police arrested
four people for criminal damage and public order offenses.
   Defense Ministry police said they arrested six more protesters.
   About 1,000 of the demonstrators walked the 52 miles from London
to the Aldermaston Atomic Weapons Research Establishment in
Berkshire County. They set off from London's Hyde Park on Good
Friday.
   Some of the demonstrators attached paper doves to the six-mile
chain-link fence surrounding the establishment. Others watched
street musicians and entertainers peforming outside the base's
gates or had picnics with their families.
   The Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament, Britain's main
anti-nuclear group, and the Aldermaston Women's Campaign, asked the
demonstrators not to try to enter the base.
   Dick Tomms, 75, who was on the first march to the base in 1958,
was among the demonstrators Monday.
   ``The early Aldermaston marches were very important world events
and we hope that it might get back to being on that scale,'' Tomms
said.
   Organizers had planned to circle the base holding hands, but the
crowd size made it too difficult, they said.
</TEXT>
