<1ST_LINE>r w AM-TreasuryBills     04-04 0170</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Treasury Bills,160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>T-Bills Up In Monday's Auction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on short-term Treasury
securities rose in Monday's auction to the highest levels since
mid-January.
   The Treasury Department sold $6.4 billion in three-month bills
at an average discount rate of 5.98 percent, up from 5.69 percent
last week. Another $6.4 billion was sold in six-month bills at an
average discount rate of 6.21 percent, up from 6.0 percent last
week.
   The rates were the highest since Jan. 19 when three-month bills
sold for an identical 5.98 percent and six-month bills averaged
6.37 percent.
   The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors
_ 6.16 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling
for $9,848.80 and 6.5 percent for a six-month bill selling for
$9,686.10.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said Monday that the
average yield for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index
for making changes in adjustable rate mortgages was 6.78 percent
last week, virtually unchanged from 6.77 percent the previous week.
</TEXT>
