<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Wisconsin-Unions     04-04 0733</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wisconsin-Unions,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Wins Support of Blue-Collar Unions in Wisconsin</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson appears to have won the hearts
of Wisconsin's packinghouse, auto and paper workers _ people he
calls the victims of ``economic violence'' _ but the state's two
biggest unions remain divided going into Tuesday's primary.
   The three blue-collar groups in the past year have suffered
through announcements of plant shutdowns or ongoing attempts to
replace them with strikebreakers.
   Jackson alone among the Democratic presidential candidates has
stood on all of their protest and picket lines, and well before
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis and Tennessee Albert Gore Jr.
stepped foot in the state.
   ``Al Gore visited us and Dukakis showed up at the Labor Temple
in Green Bay last Friday,'' said Roger Murphy, one of 370 mostly
white paperworkers on strike the past 10 months against
International Paper Co.'s mill at DePere.
   ``But they're just reading off the script Jesse wrote,'' Murphy
said. ``Anybody who belongs to any kind of union will vote for
Jackson; he represents our personalities the most.''
   The DePere strike, another by 900 United Food and Commercial
Workers at Smithfield Foods' plant at Cudahy, and Chrysler Corp.'s
plans to close it 5,500-employee Kenosha plant have gotten the
candidates' attention.
   And the 6,770 workers at all three have clearly sided with
Jackson. But there are 220,000 other union workers in Wisconsin,
and their preferences are unclear, according to leaders of their
unions.
   ``The problem is the people who are striking or are in trouble
are the ones who vote, and those who are working don't,'' said Joan
Baggett, political director for the Bricklayers union and a Dukakis
supporter. ``That raises a real question about us getting a
November-electable candidate.''
   Joel Vattendahl, head of the United Steel Workers' 13,000
members in Wisconsin, believes Dukakis will get more of their votes
than Jackson, as does Morris Andrews, exeuctive secretary of the
largest union in the state, the 48,000-member Wisconsin Education
Association.
   ``Jackson is turning on the people who don't normally vote,''
said Andrews, a Gore supporeter and a member of the Democratic
National Convention's platform committee four years ago. ``But he's
coming from behind and we're all over the lot.''
   The American Federation of State, County and Municipal
Employees, with more than 46,000 members in Wisconsin, also is
divided.
   AFSCME is running Wisconsin phone banks for both Dukakis and
Jackson. In congressional districts where there are black
population pockets _ Milwaukee, Madison and Racine _ AFSCME locals
have endorsed both Dukakis and Jackson. In the six other mostly
white areas of the state, its endorsement went only to Dukakis.
   The clear loser, labor activists agree, in Tuesday's balloting
will be Illinois Sen. Paul Simon. Based solely on his win in his
home state primary May 15, Simon now has more labor convention
delegates than any other candidate: 20 according to the AFL-CIO's
latest tabulations.
   Jackson is second with 15, followed by Gore with 10 and Dukakis
with six.
   ``Quite sadly, Wisconsin will show Simon to be yesterday's
tomatoes,'' said Vattendahl of the Steel Workers, a union where
Simon has enjoyed the greatest support.
   The Steel Workers were instrumental in persuading Simon to stay
in the race through the Illinois pimary and had hoped he would do
well enough in Wisconsin to stay in the race through the April 26
primary in Pennsylvania, where the union has its greatest political
clout.
   Vattendahl now believes his union's Wisconsin members will vote
Dukakis and Jackson ``in that order'' Tuesday despite what he
called Jackson's ``willingness to get down with the people.''
   Mark Rosenbaum, president of the UFCW Local P-40 that is
striking the Cudahy plant, has made trips to California to raise
campaign money on Jackson's behalf.
   ``The picket line is white, the strikebreakers are black,'' said
Allen Zack, a UFCW spokeman. ``The company orchestrated letters to
Jackson from scabs saying that he was selling them out. And he
replied a scab is a scab. Our Cudahy people are big Jackson fans.''
   Jackson, likewise has been endorsed by Local 72 of the United
Auto Workers that represents the 5,500 workers at Kenosha after
visiting it right after Chrysler announced in January its intention
to close the plant next summer.
   Both Gore and Dukakis in the past week have denounced Chrysler
Chairman Lee Iacocca, but labor leaders view it as too little and
too late.
</TEXT>
