<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 2025EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-KillerWeed     04-04 0227</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Killer Weed,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Plant-Killing Weed Making Inroads in Western U.S.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dyer's woad, a weed that wages chemical war
against neighboring plants, is infesting parts of the West, the
Agriculture Department said Monday.
   Range scientist James A. Young of the department's Agricultural
Research Service facility in Reno, Nev., said dyer's woad was used
in Europe for thousands of years to make purple dye. Its seeds may
have come into the United States in alfalfa seed from Ireland in
the 1920s.
   In any case, he said in a report issued in Washington, the
3-foot-tall weed has taken hold in California, Oregon, Utah,
Wyoming and Idaho, and it's difficult to eradicate.
   Young became interested in dyer's woad when he noticed it
spreading into northern California fields already infested with
other weeds. Laboratory and field studies showed dyer's woad seed
pods secreted a toxin that killed the roots of nearby grasslike
weeds, including those grazed by cattle.
   The process is called allelopathy _ when one plant species
secretes a chemical that inhibits the growth of another species.
The only way neighboring plants can be saved from dyer's woad is by
spring rains that soak into the ground and flush away the chemical,
he said.
   If the chemical could be synthesized, it might be turned into an
evironmentally safe herbicide, ``but that's all down the road,''
Young said.
</TEXT>
