<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PosnerSentence     04-04 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Posner Sentence,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Challenges Posner's $3 Million Homeless Gift Sentence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sentence that requires industrialist Victor
Posner to make a $3 million contribution to the homeless is illegal
and shows ``the rich can trade money for liberty while the poor
cannot,'' prosecutors said Monday in a challenge to the penalty.
   Posner pleaded no contest to 10 federal tax fraud counts for
inflating the value of land he donated to a religious school, but
avoided prison when he was sentenced Feb. 12 to pay $4 million in
court costs and penalties, plus $3 million to South Florida
homeless programs.
   ``Laudable as the project envisioned by this court may be, we
submit it would disserve and cause disrespect for our system of
justice, and only emphasize that the rich can trade money for
liberty while the poor cannot,'' said U.S. Attorney Leon Kellner in
a motion filed Monday.
   A hearing on Posner's plan for distribution of the $3 million is
scheduled for Wednesday before U.S. District Judge Eugene P.
Spellman.
   Among the conditions imposed by Spellman was that Posner could
not take a tax deduction for the donation and that he could not
file for voluntary bankrutptcy.
   Spellman said he would have no comment on the motion and was
awaiting a response by Posner's attorneys.
   A federal court ``cannot order a convicted defendant to make a
charitable contribution of money to a non-aggrieved person as a
condition of probation,'' said Kellner.
   The court can only ask, not demand, that Posner make the
donation, and cannot incarcerate him if he fails to do so, Kellner
said.
   ``Sadly, we are compelled to observe that this sentence is
illegal,'' the prosecutor said.
   The motion says Spellman stated that if any of the special
conditions were violated, it would result in Posner having to serve
a prison sentence, although the court ``did not indicate what its
sentence would otherwise have been.''
   The government does not believe that Posner's acceptance of the
terms changes the illegality of the sentence, prosecutors said.
   ``The law does not allow an exchange of money for jail time,
even for the benefit of a badly needed societal purpose,'' said the
motion.
</TEXT>
