<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp, 2d Ld - Writethru, a0654,0656</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Bombs and Rockets Oil Centers, Iraq Fires Missile at Isfahan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs, to UPDATE with claim attack repulsed,
edit; picks up 10th `Isfahan has'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran hit Iraqi oil centers with a missile
and air raids Monday in response to attacks on its major
refineries, and Iraq fired a rocket into Isfahan.
   Iran said its artillerymen shelled defensive positions in the
Kurdistan mountains of northeast Iraq, where Revolutionary Guards
have captured a large area around strategic Lake Darbandikhan in a
3-week-old offensive.
   It said Revolutionary Guards and Kurdish guerrillas repulsed
counterattacks by two Iraqi brigades in the battle zone, killing or
wounding 150 men.
   Javier Perez de Cuellar, U.N. secretary-general, is to meet
Iranian and Iraqi envoys in New York this week in search of a
cease-fire in the war, which began in September 1980. The Security
Council passed a resolution July 20 demanding a truce.
   The Iraqis threatened on Monday to level Iran's cities in
revenge for the northern offensive. Iranian invaders are 75 miles
from the Kirkuk oil fields, which account for more than half the
crude oil production with which President Saddam Hussein's
government finances the war.
   A dispatch from Tehran's official Islamic Republic News Agency
said Revolutionary Guards shot a long-range missile at Kirkuk's oil
refinery Monday in retaliation for Iraqi air raids the previous day
on oil refineries in Tabriz and Isfahan.
   IRNA said 22 civilians were killed and 77 wounded Sunday in
Tabriz but gave no report of casualties in Isfahan, the 17th
century capital of Persia.
   Baghdad's official Iraqi News Agency said the missile fired
Monday exploded in a residential neighborhood of Kirkuk, killing or
wounding ``many civilians.''
   Other reports from the agency said Iraq's air force flew 206
sorties against Iranian troop concentrations and bombed oil
installations in Mahshar on the Persian Gulf coast.
   The Iranians reported casualties in Mahshar, but did not give
figures. They said Iraq jets bombed Dezful in western Iran and
Abadan, a southwestern oil center.
   Isfahan has been the target of 12 missiles, including the one on
Monday, since Iran and Iraq began firing long-range missiles in to
each other's cities Feb. 29. Iraq had suspended attacks on Iranian
cities for three days during a visit to Baghdad by Prime Minister
Turgut Ozal of Turkey that ended Sunday.
   A total of more than 250 missiles have been launched by both
sides. Iran has reported more than 1,150 civilians killed and 4,000
wounded. Iraq has not given figures but said there were hundreds of
casualties.
   Reports from IRNA said Iranian fighter-bombers attacked a
petrochemical complex in the battered southern port city of Basra
twice on Monday.
   Iraq's news agency quoted a military spokesman in Baghdad as
saying: ``Because Iran insists on committing more crimes, we shall
pound Iranian cities with missiles and other means until they are
destroyed.''
   Perez de Cuellar is to meet with Iran's deputy foreign minister,
Mohammed Javad Larijani, and Foreign Minister Tariq Aziz of Iraq.
   Akram al-Witri, chief of the legal department at Iraq's Foreign
Ministry, accused Perez de Cuellar on Sunday of having ``vested
interests'' in favoring Iran. He was not specific.
   Last week, Aziz expressed ``bitterness and disappointment at the
biased and ill-balanced nature'' of recent statements by the U.N.
secretary-general on the alleged use of chemical weapons by Iraq.
   Iran claims the Iraqis dropped chemical bombs March 16-17 on
Kurdish towns captured in the northern offensive, killing 5,000
civilians and wounding an equal number.
   Iranian-backed Kurdish guerrillas say hundreds more have been
killed in poison gas attacks on mountain villages.
   Iraq has not denied using chemical weapons, which are outlawed
under a 1925 Geneva agreement, and said March 26 it was ``firmly
determined to use all available capabilities to destroy the
invaders.''
</TEXT>
