<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Romania     04-04 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Romania,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Romanian Negotiators Seek Trade Concessions Despite Rights
Violations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Romania is asking for concessions to offset
the effects of its unilateral renunciation of special trade
privileges with the United States, U.S. sources close to the talks
said Monday.
   The State Department announced that talks were held last week in
Washington with a Romanian trade delegation to assess the effects
of Romania's decision to renounce its Most Favored Nation trade
status.
   The decision, announced in February, means that on July 3 all
Romanian exports to the United States will be taxed as much as 40
percent, compared with 3 or 4 percent previously.
   Romania, which has implemented severe austerity measures,
estimates the lost privileges will cost it $250 million in export
revenues from the United States, which amounted to $775 million in
1987. The Romanians sell the United States wooden furniture, small
engines, leather, textiles and aluminum products.
   The Romanian decision appears to have been motivated by its
reluctance to ease human rights restrictions in return for the
favored trading status, which most other communist countries do not
enjoy. The United States has accused Romania of suppressing free
speech, religious practice and political organizing.
   The U.S. delegation at last week's trade talks ``stressed that
issues of human rights would continue to be a central part of the
U.S.-Romanian dialogue, and that positive movement on such matters
would be an important factor permitting progress in other areas of
our bilateral relations,'' the State Department said.
   The statement also said both sides agreed to hold future
high-level consultations on trade and human rights issues. U.S.
officials refused to further discuss the talks.
   However, two U.S. sources who spoke on condition of anonymity
said Romania had asked for special concessions. The sources did not
elaborate on what Romania had specifically sought during the two
days of talks.
   Romanian Deputy Foreign Minister Olimpia Solomonescu, who led
her country's negotiating team, indicated she had not won any
concrete concessions from the U.S. side, one source said.
   ``But she said she felt it was a good start'' for future talks,
he added.
   While Romania is no longer eligible for U.S. trade concessions,
it has other bargaining chips such as its non-aligned foreign
policy.
   For instance, Romania is the only communist country to have full
diplomatic ties with Israel. ``In the past they've been able to use
this independence from Moscow to win favors here,'' said a source.
   But this may be less effective with the openness of the Soviet
bloc's foreign policy under the glasnost regime of Kremlin leader
Mikhail Gorbachev, he added.
</TEXT>
