<2ND_LINE>AM-Austria-Accident, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0662,0375</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four British Teens Fall To Their Deaths In The Alps</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES throughout with name of school, other detail. No
pickup. ADDS byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four British boys in the Alps for a
school outing left their group while climbing in the snow Monday,
lost their footing and slipped over a precipice, falling hundreds
of feet to their deaths, officials reported.
   Norbert Huber of the air rescue office in Salzburg said six
youngsters set off at lunchtime without skis to climb a mountain
near Untersberg, a village on the border with West Germany.
   Salzburg police said the four boys who were killed apparently
started sliding around in the snow, lost control and went over the
precipice. Police spokesman Alois Wintersteller said it appeared
they were playing.
   Wintersteller said the victims were Andrew Powell-Lee, 15;
Andrew Watts, 14; Michael Taylor, 13, and Daniel Howton, 14, all
pupils of the Altwood Church of England School in Maidenhead, in
Berkshire west of London.
   They were on a school expedition for the Easter holidays, with a
group staying at a youth hostel in Salzburg, he said.
   The four boys apparently ignored a warning from adults and
strayed from a set route, Huber and police said. They said the
party was 4,950 feet above sea level on a 6,504-foot peak.
   ``Nobody was really there to see exactly what happened, so we
don't know,'' said one police spokesman, who asked that his name
not be used. He estimated the snow at more than 6 feet deep where
the teen-agers fell and said the weather was fairly clear.
   The boys' bodies were found after their two companions went down
the mountain and met a teacher. The teacher waited with them for
the missing students and then took a ski lift up the slope to
search.
   Huber said the teacher later notified rescuers and the bodies
were recovered by helicopter. He said the boys fell between 150 and
650 feet.
   Wintersteller said the accident occurred about 2:15 p.m. but
rescue services were not notified until 4:40 p.m. because the
teacher and two boys, unaware of the tragedy, were waiting for the
youngsters to return.
</TEXT>
