<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Scotus-Libel 1stLd-Writethru a0680 04-04 0715</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus-Libel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0680,0735</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CBS News: `Disappointed' By Scotus Ruling In Favor of Cigarette
Maker</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with two grafs, picking up third pvs, and INSERTS 3
grafs after 10th pvs, ``The cigarette maker xxx, with libel expert
saying judgment is a record</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS said Monday it was ``disappointed'' that the
U.S. Supreme Court let stand a record $3 million judgment in a
libel lawsuit brought by a cigarette manufacturer.
   The libel award was the largest ever upheld on appeal, said
Henry Kaufman of the Libel Defense Resource Center in New York City.
   The court, without comment, rejected arguments that the judgment
for Brown & Williamson Tobacco Corp. violated the rights of the
network and Walter Jacobson, anchor for WBBM-TV, a Chicago station
owned and operated by CBS.
   ``We're disappointed,'' Doug Jacobs, associate general counsel
for CBS Inc., said on behalf of the network and WBBM. ``We believed
these issues were important enough for review.''
   ``There's no way that I, with malice or forethought, told a lie
on television. It's never happened and it never will,'' Jacobson
said Monday, adding that the case ``hasn't inhibited me. As long as
I can tell the truth and be fair, I'm not affected.''
   ``We're pleased that the good name of the company and its people
have been vindicated,'' said Michael Bateman, a spokesman for the
Louisville, Ky.-based cigarette maker.
   Brown & Williamson, maker of Viceroy cigarettes, accused CBS and
Jacobson of libeling it in a Nov. 11, 1981, broadcast.
   Jacobson, in a nightly feature called ``Walter Jacobson's
Perspective,'' said there was a Viceroy advertising strategy to
attract young people to smoking by linking cigarettes ``to pot,
wine, beer and sex.''
   He said the idea was to present cigarette smoking as ``an
initiation into the adult world ... as an illicit pleasure.''
   The cigarette maker denied the allegation; it said a
pre-broadcast denial to WBBM-TV was not incorporated into
Jacobson's commentary.
   Kaufman, the libel expert, said the award was nearly four times
larger than the previous standard _ an $850,000 judgment against
the Outlet Co., which he said operated a television station in
Texas.
   He said most multimillion-dollar jury awards against news media
defendants are thrown out or reduced on appeal, with those upheld
averaging between $100,000 and $150,000.
   ``This is the first libel award that has broken through the
psychological $1 million barrier on appeal, the first that has been
able to make it through the process intact,'' Kaufman said.
   A federal trial in the case ended in November 1985 with a jury
award of $5 million to Brown & Williamson.
   In August, the 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Chicago
rejected CBS' arguments that the broadcast was intended as opinion
and thus could not be libelous, upholding $3 million of the award
against CBS and $50,000 against Jacobson.
   The appeals court found the remarks about Viceroy were presented
as factual, even if the tone of the broadcast suggested an
editorial.
   The 7th Circuit also rejected CBS' claim that the broadcast was
truthful.
   In his statements about the marketing strategy, Jacobson cited
what he said was a confidential report prepared by the Federal
Trade Commission. But the court said the FTC report did not make
such allegations and the jury was entitled to find that Jacobson's
broadcast was not a fair summary.
   Finally, the appeals court ruled that Jacobson and CBS acted
with ``actual malice'' in broacasting the commentary.
   For a public figure to win a libel suit, it must be shown there
was actual malice _ that statements were made with knowledge they
were false or with reckless disregard for the truth. The tobacco
company was considered a public figure for purposes of the suit.
   The 7th Circuit court said that after the libel suit was filed,
a researcher for Jacobson destroyed documents that might have
supported the cigarette company's case.
   ``A court and a jury are entitled to presume that documents
destroyed in bad faith while litigation is pending would be
unfavorable to the party that has destroyed the documents,'' the
appeals court said.
   Jacobs, the CBS attorney, contended the original federal court
juy ``put too much stock into the destruction of documents issue.''
   CBS already has paid Brown & Williamson $3.4 million to cover
the libel award and interest.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880404-0134 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 1634EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Meese 2ndLd-Writethru a0679 04-04 1034</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Meese, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0679,930</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meese Faces Internal Ethics Investigation, Sources Say</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 1 graf after 3rd graf bgng: That review ... to add
denial from Shaheen, through department spokesman, that any
examination conducted last year; INSERTS 1 graf after 18th graf pvs
bgng: Shaheen, however ... with Shaheen denying that he had been
contemplating leaving.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Edwin Meese III faces an
ethics investigation by the Justice Department's Office of
Professional Responsibility, department sources said Monday, a
process that ultimately could result in a recommendation to
President Reagan that Meese be fired.
   Investigators in OPR, which monitors potentially illegal and
unethical behavior inside the department, began examining Meese's
ties to longtime friend E. Robert Wallach last year and whether
they constitute unethical conduct, said the sources, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   That review was halted when independent counsel James McKay
launched his criminal investigation of Meese last May 11, the
sources said.
   However, the head of OPR, Michael Shaheen, denied through a
Justice Department spokesman, Terry Eastland, that his office had
conducted such an examination of Meese-Wallach ties last year.
   The files of former Assistant Attorney General William Weld on
Meese's dealings with Wallach were moved to OPR last Friday, said
the sources, confirming a report in Saturday editions of The
Washington Post. Material collected by Weld's criminal division
last year led to McKay's criminal investigation of Meese.
   Upon completion of McKay's probe, OPR is prepared to delve into
whether Meese's actions at Wallach's behest on behalf of
scandal-plagued Wedtech Corp. and a $1 billion Iraqi oil pipeline
may have violated a 1965 presidential order on ethic standards for
executive-branch employees, the sources said.
   McKay said Friday that if he decides not to seek a criminal
indictment of Meese, the independent counsel's office ``will refer
all of those matters for review and action by the appropriate
administrative authorities,'' a reference to OPR.
   OPR has the power to recommend a range of options, including
docking of pay, suspension or dismissal.
   The executive order on ethics prohibits ``using public office
for private gain; giving preferential treatment to any organization
or person; ... losing complete independence or impartiality of
action'' and ``making a government decision outside official
channels.''
   ``From our standpoint based on what we know there has been no
violation by Mr. Meese of any ethical regulation or guidelines in
any of the affairs that the independent counsel has been looking
into,'' said one of Meese's lawyers, James Rocap.
   ``For there to be speculation before the matters have been
referred to these agencies is in my view irresponsible, specious,
unfair and unwarranted.''
   Reagan has made it clear that he is strongly supportive of
Meese, despite the nearly 11-month probe of the attorney general
and the resignations last week of Weld and Deputy Attorney General
Arnold Burns, who reportedly were concerned that the investigation
is hurting the department's operations and its image.
   But any adverse recommendation from OPR's chief, Shaheen, would
be another political embarrassment to the Reagan administration and
produce renewed cries for Meese's resignation.
   Justice Department sources supplied the following instances by
Meese suggesting possible use of public office for private gain,
preferential treatment of Wallach, loss of independence or
operating outside channels in potential violation of the ethics
order:
   _In 1981 and 1982, Wallach sent to Meese's home about a dozen
memos touting Wedtech Corp., which was trying to obtain a $32
million, no-bid defense contract to build small engines for the
Army. Meese interceded on the company's behalf, an act that
culminated with the contract going to Wedtech. Wallach, now under a
racketeering indictment, in the Wedtech scandal, collected $1.3
million from the company from 1981 to 1986. At the time he received
the memos, Meese was White House counselor.
   _In May 1985, Wallach, then representing Swiss oilman Bruce
Rappaport, sought Meese's assistance in boosting the Iraqi oil
pipeline. Meese referred the matter to then-national security
adviser Robert McFarlane, which culminated in a meeting of Wallach,
Rappaport and McFarlane. Meese later advised then-Israeli Prime
Minister Shimon Peres to meet with McFarlane rather than Secretary
of State George Shultz on the pipeline.
   _A $150,000 payment from Rappaport to Wallach wound up being
used for pooled stock trades by Meese's financial manager, W.
Franklyn Chinn. The stock trading got Meese a $40,000 profit on an
investment of just $50,000 in 18 months before the Meese-Chinn
partnership came under fire in Congress last summer and was
dissolved. Wallach had introduced Meese to Chinn, who sat on
Wedtech's board of directors in 1985 and 1986.
   Sources said Shaheen is among a number of Justice Department
personnel who in recent months have been contemplating resigning to
protest Meese's refusal to step down in the face of the ongoing
criminal investigation.
   Shaheen, however, has decided to stay on for now and is
preparing to look into McKay's referral to his office, said the
sources.
   But through Eastland, Shaheen on Monday denied that he had been
contemplating leaving at any point.
   While McKay may decide not to seek an indictment of Meese, he
will compile a report that is expected to provide a mountain of
detail about Meese's involvement with Wallach, according to one
source familiar with the case.
   Such a report would provide a foundation for Shaheen in
evaluating ethical questions, said the Justice Department sources.
   Under Shaheen, OPR found several years ago that Meese's
predecessor, William French Smith, had breached a
conflict-of-interest standard by investing in an oil and natural
gas exploration tax shelter that used a tax benefit calculation
method disapproved by the Internal Revenue Service.
   As a result of another probe by Shaheen's office, Smith in 1984
repaid the government for use of an official car by his wife.
   In a 1980 inquiry, Shaheen concluded that Billy Carter, brother
of then-President Carter, lied to government agents who were
investigating whether he was required to register with the Justice
Department as an agent of the Libyan government.
   Shaheen also said then-Attorney General Benjamin Civiletti
``dissembled'' at a July 24, 1980 news conference at which he
denied any White House contacts on the Billy Carter case. The
following day, Civiletti acknowledged the conversation with the
president.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
