<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Libya-Gadhafi     04-04 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Libya-Gadhafi,0470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gadhafi Dismantles Military Unit Formed To Act In Tunisia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Libyan leader Col. Moammar Gadhafi said Monday he
was dismantling a military unit that was created to act inside
Tunisia if the United States used that country to attack Libya, the
Libyan news agency reported.
   JANA, monitored in Rome, said Gadhafi also told the visiting
Tunisian prime minister and Cabinet that he ordered a division of
troops withdrawn from the border with Tunisia.
   The troops were sent to the border prior to the new Tunisian
government's taking power last Nov. 7, because Gadhafi believed the
United States intended to use Tunisia to attack Libya, the agency
said.
   Prime Minister Hedi Baccouche of Tunisia and his country's
Council of Ministers came to Libya for talks with Libya's Cabinet.
   Gadhafi said he also will insist on ``opening the artificial
borders with Egypt'' and withdrawing military forces from that
frontier as part of his quest for a unified Arab nation.
   JANA quoted Gadhafi as telling the meeting, ``To bolster
confidence, fraternity, security and safety among the brothers in
Libya and Tunisia, I announce the dismantling of the `Badr'
formation, which was to act inside Tunisian Arab territories if
America used ... (Tunisia) against Libya.''
   He was quoted as saying the formation's weapons were being
presented ``as a gift to the Tunisian Arab armed forces.''
   He hailed the Tunisians who came to power Nov. 7 as being
``among those who prevented America from using Tunisian Arab
territories against Libya,'' the agency said.
   He was referring to the removal of 84-year-old President Habib
Bourguiba, who made Tunisia one of the most Westernized nations in
the Arab world.
   Zine el Abidine Ben Ali, an army general and then the prime
minister, said in November that Bourguiba was incapacitated by age
and health and cited a constitutional provision in taking power.
Ben Ali now is Tunisian president.
   Gadhafi also said he was abolishing the border gate with
Tunisia. Starting Monday, ``Arabs in both Libya and Tunisia can
enter and go out without this gate standing in their way,'' JANA
quoted Gadhafi as saying.
   He expressed regret that President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt ``had
rejected the opening of the borders'' and said he would send a
letter to Egyptian parties and organizations demanding the border
be opened, the agency reported.
   ``Whoever refuses to open the borders means that he has not will
at hand, or reflects his fear for the Zionists and the Americans
who fill Egypt's streets,'' JANA quoted Gadhafi as saying.
   ``If the present Egyptian rulers are unable to achieve these
unionist proposals, others will achieve them. Victory will be for
these proposals. As for those who oppose them, they will end in the
dustbin of history.''
</TEXT>
