<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-04 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rain In East And Northwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers were scattered along the East Coast on Monday and over
the Northwest, where snow fell at higher elevations.
   The showers in the East were scattered ahead of a cold front
that extended from the eastern Great Lakes into the southern
Appalachians. Showers and thunderstorms were scattered across
central and southern Georgia.
   The showers over the Northwest were widely scattered. Mullan,
Idaho, received 1.5 inches of rain in 24 hours before the
precipitation changed to snowshowers Monday morning.
   Snow advisories were posted for the Cascades of Washington and
Oregon. Mount Baker and Mount Rainier both received 12 to 14 inches
of snow overnight, which totals up to 50 inches of new snow during
the past two days.
   Bald Mountain at Sun Valley, Idaho, got 4 inches of snow with 5
to 10 inches reported at higher elevations.
   Dense fog persisted into the early afternoon from northeastern
Minnesota into parts of Upper Michigan, cutting visibility to a
mile or less.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 32
degrees at McCall, Idaho, to 89 at McAllen, San Angelo and
Junction, Texas. The low for the day was 16 degrees at Gunnison,
Colo.
   For Tuesday, showers and scattered thunderstorms were forecast
from the Great Lakes region into parts of the middle Mississippi
Valley. Widespread rain was forecast along the northern Pacific
Coast and across northern Maine.
   Highs in the upper 40s and 50s were predicted across northern
New England; in the 50s from the Pacific Northwest through the
northern third of the Rockies, the northern Plains and northwestern
Great Lakes; in the 60s from the northern California coast across
the Great Basin to the central Missouri Valley, central Wisconisn,
Lower Michigan and the eastern Great Lakes to the New Jersey coast;
in the low 90s across southwestern Arizona and from southwestern
into central Texas; and in the 70s or 80s across much of the rest
of the nation.
</TEXT>
