<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Waldheim     04-04 0307</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Waldheim,0314</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Question Report that Waldheim Saved Life of British Pilot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The World Jewish Congress said Monday it found
``highly unlikely'' a report that President Kurt Waldheim of
Austria saved Allied prisoners from execution while he was a German
army officer.
   Bruce Ogilvie, a 66-year-old former fighter pilot, was quoted by
The Sunday Times as saying Waldheim saved him and other prisoners
from being passed to the Nazi SS when he met them on Nov. 19, 1943,
at an airfield outside Athens.
   The British office of the World Jewish Congress said Waldheim
returned to the headquarters of German Army Group E in Arsakli near
Salonika on Oct. 4, 1943, after completing his duties in Athens,
300 miles away.
   It said Waldheim received leave papers Nov. 20 to start a ``rest
leave'' Nov. 23 in Austria.
   ``Due to this chronology, it is highly unlikely that Waldheim
had anything to do with Mr. Ogilvie's story,'' the organization
said in a statement.
   Ogilvie was quoted as saying he was found armed and in civilian
clothes Nov. 17, 1943, on the German-occupied Greek island of Leros.
   He was quoted as saying the Germans took him to an airfield
outside Athens where he met Waldheim, who introduced himself by
name and made sure Ogilvie and others went to a POW camp instead of
to the SS, which shot prisoners.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's government has ordered an
inquiry into the cases of six British commandos executed in 1944
after being delivered for interrogation to the Germany army unit in
which Waldheim served.
   A panel of historians found that Waldheim was ``in close
proximity'' to Nazi atrocities during army service in the Balkans,
knew of them and did not try to stop them, but it left open the
question of whether he committed war crimes. Waldheim has denied
wrongdoing.
</TEXT>
