<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChurchShooting     04-04 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Church Shooting,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Alleged Killer Had Feuded With In-Laws Over A Gate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDNEYVILLE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of shooting his ex-wife's
parents and another person to death during an Easter funeral had
been feuding with his in-laws over a gate they had put up on land
next to his, neighbors said Monday.
   The man's mother-in-law wouldn't give him a right of way,
neighbors said.
   ``From what everyone is saying, they backed him into a corner,''
said Ted Russell, who works at a grocery store.
   Police said 41-year-old Michael Leslie Rainey of Fletcher opened
fire Sunday on mourners gathered for a relative's funeral at a
mountain church nestled among apple orchards and rhododendrons.
   His former in-laws, Wilford Owensby, 61, and Ponnelle Owensby,
60, both of Edneyville, and a 24-year-old man were slain,
authorities said. Three others, including his ex-wife, Andrea
Rainey, 40, of Kennesaw, Ga., were wounded.
   Rainey was charged with three counts of murder and three of
assault with a deadly weapon with intent to kill. He was ordered
held without bail Monday.
   Henderson County District Attorney Alan Leonard said he will
seek the death penalty.
   Sheriff's Capt. Tom Hatchett said the shootings apparently
stemmed from a argument over land in Edneyville, a town about 20
miles southeast of Asheville. Rainey owned land adjacent to
property belonging to Mrs. Rainey's family near the church.
   Rainey had sued the Owensby family in August, alleging the
Owensbys had erected a gate on a driveway extending across their
property and onto Rainey's. He charged that the locked gate
prevented him from getting to motor vehicles that he kept on his
property.
   According to court records, Rainey and his former wife were
given the land by his former wife's grandparents, D.T. and Effie
Justice, in 1979. Sunday's shooting occurred as Effie Justice's
funeral was about to begin.
   Railey won a preliminary injunction in August ordering the
Owensbys to open the gate.
   Nearly everyone interviewed in Edneyville on Monday knew about
the dispute.
   ``His mother-in-law wouldn't give him the right of way. He just
couldn't take it anymore. He had to walk to his own place,'' said
an elderly woman living nearby. She declined to give her name.
   Jim MacKenzie, who owns an auto supply store, said Rainey
stopped by the shop about three weeks ago to say he considering
selling his house and moving away. ``He said all of this was too
much trouble,'' MacKenzie said.
   ``He was a real nice guy, real happy-go-lucky,'' MacKenzie said.
``But anyone can be pushed too far. He was by no means a Charlie
Manson.''
   MacKenzie said Rainey had worked as an installer for Southern
Bell, the telephone company.
   In an interview, Roy Neill, assistant district attorney, said
Rainey was ``dangerous and unstable'' and had shot some victims
more than once, while they were down. ``This was not your
garden-variety murder,'' Neill said.
</TEXT>
