<2ND_LINE>AM-Napper-Gun Control,0284</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Atlanta Public Safety Chief, In Newspaper Ads, Blasts NRA On Gun
Issues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Atlanta's police chief marked the anniversary of
Martin Luther King Jr.'s shooting Monday by condemning the National
Rifle Association and calling for ``sane'' handgun control laws in
full-page newspaper ads.
   Atlanta Public Safety Commissioner George Napper appeared in the
latest in a series of ads placed by Handgun Control, a
Washington-based lobbying group, featuring messages from leading
law enforcement officials.
   In the ad's headline, Napper asks, ``Cop-killer bullets,
mail-order handguns, machine guns ... has the N.R.A. gone off the
deep end?''
   In the text, he urges readers to mark this year's 25th
anniversary of President Kennedy's assassination and 20th
anniversary of the King and Robert Kennedy assassinations by
``sending Congress a message _ America wants sane handgun laws
now!''
   Napper advocates waiting periods for the purchase of handguns
and ``a national, uniform minimum standard of handgun laws.''
   He blasted the NRA's efforts to repeal federal, state and local
gun control laws and its defense of armor-piercing ``cop-killer''
bullets, privately owned machine guns and mail-order gun sales.
   Napper said Monday in a telephone interview that he has ``very
strong feelings about handguns ... the only purpose for a handgun
is to kill people.''
   Handgun Control officials said the Atlanta advertisements cost
them about $16,000, and that the two-year series of advertisements
has cost about $750,000.
   The group's vice-chairwoman, Sarah Brady, is the wife of Reagan
White House press secretary James Brady, who was permanently
disabled by pistol fire from would-be presidential assassin John
Hinckley. Both Kennedy and King were shot with rifles.
</TEXT>
