<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthKorea     04-04 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Korea,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Attack Train as Violent Protests Break Out At Campuses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of radical students fought
riot police in clashes at two Seoul colleges Monday and others were
reported to have attacked a passenger train with firebombs and
rocks.
   At Sungkyunkwang and Konkuk universities in Seoul, hundreds of
riot police fired tear gas to block anti-government students from
marching into the streets. No arrests or injuries were reported.
   In the southern city of Chinju, press reports said a passenger
train was caught in a clash between police and about 1,200 students.
   The Korean news agency Yonhap said most passengers escaped
unhurt, but that a student barrage of firebombs and rocks shattered
at least 300 train windows and destroyed some seats.
   The violence at Chinju followed an anti-government rally at
nearby Kyongsang University, where students were protesting weekend
police action.
   Students said dozens of people were hurt Saturday when police
firing tear gas stormed the Kyongsang campus to disperse about
3,000 students and workers demanding a freer labor movement and a
boycott of agricultural imports.
   About 1,200 students from Hankook University occupied a road in
Seoul's southern shopping center Monday after boycotting a one-week
period of obligatory military training at army barracks.
   They cried, ``Down with the military dictatorship that forces us
to take mercenary training for Yankees!''
   The students denounced the government of President Roh Tae-woo
as a dictatorship.
   They also shouted slogans such as ``Drive out American economic
aggressors!'' They said the Roh government allows such
``aggression'' by accepting U.S. demands to open South Korean
markets.
   Violent campus demonstrations increased steeply in recent weeks
despite democratic reforms proposed by the government. Students
have called for full democracy, but government officials say recent
protests were organized by leftists trying to overthrow the
government by force.
   Roh, who succeeded Chun Doo-hwan as president in February,
pledged to end authoritarian rule but at the same time called for
stern punishment of violent protests to ensure stability.
</TEXT>
