<HEAD>Branstad Plans Active Role In Bush's Iowa Effort</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Terry Branstad, who remained
neutral during Iowa's precinct caucuses, said Monday he has met
with Vice President George Bush about taking an active role in the
likely Republican presidential nominee's attempt to carry Iowa in
November.
   ``I intend to be actively involved in that campaign,'' Branstad
told reporters. He said he met with Bush after Kansas Sen. Bob
Dole, Bush's chief opponent, quit the race and thus virtually
assured that Bush will be the GOP presidential nominee.
   But Branstad said Iowa will not be fertile ground for the
Republicans in the election. ``I think we have to recognize it's
going to be an uphill battle for Republicans in Iowa this year,''
he said.
   Iowa has struggled through years of a farm-based recession, and
Republicans have had problems as Democratic ranks expanded in
protest of GOP farm policies.
   ``We're outnumbered in terms of registration,'' Branstad said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Jackson, Simon Oppose Opening Shoreham Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential candidates Jesse
Jackson and Sen. Paul Simon of Illinois oppose opening the Shoreham
nuclear power plant on Long Island, according to material released
Monday by Sen. Daniel P. Moynihan, D-N.Y.
   ``Shoreham should not be opened, in large part ... because of
the inherent problems of any possible evacuation in the event of an
emergency,'' Simon said in a letter to Moynihan. Jackson spokesman
Hulbert James told Moynihan aides that Jackson is against opening
the $5 billion plant.
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr. of Tennessee and Massachusetts Gov. Michael
Dukakis were more cautious but both said they would support
legislation to forbid the Nuclear Regulatory Commission from
licensing the plant without an emergency evacuation plan approved
by the Federal Emergency Management Agency.
   FEMA has said Long Island could not be safely evacuated without
the cooperation of state and local officials, who have refused to
participate in such planning. However, the NRC changed its own
rules last year to allow it to assume state and local officials
would cooperate in any actual nuclear emergency.
   The candidates responded to a March 31 letter in which Moynihan
asked their position on legislation he offered last year to require
the NRC to abide by FEMA's decision. The bill lost in committee.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Top Iowa Democrats Launch Offensive Against LaRouche Backers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top Iowa Democrats launched an offensive
Monday against backers of political extremist Lyndon LaRouche.
   At a news conference, party leaders said they were worried that
expected low voter turnout in the June primary could be good news
for 16 LaRouche backers who filed as Democrats for legislative and
congressional seats.
   LaRouche backers are the only Democrats who have filed for the
June primary in two legislative districts, meaning they will appear
on the ballot as the Democratic candidates there.
   House Speaker Don Avenson said he'll campaign for the Republican
candidates there. ``I would much prefer to have a mainstream
Republican hold a legislative seat to a LaRouche supporter who has
... conspiratorial theories about the world,'' he said.
