<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FugitiveArrest     04-04 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fugitive Arrest,0367</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hearing Scheduled To Determine Identity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Mexican national being held for removal
to California denied on Monday that he is the man authorities want
to question in the 1985 torture-murder of U.S. narcotics agent
Enrique Camerena Salazar in Mexico.
   Authorities say Leonardo Contreras Subias, 42, also wanted on
drug distribution charges in Los Angeles, has been one of the U.S.
Drug Enforcement Agencies most hunted fugitives.
   ``He's one of our major, major fugitives, because of the drug
charges and also because of the agent's death,'' said Steve Lough,
agent-in-charge of the DEA's Salt Lake City office.
   Lough has said earlier that Subias is wanted only for
questioning and is not a suspect in Salazar's death.
   But the man who appeared in federal court here on Monday said he
is not Subias, but Jose Gonzalez Guillen. The man was arrested
Friday night while having dinner with his wife and children at a
downtown restaurant.
   Lough said the man, reportedly in Salt Lake City several times
in recent months, was arrested on a tip from a DEA task force
investigating Salazar's death.
   U.S. Magistrate Ronald Boyce ordered the man held without bail
in the Salt Lake County Jail until a hearing Thursday to determine
his identity. Assistant U.S. Attorney David Schwendiman said
witnesses are en route from Los Angeles who can positively identify
the man as Subias.
   If his identity is confirmed, authorities will seek to remove
Subias to Los Angeles for questioning regarding Salazar's death and
for prosecution on one count of possession of a controlled
substance with intent to distribute and one count of distribution
of a controlled substance.
   Lough said the charges stem from the alleged sale of cocaine to
an undercover officer in 1980. Each count carries a maximum penalty
of 15 years in prison and a $10,000 fine.
   The defendant, who appeared to walk with a slight limp, asked
Boyce if he could be allowed to continue physical therapy for a
gunshot wound to the leg that still is healing. Boyce said that
would be up to the jail's medical staff.
</TEXT>
