<DOCNO> AP880404-0145 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 2047EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MissileProtesters     04-04 0609</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Missile Protesters,0626</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Protesters Arraigned On Trespass Charges</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmits a0722 to fix spelling of protesters</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By D.W. PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four protesters accused of attacking the
battleship Iowa with hammers, boltcutters and vials of what
appeared to be blood will remain in jail rather than post bond, a
supporter said Monday.
   Longtime activist and former Catholic priest Philip Berrigan,
64, Gregory Boertje, 32, Andrew Lawrence, 28, and Sister Margaret
McKenna, 57, a member of the Medical Mission Sisters, all face
misdemeanor trespassing charges.
   ``They believe that in a corrupt world, their place is in jail.
They are not evading their respnsibility for their actions,'' said
Max Obuszewski. He said the four would not seek to leave jail under
bond.
   The four allegedly boarded the battleship with a tour group
Sunday, then slipped away and attacked two launching boxes holding
Tomahawk missiles.
   Magistrate Tommy Miller explained because the charge was petty
trespassing, the defendants had the choice of trial before a
magistrate or a district judge, but not before a jury.
   Miller set bond at $2,500 and continued the hearing until April
15, when a trial date will be set. No pleas were entered during the
appearance. If convicted each faces a maximum six months in jail
and fine of $500.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney John Martin would not comment on the
charges nor say why trespassing charges were filed rather than the
destruction of government property charges first indicated by
federal officials.
   The felony destruction charges would have given the defendants
the right to a jury trial.
   The four are members of Nuclear Navy Plowshares, an offshoot of
the Plowshares-Disarmament Actions, which has staged numerous
protests on nuclear weapons.
   The group takes its name from Isaiah 2:4, ``and they shall beat
their swords into plowshares, and their spears into pruning hooks;
nation shall not lift up sword against nation, neither shall they
learn war anymore.''
   In a joint statement distributed prior to the hearing by
Obuszewski, a national representative of the Plowshares group, the
four said:
   ``The USS Iowa is not a component, but a symbol of this
superstate madness... So we come to Norfolk bearing blood and
hammers _ symbols of another kind. They are symbols of repentance
and recreation, most appropriate to this season of resurrection and
rebirth.''
   Berrigan, Boertje and Lawrence are from Baltimore, and Sister
McKenna is from Fox Chase, Pa., a Philadelphia suburb.
   Berrigan, a former Josephite priest, first came to prominence as
a member of a group of draft protesters who threw blood on draft
cards May 17, 1968, at a selective service office in Catonsville,
Md., to protest the Vietnam War.
   In 1980, Berrigan, his brother, Daniel, and six associates
entered the General Electric plant in King of Prussia, Pa., and
hammered at Mark 12-A nuclear warheads.
   Boertje has been wanted by the FBI since he failed to show at
his Nov. 17, 1987, sentencing for allegedly damaging military
aircraft at Willow Grove Naval Air Station outside Philadelphia.
   According to the criminal complaint filed Monday by the FBI,
Berrigan and Sister McKenna appeared alongside the Iowa at the
Norfolk Naval Base on Saturday and questioned a sailor about the
ship's armament. Federal investigators said four protesters then
boarded the ship as part of an open house and attacked the two
launchers.
   Capt. Archie Galloway, a Navy spokesman, said the Navy normally
has two ships open to the public over the weekend. He said the four
protesters where apprehended by the ship's crew following their
demonstration.
   The Tomahawk missile, which can carry either a conventional or
nuclear warhead, is launched from surface ships, submarines and
aircraft.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
