<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PolygamistClan     04-04 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Polygamist Clan,0408</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Refuses To Dismiss Some Counts In Polygamist Standoff</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARNI McENTEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge denied a defense motion
Monday to dismiss three counts of a nine-count indictment against
the matriarch of a polygamist clan that held police at bay in a
13-day standoff.
   Vickie Singer is charged along with her son, John Timothy
Singer, clan leader Addam Swapp and his brother Jonathan in the
bombing of a Mormon chapel and the standoff that ended in a gun
battle Jan. 28.
   They are to go on trial Wednesday.
   Addam Swapp was wounded and Corrections Lt. Fred House was
killed when the siege reached its bloody climax at Marion, Utah.
   In the fifth day of pre-trial hearings, Mrs. Singer's defense
attorney, Kathryn Collard, argued that three counts against her
client should be dismissed because the bombed Kamas Stake Center
chapel was not involved in interstate commerce, but rather in
religious activities.
   That would imply that the three counts, which include charges of
bombing, attempting to kill federal officer, firearms violations,
assault and conspiracy, would not fall within federal jurisdiction,
Collard said.
   However, Assistant U.S. Attorney Richard Lambert argued that the
statute was meant to be given a broad interpretation and that a
clause citing federal jurisdiction over ``any'' bombed building
should apply.
   Lambert said the stake center clearly was used for a variety of
interstate commerce activities, including collections that
ultimately go into the church general fund for use throughout the
nation and the world, a linkage to a worldwide satellite system,
and an international missionary network that begins at stake
centers.
   Collard countered that only business-related activities
constitute commerce and that church officials certainly would not
consider their activities as part of business.
   ``They take the position what they do is a furtherance of their
religious mission so they won't be taxed,'' she said.
   The bombing of the Mormon chapel allegedly was in revenge for
the death of Mrs. Singer's polygamist husband, John Singer, who was
killed in a confrontation with authorities nine years ago. Swapp is
married to two of Singer's daughters, and was a leader of the
family along with Mrs. Singer. They blamed the Mormon Church, of
which their group is an offshoot, and police in Singer's death.
   Swapp claimed a violent confrontation at the family's rural
compound would bring about Singer's ``resurrection.''
</TEXT>
