<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Mideast     04-04 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Mideast,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Chief Sees No Consensus on Middle East Peace Conference</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Shultz, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
said Monday he could find no consensus for a Middle East peace
conference as called for by the General Assembly.
   There has been strong support in the United Nations for an
international peace conference that would include the Palestine
Liberation Organization.
   Israel, however, refuses to deal with the PLO, maintaining it is
a terrorist organization determined to destroy the Jewish state.
   The United States also rejects official contacts with the PLO
and while supporting an international conference says it should
only prepare for direct negotiations between Israel and its Arab
neighbors.
   In a report issued Monday, Perez de Cuellar noted the U.S. and
Israeli positions and said ``sufficient agreement does not exist
either amongst the parties directly concerned or with the Security
Council to permit'' an international conference.
   ``Meanwhile, the recent and continuing events in the occupied
West Bank and Gaza Strip have dramatically highlighted the urgent
need for the negotiation ... of a comprehensive, just and lasting
settlement of the Arab-Israeli conflict,'' he said.
   Palestinians in the West Bank and Gaza Strip have been rioting
since Dec. 8 against Israeli occupation.
   The General Assembly passed a resolution in December calling for
a U.N.-sponsored peace conference that would include the PLO and
the five permanent members of the Security Council: the United
States, Soviet Union, Britain, France and China.
   Washington is pursuing its own Middle East peace initiative and
Secretary of State George P. Shultz is now in the region on his
second tour within the past month.
</TEXT>
