<1ST_LINE>u i AM-ColombiaDeaths 1stLd-Writethru a0663 04-04 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia Deaths, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0663,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hooded Gunmen Kill 33 at Colombian Village Easter Festival</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New information and editing throughout, UPDATING with higher
toll, giving survivor's account. No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hooded gunmen encircled about 500 people
at a Easter festival in a village plaza and fired for half an hour
at the screaming crowd, killing 33 and wounding eight, a survivor
said Monday.
   Right-wing death squads in Colombia usually wear hoods. The
attackers at the small village of Mejor Esquina in northern
Colombia also were wearing army uniforms, frequently used by death
squads.
   A survivor, Segundo Benitez, said he counted the dead and
wounded in the Sunday massacre. He said a brother, two nephews and
a cousin of his were among the dead. Benitez said there were 10 to
15 attackers.
   ``The one in charge shouted `Kill everyone you can!''' Benitez
said in an interview with the Colombian radio chain Caracol.
   ``They just shot at everybody, at those who were dancing and
those who tried to run away.
   ``They made a lot of the people lie down on the ground and then
shot them in the head.''
   Benitez said men, women, old people and children were among the
victims.
   Mejor Esquina, in Cordoba state, was celebrating the end of Holy
Week. It is a village of about 600 and lies about 280 miles
northwest of Bogota, the capital.
   Enrique Llorente Lopez, the mayor of the nearby town of
Buenavista, said earlier that about 10 men arrived in vehicles
Sunday night at Mejor Esquina. He had heard that 28 people were
killed.
   Cordoba Gov. Jose Miguel Amin said in a broadcast interview with
Caracol that the police told him they did not know who attacked the
townspeople.
   However, in the town of Planeta Rica, a few miles from the
massacre, someone had painted on a building's walls, ``The
Magnificient Ones are here to clean things up.''
   There are more than a dozen right-wing death squads in Colombia,
with names like the Vampires and the Crickets. The Manificient Ones
was a new name.
   Mejor Esquina is in the heart of a mountainous area where a
left-wing guerrilla group, the People's Liberation Army, has been
organizing lately.
   Sunday's attack was the second massacre in Colombia in a month.
   On March 4, a right-wing death squad fired on sleeping workers
at a ranch in northwest Colombia and killed 20 of them.
   Death squads have killed more than 600 people in Colombia in the
last three years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880404-0154 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 2101EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Nofziger     04-04 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nofziger,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Letters From Cabinet Members, Lawmakers Support Probation for
Nofziger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two members of President Reagan's Cabinet and
four members of Congress have written letters of support for Lyn
Nofziger to the judge who will sentence the former presidential
aide for illegal lobbying.
   The letters from Energy Secretary John S. Herrington and Labor
Secretary Ann McLaughlin were among 62 from current and former
government officials that were filed Monday with a defense memo
that urged Nofziger serve a period of unsupervised probation.
   Letters also were sent by Sen. Chic Hecht, R-Nev.; Reps. Jack
Kemp, R-N.Y.; Helen Delich Bentley, R-Md.; Mervyn Dymally,
D-Calif.; ex-Sen. Paul Laxalt, R-Nev.; and former Health and Human
Services Secretary Margaret M. Heckler, now ambassador to Ireland.
   In one letter, Secret Service director John R. Simpson vouched
for the defendant's reliability and integrity, recalling when
Nofziger became the White House spokesman after President Reagan
was shot on March 30, 1981.
   ``Once Mr. Nofziger took the podium,'' Simpson said he was
quickly aware of ``the rapport and trust the press had for any
statements he made.''
   Nofziger, 63, is scheduled to be sentenced Friday by U.S.
District Judge Thomas Flannery for illegally lobbying on behalf of
Wedtech Corp., a maritime engineers' union and the manufacturer of
the Air Force's A-10 anti-tank plane.
   The former White House political director could receive a
two-year prison term and be fined as much as $10,000 for each of
the three felony convictions for lobbying ex-colleagues within a
year of leaving the president's staff.
   In its filing, Nofziger's lawyers accused independent counsel
James C. McKay of making a ``vindictive'' and ``mean-spirited''
request for imprisonment. The defense said a prison term ``would
unnecessarily add to the degradation and humiliation Mr. Nofziger
has already suffered as a result of his indictment and trial.''
   ``It is inconceivable that a sentence other than probation is
appropriate under these circumstances,'' said the sentencing memo
filed by defense lawyers Robert Plotkin and E. Lawrence Barcella.
   The letters attached to the sentencing memo were from current
and former Reagan administration officials, personal friends and
political associates of Nofziger who vouched for his character and
integrity.
   ``He has always been a man who cares more for the good of a
cause than for personal gain,'' wrote Kemp, who urged the judge to
balance ``the requirements of justice with the quality of mercy.''
   In a three-page letter, Herrington urged Flannery to ``show
compassion and understanding'' for Nofziger.
   ``Society has been paid by what he has gone through in this
trial and the effect that it has had on him as an individual,'' the
secretary said.
   ``Lyn Nofziger will never engage in this activity again in any
way, shape or form, and my fear is that he will probably never
participate in politics again. And I think that will be a shame,''
Herrington said.
   In a memo filed last week, McKay said Nofziger had unjustly
enriched himself after leaving the White House in early 1982,
amassing a current net worth of $2.8 million.
   McKay said Nofziger deliberately ignored the Ethics in
Government Act restrictions on lobbying and showed no remorse after
his conviction in February.
   Plotkin and Barcella said Nofziger's legal bills total $1.4
million and will increase when the conviction is appealed.
   The defense said Nofziger ``does not dispute the need for fair,
clear and balanced post-employment restrictions'' but contended
that if the statute were clearer, ``Mr. Nofziger likely would not
be before the court for sentencing.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
