<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Secrets     04-04 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Secrets,0254</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Art Dealer Held Under Britain's Secrets Act</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scotland Yard announced Monday night that art
dealer Erwin van Haarlem will be charged under the anti-espionage
Official Secrets Act and news reports said the case involved the
KGB and British underwater research.
   London's Daily Express said earlier Monday the arrest involved a
Soviet spy ring seeking sensitive details about how NATO tracks
Soviet submarines heading into the Atlantic from their base at Kola
near Murmansk on the Barents Sea.
   A police spokesman, speaking anonymously in keeping with British
regulations, would say only that van Haarlem will appear in a
London court Tuesday to be charged under the secrets act. Police
released no details.
   Van Haarlem, 43, was arrested in his north London apartment
Saturday and was questioned for two days by Special Branch, the
police department responsible for political security.
   Britain has long been a world leader in underwater warfare
detection methods and the underwater warfare development center at
Portland on the English south coast was the target of a Soviet spy
ring cracked in 1962.
   The Daily Express said Britain's MI5 counter-espionage agency
ordered van Haarlem's arrest after it investigated spying
operations against the government underwater research center at
Bath in western England.
   Other British news reports said that while van Haarlem claimed
to be Dutch-born, he was a Czechoslovak citizen employed by the
Soviet KGB secret police.
   Officials at the Dutch and Czechoslovak embassies in London
denied knowing anything of van Haarlem.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
