<DOCNO> AP880404-0160 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 2223EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Armenia     04-04 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Armenia,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Media Links Dissident and Western Broadcasts to Armenian
Unrest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN GILMOUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet newspaper on Monday linked Western
broadcasts and an Armenian dissident to ethnic violence in the
republics of Armenia and Azerbaijan.
   The Communist newspaper Pravda called Armenian nationalist
Paruyr Ayrikyan, who is under arrest, a ``former criminal who has
engaged in the fanning up of national division.'' It said Ayrikyan
and the Western news media are ``like Siamese twins.''
   Pravda specifically criticized the British Broadcasting Corp.,
the Voice of America and Radio Liberty for their coverage of the
riots and protests in the two Soviet republics and said:
   ``Their masters have their own interest here. They hope to put
an end to socialism by dragging it piecemeal to separate national
compartments. In the same stride they try also to defame
restructuring in our society and the process of its
democratization.''
   Ayrikyan, who was a political prisoner for 17 years, emerged as
a spokesman for activists shortly after Armenians began
demonstrating Feb. 13 for annexation of the Nagorno-Karabakh region
from neighboring Azerbaijan. He traveled to Moscow and held two
news conferences for foreign journalists.
   Western journalists have been barred from traveling to Armenia
and Azerbaijan and telephone calls to the region go through only
sporadically.
   Nagorno-Karabakh has been part of the mainly Moslem Azerbaijan
republic since 1923, although more than three-quarters of the
region's 160,000 residents are Armenians, most of whom are
Christians.
   The annexation issue touched off rioting in the Azerbaijan city
of Sumgait that left 32 people dead. Officials confirmed that most
of those killed were Armenians.
   Instead of agreeing to the annexation demand, the Communist
Party and government offered a $690 million program of improved
housing and social services, such as Armenian language schools and
television broadcasts in Armenian.
   Ayrikyan, 38, was leader of an underground Armenian nationalist
group called the National Unification Party and was jailed for 17
years beginning in 1969 for his political activities. He now is
chairman of the Alliance for National Self-Determination.
   A Foreign Ministry spokesman last week confirmed that Ayrikyan
had been arrested, but said he did not know on what charge.
Ayrikyan's relatives told Moscow dissidents that he was charged
under a law that prohibits spreading of false information
discrediting the Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880404-0161 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 2224EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Venezuela-Fast     04-04 0166</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Venezuela-Fast,0170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hunger Strikers' Health Deteriorates After Three Weeks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two of five hunger strikers who have
been fasting for 22 days in the main hall of the National Congress
are suffering from kidney ailments, a doctor said Monday.
   Two university students, two professors and one university
worker began their fast March 14 in support of a strike by
university faculty members demanding 43 percent salary increases.
   Students Aldrin Torres, 22, and Luis Mendoza, 25, have
``symptoms of kidney infection,'' said Dr. Leon Uzcategui after
examining the five hunger strikers Monday morning. ``Mendoza also
seems to suffer from a liver problem now,'' he said.
   The strike by 40,000 teachers and administrative employees began
in January and has affected nearly 500,000 students.
   A government offer of a 5 percent wage increase was rejected by
the strikers. The government said it could not afford to offer more.
   Salaries for full-time university teachers ramge from the
equivalent of $550 per month to $1,380 per month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
