<DOCNO> AP880404-0162 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 2232EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SmokingBan     04-04 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Smoking Ban,0514</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>In Much of New York, Ban On Smoking Begins Wednesday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sweeping ordinance restricting or banning
smoking in most New York City public places goes into effect
Wednesday, but officials say it may take months to sort out the
rules and effects.
   The measure _ the result of six years of battle _ restricts
smoking in workplaces, restaurants, banks, hospitals, hotels,
theaters, large stores and even taxicabs.
   But enforcement is likely to be clouded by unclear wording in
the ordinance, delays in related regulations and conflicting
messages from the Health Department.
   ``You're talking about a complex social change in a city of 8
million people,'' said Dr. Stephen Joseph, city health
commissioner. ``You don't expect a social change to take place at
the stroke of midnight.''
   Some of the confusion has been sown by Joseph's own department.
It opened a phone line to take questions on the new law, and an
operator mistakenly told a caller last week that the law has been
postponed until further notice.
   Hotel, restaurant and business associations say their members
have been briefed and are prepared to obey, however reluctantly.
   ``For the past few weeks they have been pulling their hair out,
trying to figure out what to do to comply,'' said Cynthia R.
Darrison, head of the Restaurant League of New York.
   Under the ordinance, restaurants with more than 50 seats _ there
are perhaps 5,000 of them _ must ban smoking at half the tables.
   In its most far-reaching section, businesses with more than 15
employees must provide non-smoking work areas designated by signs
and issue written policies on smoking.
   But the regulations for signs are not out yet and the written
policies are not due until July 5, and the result has been
confusion in the business community.
   Irwin S. Davison, Health Department counsel, said the city will
allow a two-month grace period before issuing tickets, which carry
fines up to $500 for repeat offenses.
   Even after June, the department intends the ordinance to be
chiefly ``self-enforcing,'' meaning it hopes the public will keep
employers and shopkeepers in compliance, Joseph said.
   The ordinance defines a smoke-free workplace as one at least
eight feet from a smoker. Some companies call that arrangement too
difficult to configure or enforce.
   The New York Post is banning smoking entirely in its offices; so
will The Associated Press.
   ``We don't feel it's right to allow smoking for people who have
offices and ban it for people who don't,'' said Wick Temple, AP
director of human resources. ``It's a matter of fairness.''
   For restaurants, breaking dining rooms into smoking and
no-smoking areas means regular customers may have to change their
habits if they want their usual tables. And there could be a line
for one area while tables are free in the other.
   ``This is New York. You could have fistfights in restaurants,''
said Ms. Darrison of the Restaurant League.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
