<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NorthKorea-Japan     04-04 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-North Korea-Japan,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>North Korea Says Japanese Sanctions Block Return Of Ship Crewmen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese sanctions against North Korea imposed
after the disappearance of a South Korean airliner last November
have blocked chances for the return of two Japanese sailors held by
North Korea, it was reported Monday.
   North Korea's official Korean Central News Agency said the
Japanese government's attempts to negotiate the return of the
sailors through third countries following its ban on direct
contacts with North Korean officials were a ``shameless and crafty
trick to mislead public opinion at home and abroad.''
   The two crewmen from the ship Fujisan-maru No. 18 were seized in
1983 when the vessel returned to North Korea after an earlier
voyage during which a North Korean stowed away aboard the ship and
disembarked in Japan.
   The crewmen were held for years without trial, apparently to
reinforce North Korean demands for the return of the stowaway, and
then were convicted last year on spying charges and sentenced to 15
years in prison.
   Although Japan has no formal diplomatic relations with communist
North Korea, Foreign Ministry officials said the two sides held
talks several times last year on the fate of the crewmen.
   But in January, Japan imposed sanctions on North Korea,
including restrictions on contacts between official
representatives, following the Nov. 29 disappearance of a Korean
Air jetliner carrying 115 people. The plane disappeared while
flying over Burma and South Korea claimed North Korean agents had
planted a bomb aboard the plane.
   Japan also blamed North Korea, which denied any involvement.
   ``The Japanese government itself blocked the road of the
solution of the crewmen's problem by severing contact between
(North) Korean and Japanese diplomats,'' the Korean Central News
Agency said in a dispatch monitored in Tokyo.
</TEXT>
