<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Panama 2ndLd-Writethru a0738 04-04 0904</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Panama, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0738,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Rebukes Jackson for Contacts with Noriega</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: INSERTS 2 grafs after 11th graf pvs, bgng: ``I remain ...''
to UPDATE with Jackson conversation with State Department; Picks up
12th graf pvs, bgng: ``On Sunday ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reagan administration officials gently rebuked
Democratic presidential candidate Jesse Jackson on Monday for his
contacts with Panamanian strongman Manuel Antonio Noriega,
contending that such communications could prolong his hold on power.
   State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said the
``proliferation of channels is a tactic Noriega likes to use to buy
time.''
   She added: ``We have available channels of communication with
Noriega if and when they are needed. We think it would be best to
continue to use these channels exclusively.''
   Jackson disclosed that he sent a letter to Noriega on March 22
urging him to depart Panama. He said a response he had received
from Noriega will be sent to Secretary of State George P. Shultz
and appropriate members of Congress.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater, traveling with President
Reagan in California, professed bewilderment at Jackson's
activities, saying, ``We haven't heard from Jesse, so we're not
sure what kind of a proposal he has made. ... We just don't know
what he has in mind.''
   Fitzwater said he was confident that Noriega will resign.
   ``The economic sanctions are in place. We think their impact
will be significant, and things are only going to get more
difficult there for Noriega,'' Fitzwater told reporters covering
Reagan while the president vacations at his ranch near Santa
Barbara.
   Jackson, appearing Monday in Milwaukee, renewed his call for
Noriega to leave Panama and released a letter in which Noriega
rejected ``any political and economic program that will be dictated
from Washington, D.C.''
   ``My duration as commander and chief of the defense forces is
governed by the Panamanian constitution and law of the defense
forces,'' Noriega's letter said.
   While releasing the letter, Jackson renewed his call for Noriega
to step down.
   ``I remain convinced that it is in the best interests of the
Panamanian people for General Noriega to leave. Today I reiterate
my public moral appeal for him to depart,'' Jackson said.
   Jackson told reporters he spoke by telephone Monday afternoon
with high-ranking State Department officials who offered no
disagreement with his appeal for Noriega to leave.
   He said the officials _ John C. Whitehead, the deputy secretary
of state, and Michael H. Armacost, undersecretary of state for
political affairs _ made no suggestion that he should tone down his
efforts or be more cautious in dealing with Noriega.
   On Sunday, Jackson had said during a campaign stop in Denver
that he had offered to do whatever he could ``to facilitate''
Noriega's exit from Panama but he ruled out a mediating role for
himself.
   Jackson said a friend, Cirilo McSween of Chicago, had gone to
Panama at his request to meet with Noriega. Jackson described
McSween as a friend of 20 years who was originally from Panama.
   Using rhetoric from his recent speeches, Jackson said U.S.
policy has been misguided:
   ``We've set the forest on fire to smoke one person out,'' he
said, referring to U.S. economic sanctions that have contributed to
a financial collapse in Panama. Jackson said he did not plan a trip
to Panama.
   Fitzwater also criticized Jackson's involvement in the Noriega
matter. ``We have a bipartisan coordinated plan for dealing with
Noriega. That's why it's important to Congress and the public, and
we believe it's been working,'' he said.
   ``Jesse's been involved in a number of these kinds of mediation
efforts. He's offered to go to Libya and Cuba and all kinds of
places,'' Fitzwater said.
   Asked about published accounts over the weekend in which deposed
Panamanian President Eric Arturo Delvalle rejected any notion of
U.S. military force to get Noriega out, Fitzwater replied, ``He
says that because he thinks the economic sanctions are working,
that we just need to give these things a chance to kind of
percolate through the system, rather than try to take any more
action.''
   Fitzwater reiterated that the United States plans no further
immediate steps beyond the economic sanctions and the deployment
Tuesday of an additional 1,300 U.S. military forces to the troubled
country.
   He said the troops were ``to reinforce our security efforts in
Panama, to make sure we have the capability of protecting American
citizens there if that should become necessary. But there's no
steps beyond that at this point.''
   Mrs. Oakley, meanwhile, escalated the administration's criticism
of Panamanian authorities over an incident Sunday in which U.S.
Ambassador Arthur Davis was pursued for two miles in Panama City by
a government military vehicle with its siren blaring.
   ``We consider any threat to the safety of the ambassador to be
serious as always,'' she said. ``We will take the necessary steps
to protect Americans. I am condemning the incident from the podium;
we regard the action as deliberate harassment.''
   Embassy spokesman Terence Kneebone said Davis was leaving the
home of Vatican Ambassador Jose Sebastian Laboa when the Panamanian
vehicle ``began following immediately, picking them up right
outside the gate.'' He said it tried to stop the chauffeur-driven
car with its lights and sirens.
   ``The ambassador's driver, in accordance with instructions, did
not stop. The ambassador was driven to his residence, and the other
vehicle followed all the way,'' Kneebone said. The residences are
about two miles apart.
</TEXT>
