<HEAD>Simon Makes Labor Pitch In What Could Be Last-Stand State</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By P.B. SEYMOUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Paul Simon campaigned in a motorcycle
factory Monday, in a final bid to rev up his faltering presidential
bid in time for the Wisconsin Democratic presidential primary on
Tuesday.
   ``I'm going to do well here tomorrow,'' insisted Simon. But
polls have suggested he is running well behind Massachusetts Gov.
Michael Dukakis and Jesse Jackson.
   Simon has indicated he needs a good showing in Wisconsin in
order to continue his campaign. His only victory has come in his
home state of Illinois.
   Voters, Simon said, should send this message: `We're not going
to follow the pollsters; we're going to elect the man best
qualified to be president.''
   ``Al Gore agrees with that too,'' Simon added, referring to Sen.
Albert Gore. Jr of Tennesse. Polls indicate Gore, like Simon, is
lagging behind the two front-runners.
   ``There's no question the pollsters have shifted to a
Jackson-Dukakis race, partly because of what happened in
Michigan,'' Simon said.
   Jackson scored a 2-1 victory over Dukakis in Michigan on March
26.
   Simon shook hands with workers at Harley-Davison Co., the
nation's largest domestic producer of motorcycles. He noted
government revisions on import rules are credited with helping the
company improve its share of the American market in the face of
Japanese competition.
   The International Trade Commission's role in helping commerce
and employment could be strengthened, Simon said.
   ``We've had bankers and academicians and all sorts of people;
what we need is some labor representation on that commission,'' he
said.
   Simon was asked his opinion of Jackson's tactic of making
appearances in Kenosha, De Pere and other Wisconsin cities, in
sympathy with workers on strike or facing layoff.
   He said he does not want to criticize Jackson but said of his
rival's strategy: ``There is no question it is based in part on
rhetoric and not on programs.''
