<DOCNO> AP880404-0171 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 2250EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DeathScreen     04-04 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Death Screen,0504</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UF Lab Uses New X-Ray Video Technique to Identify Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A University of Florida lab says it is
using video equipment to identify the remains of crime victims in a
technique more sophisticated than that used in the case of Nazi
death-camp doctor Josef Mengele.
   Forensic anthropologist William R. Maples, who works at UF's
Florida State Museum, said Monday he superimposes on a video screen
X-rays of the victim's skull and photographs taken during his or
her lifetime.
   In one recent case, Maples said, the method allowed the
identification of a girl who had never had a medical or dental
X-ray taken in her life. Such X-rays often are used to identify a
victim with a high degree of certainty.
   By superimposing the girl's class picture and an X-ray of the
skull, Maples could precisely align the teeth, jaw bone and
openings for the eyes, ears and nose.
   ``Without this technique, the only evidence we have is the
general age, sex, race and height of the body, and that the
skeleton was found shortly after the girl disappeared,'' Maples
said. ``That's not very convincing.''
   The museum's C.A. Pound Human Identification Laboratory is the
only one in the country with such equipment, he said.
   Experts had questioned the identification of Nazi war criminal
Mengele in Brazil in 1985 because comparisons were made between
photographs of Mengele as a young man and those of an older man
presumed to be him. Dental evidence later established the skeletal
remains as Mengele's, Maples said.
   Photographs and skulls were manually superimposed in the
darkroom as early as the 1930s, but forensic experts often settled
for inexact results because of the dozens of tries required to
align the two images, he said.
   Video equipment has been used in the 1980s with little success
because most of the work was done by studio technicians not trained
in forensics, he said.
   Maples said the comparison of photos and X-rays on
high-resolution video equipment is an important tool.
   ``We can't rely on dental X-rays alone because there may be
none, people may have lost their teeth years after the X-rays were
taken or teeth may be destroyed in a fire, plane crash or other
disaster,'' he said.
   Maples said the technique confirmed his identifications in a
case in which a man and woman's skeletal remains were found in a
burned shack in High Springs.
   A suicide note in an abandoned car nearby linked the couple with
the slaying of the woman's parents in New Hampshire, and Maples
said he was able to confirm their identities by comparing teeth and
bone fragments from the fire with X-rays of the couple's teeth and
bones.
   The New Hampshire attorney general's office agreed with the
identification of the woman but isn't convinced in the case of the
man. Prosecutors there are keeping open murder warrants against the
man, citing the possibility he faked his suicide.
 
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880404-0172 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 2251EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Gulf     04-04 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Gulf,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Asks U.N. Probe of Alleged Chemical Attacks by Iran</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Rdp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq said Monday it wants a U.N. team to
go to Baghdad to examine 88 soldiers it claims are victims of an
Iranian chemical attack.
   A U.N. spokesman said the request was under consideration.
   Last year a U.N. team visited Iraq and reported it found no
evidence that Iran had used chemical weapons. Its report left open
the possibility the Iraqi soldiers were accidentally injured while
handling their own chemical weapons.
   Other U.N. teams that visited Iran said they found evidence that
Iraq had used both mustard gas and nerve gas several times in the
Iran-Iraq war that began in September 1980.
   Iraqi Foreign Minister Tariq Aziz asked for a U.N. inspection
team in a letter to Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar, who
sent investigators to Iran last month to investigate Iranian
charges against Iraq.
   Aziz said Iranian warplanes and artillery carried out chemical
attacks on Iraqi positions on March 30-31 near Halabjah in the
northern Kurdistan region.
   Iran has accused Iraq of using chemical weapons in the same
general area.
   Aziz said 88 Iraqi soldiers gassed in the attacks are now
hospitalized in Baghdad, the capital. ``The Iraqi government
requests your excellency to send a mission immediately to Iraq to
see the wounded and to get acquainted with the details of the
aggression,'' his letter said.
   Iran has denied using chemical weapons, which were
internationally outlawed after World War I. It has frequently told
the United Nations that Iraq is using the banned weapons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
