<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FakePardon     04-04 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fake Pardon,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Rules Against School Hostage-taker</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOYT HARWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge on Monday rejected a
request that he free a gunman who took 84 people hostage in a
school at Tuscaloosa then surrendered after getting a purported
pardon from the governor.
   ``The public interest is not served by allowing someone to
profit by his own misconduct,'' U.S. District Judge Sam Pointer Jr.
said in dismissing a complaint by James Harvey's public defenders.
   Harvey put down his guns and surrendered after a 12-hour siege
Feb. 2 at West End Christian School, shortly after he was shown a
videotape of a phony pardon by Gov. Guy Hunt.
   Pointer said after a 60-minute hearing that Harvey had no legal
right to keep hostages or to refuse to surrender.
   The judge also said Hunt had no right to grant pardon or
immunity, since the state has a board for that purpose.
   One of Harvey's attorneys, Mike Cornwell, had argued that the
governor used means that ``cause dishonor to society.''
   He said the court should ``hold the governor to a higher level
of integrity than was shown that day.''
   Attorney General Don Siegelman told the court any agreement
between Hunt and Harvey was not binding and that enforcement of it
was not a constitutional right.
   ``Criminals have no legal right to negotiate by threatening the
lives of children,'' he said. ``The state, however, does have a
right to give false promises when necessary to protect the lives of
innocent children.''
   A Siegelman assistant, Susan Russ, said it was ``important to
vindicate the right of the governor to do what he did.''
   She also said that no pardon can be granted until a person is
convicted.
   Bargaining, she said, ``is nothing more than a law enforcement
tool. The governor could have used deadly force as a tool.''
   Hunt, Ms. Russ said, was the one being pressured because Harvey
was holding the children hostage.
   She said the ``contract'' by Hunt should not stand ``because it
was obtained under duress.''
   Ms. Russ also said Hunt had no option, that he was ``almost
forced to make this promise to avoid possible bloodshed.''
   Ms. Russ said Harvey still has all his rights to a fair trial.
   Albert Miles, an assistant to Cornwell, contended that Harvey
``had a fundamental right to trust the word of the government.''
   After Pointer's ruling, Cornwell gave notice that he plans to
appeal.
</TEXT>
