<HEAD>Reagans Attend Luncheon for Planned Presidential Library</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New in first four grafs to UPDATE with Reagan arrival and
departure. Picks up 5th graf pvs bgng: The Ronald ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LAGUNA NIGUEL, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan and his wife,
Nancy, left their vacation ranch Monday and attended a luncheon
with financial supporters of a planned Reagan library.
   The reception and luncheon were given by supporters of the
Reagan Library Foundation at the estate of developer Gen. William
Lyon in Laguna Nigel, an Orange County community south of Los
Angeles.
   Some 75 supporters of the presidential library greeted the first
couple at Lyon's sprawling colonial mansion, set back hundreds of
yards from the road. Reagan, arriving by helicopter in a field
nearby, declined to answer questions from reporters, pointing at
his watch to suggest he did not have time to stop.
   The president also di not comment after the luncheon as he
boarded the helicopter for the return flight to his ranch near
Santa Barbara.
   The Ronald Reagan Presidential Library will be built in the Simi
Valley, northwest of Los Angeles in Ventura County. Library
planners earlier were forced to abandon a site at Stanford
University in Palo Alto because of widespread protests there.
   Since then, the Los Angeles real estate firm of Blakeley-Swartz
donated a 100-acre site near the community of Simi Valley for the
library. But the site impinges on a greenbelt area that is
protected from large-scale development by a decade-old, non-binding
agreement among Simi Valley, Moorpark and Thousand Oaks.
   Mrs. Reagan was driven to the new site during a California
vacation last August, and approved it. The president gave his
approval after flying over the site, the library planners said.
   The Reagans, in the fourth day of a planned 10-day California
stay, did not venture from their 688-acre ranch near Santa Barbara
on Sunday.
</TEXT>
