<2ND_LINE>AM-Lobster Rescue, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0602,0557</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Big Old Lobsters Headed Back To Sea _ Hopefully</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with lobsters arriving in Maine, quotes,
details. New byline.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Precede PHILADELPHIA</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVA PARZIALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 25-pound lobster with claws the size of
baseball mitts that was saved from becoming an Easter dinner
arrived in Maine on Monday on the final leg of a roundabout journey
back to the sea.
   Maine marine officials gently placed ``Shirley,'' a male
estimated at 40 to 125 years, and a 19}-pound companion lobster
into a 600-gallon tub of icy saltwater after their flight from
Philadelphia. Freed from their ice-packed travel boxes, the
lobsters immediately began moving their giant claws around.
   ``Very good, he's moving around already. That's a good sign,''
Col. Robert Fogg, chief of the Bureau of Marine Patrol of the Maine
Department of Marine Resources, said of Shirley. ``A real weak
lobster would be very lifeless.
   ``They're excellent. I'm pleased with the way they've shown up.''
   Marine officials planned to return the crustacean behemoths to
the Atlantic early Tuesday off Cape Elizabeth if they remained
healthly overnight.
   ``This is symbolic of what we're trying to do and what citizens
are trying to do for a natural, sustainable resource,'' Fogg said.
``By protecting these large lobsters, there's more of a chance of
them reproducing'' and perpetuating the industry.
   Maine law protects lobsters with body shells longer than five
inches, covering lobsters larger than 4 to 5 pounds.
   If the lobsters' health deteriorated during the night and they
could not be saved, Lt. Joseph Fessenden of the Maine Bureau of
Marine Patrol said the largest would be turned over to the Maine
State Museum.
   ``They're looking for a lobster to stuff,'' he said.
   Shirley and the companion lobster had been trucked to
Philadelphia from Long Island, N.Y., and sold for $287. After
crustacean rights advocates took up the cause, Kevin Hill, owner of
Hill's Main Line Seafood Co. in the suburb of Ardmore, persuaded
the buyer to take 45 pounds of smaller lobsters instead.
   Hill put the lobsters in a window tank for the rest of their
visit to Philadelphia's Main Line. He acknowledged that saving
lobsters from dinner palates was something new for him, ``which is
all right.''
   He also said that the lobsters had been good business, as
thousands of peole dropped by for a look at Shirley.
   ``It's been very good for business. If they don't buy now, at
least they know where we are,'' said Hill, who planned to travel to
Maine to be on hand for the lobsters' release into the Atlantic.
   Hill delayed packing the lobsters for their trip until the last
possible minute. ``Believe it or not, I'm still getting people
coming by the window to look at 'em,'' he said Monday.
   Pity Not Cruelty Inc., a small animal rights group, made
arrangements with Maine officials to turn the creatures loose and
assumed the $40 flight cost.
   If it seems to be a lot of fuss over a couple of lobsters, group
vice president Gloria Felscher-Cohen makes no apologies.
   ``Why not? These two lobsters have survived hazards,
particularly Shirley, over 100 years,'' she said. ``Why should she
need to succumb to the cruelest predator of all, man?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880404-0177 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 2119EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Wedtech     04-04 0531</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wedtech,0551</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wedtech Witness: We Tried to Sell to Iran, Iraq and Saudi Arabia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Wedtech Corp. executive testified
Monday that the scandal-plagued defense contractor tried
unsuccessfully to sell military equipment to Iran, Iraq and Saudi
Arabia.
   The negotiations to sell bridge pontoons and other supplies
eventually fell through with all three nations, said former Wedtech
Vice Chairman Mario Moreno.
   Moreno, in his 14th day of testimony at the racketeering trial
of Rep. Mario Biaggi, D-N.Y., and six others, was questioned by
defense attorneys about Wedtech's Middle East dealings.
   The jury was not present during questioning on that topic and
U.S. District Judge Constance Baker Motley later ruled it
inadmissible.
   The judge said the testimony would unduly prejudice the jury
because there was no evidence a crime had been committed.
   In other testimony, the defense tried to throw some doubt on
Moreno's previous testimony that Biaggi had demanded 5 percent of
Wedtech's stock in return for his law firm's assistance in
obtaining no-bid government contracts.
   They pointed out that in a February 1987 interview with federal
prosecutors, Moreno said another Wedtech official wanted to give
the stock to the Biaggi and Ehrlich law firm in exchange for unpaid
legal services.
   Biaggi, his former law partner Bernard Ehrlich and five others
are charged with turning Wedtech, a now-bankrupt, Bronx defense
contractor, into a racketeering enterprise that paid out millions
of dollars in bribes.
   Wedtech grew from a small machine shop into a multi-million
dollar manufacturer through a federal program that set aside
contracts without competitive bidding for companies controlled by
minority group members.
   Prosecutors claim Biaggi and others helped Wedtech falsely
portray itself as a minority concern eligible for the no-bid
program.
   Defense attorney Dominic Amorosa asked Moreno if Wedtech had
acted on behalf of the U.S. government in the Middle East.
   ``No, we were acting as Wedtech,'' said Moreno, one of four
ex-Wedtech executives to plead guilty to state and federal
corruption charges.
   The witness said Wedtech sought to sell military equipment to
Iran in 1982-1983 and to Iraq in 1984-1985, adding, ``We believed
we could do it legally.''
   ``You knew you could never legally have gotten an export license
(to sell military equipment)?'' asked Amorosa.
   ``It crossed my mind,'' said Moreno.
   Asked if E. Robert Wallach, a close friend of Attorney General
Edwin Meese III, had said he could help obtain export licenses,
Moreno replied: ``It never got to that point.''
   Moreno previously testified that Wedtech paid Wallach $800,000
for his ``influence with Ed Meese'' although no wrongdoing by Meese
has been established.
   Moreno also said a former Meese financial adviser, W. Franklyn
Chinn, was helping with Wedtech negotiations with the Iraqis.
   ``Chinn was a conduit in trying to sell arms to Iraq,'' said
Moreno.
   ``I've never heard this allegation before, and I continue to
deny that Frank Chinn has engaged in any illegal conduct,'' said
Cristina Arguedas, Chinn's lawyer, when called at her Berkeley,
Calif., office.
   Both Wallach and Chinn are under indictment with a third man,
Chinn business associate R. Kent London, accused of extracting
payoffs from Wedtech for allegedly influencing Meese and other
officials.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
