<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Talib-Rasul Hakim</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Talib-Rasul Hakim, a composer and music
educator, died Saturday. He was 48.
   Hakim trained in piano, clarinet and composition at the
Manhattan School of Music, and studied at the New School of Social
Research, both in New York City. His compositions have been
performed by symphony orchestras throughout the country, including
those in Detroit, Atlanta, Dallas, Denver, Houston, and the
Washington, D.C., Youth Orchestra Program.
   Among his works is ``Birmingham Reflections,'' commissioned by
the New Haven Symphony Orchestra to honor the late Dr. Martin
Luther King. The work premiered in 1986.
   He has also taught, lectured or been a consultant at a number of
colleges, including Hofstra University, the University of
Connecticut, Barnard College, Bowdoin College, Hofstra University,
and Pace College.
