<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Reagan-Meese 3rdLd-Writethru a0784 04-04 0892</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Meese, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0784,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Plans Scuttled For Weld Replacement; Burns' Successor In Doubt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: New in first 14 grafs to UPDATE with Adams in interview
saying he might not take job, other details. Picks up 10th graf pvs
bgng: Meese had ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration on Monday scuttled
Attorney General Edwin Meese III's plans to designate a Justice
Department deputy as the new head of the criminal division, sources
said, and Meese's choice for the department's No. 2 post said he
may not take the job.
   The two men were to have filled posts being vacated because of
the resignations of two of Meese's top aides.
   Arlin Adams, the Philadelphia lawyer who had been the attorney
general's choice to fill the Justice Department's No. 2 post, says
he told Meese on Monday that he is ``not optimistic'' that he will
be able to take the job.
   In an interview, Adams said that his colleagues at his law firm
``take a very dim view of my leaving at this time'' because he is
handling an extensive caseload in Philadelphia, including a major
antitrust case, and ``I don't want to leave the firm in the lurch.''
   Adams, who would be succeeding Deputy Attorney General Arnold
Burns, pointed out that he resumed private practice just last year
after stepping down from the 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
   ``I've not made a decision (on whether to accept the Justice
Department post), but I'm not optimistic and I told the attorney
general that today,'' said Adams.
   Meanwhile, a Justice Department source speaking on condition of
anonymity said that James I.K. Knapp, 45, a deputy assistant
attorney general in the department's tax division, is being removed
from consideration to fill the post formerly held by Assistant
Attorney General William Weld.
   The White House on Friday held up Meese's plans to announce the
replacements for Weld and at least one other aide, pending
completion of background checks.
   Department sources declined to say why Knapp's name was being
removed from consideration, and a reporter's telephone messages
left at Knapp's home were not immediately returned.
   A Justice Department news release had been prepared last week
containing Knapp's name as Meese's choice for the post, said the
sources.
   Burns and Weld resigned out of concern that the 11-month-old
criminal investigation of Meese was hurting the Justice
Department's operations and image.
   Asked whether he had any qualms about serving under Meese, Adams
said that ``I look at the job as serving the United States
government and the Department of Justice; I really don't know the
background'' of the allegations concerning Meese.
   Of the investigation of Meese, he said that ``It would be much
better if that did not exist, but that is not dominating my
decision.''
   He said that when Justice Department officials ``called me down
(to Washington on Thursday), almost right away I told them that I
was honored to be asked.''
   Meese had been prepared on Friday to announce the replacement
for Weld and at least one other top Justice Department vacancy, the
post held by Associate Attorney General Stephen Trott, who is
leaving to become a federal appeals court judge.
   Francis A. Keating II, assistant Treasury secretary for
enforcement, is to take the No. 3 department job being vacated by
Trott, Justice Department sources said late last week.
   Earlier Monday, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said that
``We have received some names. We are processing the normal FBI
clearances, but there's nothing out of the routine.'' Fitzwater
made the comments in Santa Barbara, Calif., as President Reagan
vacationed at his nearby ranch.
   Meese, who is the subject of criminal investigations, is trying
to rebuild the top echelon of the Justice Department in the wake of
the resignations of Burns and Weld.
   Asked Monday if there had been any high-level White House
discussions of the political ramifications of Meese's legal
problems, Fitzwater said, ``No.''
   He also said ``I don't know of any plans'' for Reagan to discuss
the subject directly with Meese, his longtime friend and aide.
   Of the choices to succeed Burns and Weld, who resigned last
Tuesday, Fitzwater said: ``There are some names that have been
floating around in the press, but at this point we have not
received formal nominations.''
   The candidates to succeed Burns, Weld and Trott will ``go
through the White House and the president will announce his
intention to nominate,'' Fitzwater said.
   Meese is leaving the country Wednesday for a week-long trip to
South America to speak to officials there on drug-related matters.
   Independent counsel James McKay, who has been conducting a
criminal investigation of Meese since last May 11, said Friday he
did not plan to seek an indictment of Meese, ``based on the
evidence developed to date.''
   This news heartened Reagan, according to White House officials,
who noted that the president has steadfastly supported his
embattled attorney general.
   But two White House officials were quoted in the Los Angeles
Times Monday as saying they thought Meese should step down.
   These officials, who were not named by The Times, said the
attorney general had become a political liability for Reagan and
for the Republican Party.
   They said they were discussing the Meese situation despite
orders by White House chief of staff Howard H. Baker Jr. to
maintain silence on the matter.
</TEXT>
