<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MoundsvilleEscape 2ndLd-Writethru a0741 04-04 0669</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Moundsville Escape, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0741,0688</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Escaped Police Killer Prompts Worry, Manhunt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 18 to end, bgng `The men ...,' with 7 new grafs to
UPDATE with details of escape. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOUNDSVILLE, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge and a witness were given
police protection Monday after a vengeful cop killer described as
``educated and cold-blooded'' broke out of a maximum security
prison along with two other murderers.
   Bobby Stacy, 35, and two other inmates serving life sentences
without chance of parole escaped from the West Virginia
Penitentiary here on Sunday.
   ``My fear is that some police officer is going to get killed,
because that's this guy's method. He has nothing to lose, plus it's
his history,'' said Charles Hatcher, the assistant Cabell County
prosecutor whom Stacy had threatened.
   Stacy, formerly of Columbus, Ohio, was convicted in the 1981
murder of a Huntington police officer. At the time of the slaying,
he was free on bail on charges that he shot an Ohio patrolman.
   Police immediately assigned protection to some of those who
helped convict Stacy. Stacy repeatedly threatened to kill the judge
and the prosecutor at the 1982 trial, according to Huntington
police Lt. Joe Walker.
   ``He is educated and cold blooded. That's the worst combination
there is,'' Hatcher said in Huntington, 160 miles south of the
prison. He said he had no plans to ask for protection for himself.
   Stacy was a successful businessman who used the money from his
crimes for business ventures. When he was arrested, he owned a bar,
at least two houses and several automobiles.
   Roadblocks were set up on routes leading into Ohio and
Pennsylvania, which borders Marshall County, where the prison is,
to the east.
   State police in West Virginia, Ohio and Pennsylvania, as well as
sheriff's deputies, combed the countryside, said warden's secretary
Jerrie Clutter.
   Circuit Judge Alfred E. Ferguson, who asked that an extra
sheriff's bailiff be assigned to him, said he was concerned about
his safety. ``I'll be more worried if he is out for awhile,''
Ferguson said in Huntington.
   Also under protection was an unidentified Columbus, Ohio, woman
and former friend of Stacy's who had testified against him, said
Columbus police Officer Clarence Ward.
   ``If anyone has to fear, she does,'' Hatcher said. Her car was
torched and she received death threats during the trial, he said.
   Hatcher said he was offered police protection but turned it down.
   ``Let's face it, if somebody wants to kill you, they're not
going to announce it and swing into town,'' he said. ``They're
going to do it at a red light, or through your kitchen window.''
   Huntington police officers, who usually patrol alone, worked in
pairs Monday.
   ``A suspect is less likely to shoot that way,'' said Lt. Toby
Shy.
   Stacy, David Williams, 28, and Tommie Mollohan, 45, were
discovered missing during a routine check Sunday night, officials
said.
   Warden Jerry Hedrick said Monday the inmates, all maintenance
workers, knocked a hole in a wall of an elevator shaft in the
infirmary to gain entrance to a shed where bolt cutters were kept.
   Then they climbed through another elevator shaft, this one in an
unused building, to the second floor, where they used pipe and a
cord to lower themselves to the ground, he said.
   The escapees hid behind ventilation equipment, then used the
bolt cutters to cut through a lock on a gate and flee, he said.
   Hedrick said evidence indicated the escapees had outside help.
He said bloodhounds tracked their scent across the street to a
museum parking lot, where the trail disappeared.
   ``It obviously was well-planned. Therefore we have got to assume
plans were also made for the outside once they got out,'' said
Corrections Commissioner A.V. Dodrill.
   Mollohan was convicted of robbing and then killing a Brounland
grocer in 1973. Mollohan at the time was an escapee from a Florida
prison.
   Williams was convicted of murder, arson and robbery in the 1980
slaying of a Marytown resident found bludgeoned in his burned home.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
