<DOCNO> AP880404-0186 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 2227EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Cotap-Morison 1stLd-Writethru a0685 04-04 0637</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cotap-Morison, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0685,0648</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Espionage Conviction Upheld In Satellite Photo Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS two grafs aftr 7th ``Prosecutors said'' to UPDATE
with ACLU comment. Picks up 8th graf pvs, ``Defense attorneys.''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOE TAYLOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court refused Monday to
reverse the espionage and theft convictions of a former U.S.
intelligence analyst who gave secret satellite photographs of a
Soviet ship to a British magazine.
   A three-judge panel of the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
unanimously rejected Samuel Loring Morison's arguments that
Congress intended laws against spying to protect against the
distribution of classified material to a foreign government rather
than leaks to the press.
   Several news organizations _ including The New York Times, The
Washington Post, The Wall Street Journal and three television
networks _ filed briefs in the appeal, which focused on First
Amendment guarantees of free speech and freedom of the press.
   Morison, grandson of the late Pulitzer Prize-winning naval
historian Samuel Eliot Morison, was convicted in October 1985 of
giving to Jane's Defence Weekly photographs taken by a U.S. spy
satellite of a Soviet nuclear aircraft carrier under construction.
   Morison, who worked as a civilian for the Navy, also was
convicted of the theft of the photos and government documents
describing a May 1984 explosion at the Soviet Union's Severomorsk
naval base.
   He was sentenced to two years in prison but has been free under
$100,000 bond pending the appeal.
   Prosecutors said Morison's actions endangered national security
because the photos revealed how a U.S. spy satellite worked. They
also said he leaked the photos to get a full-time job with Jane's
after doing part-time work for the military journal while employed
by the Navy.
   The American Civil Liberties Union denounced the appeals court
decision.
   ``The decision poses a grave threat to the First Amendment,''
said Kate Martin, speaking for the civil liberties group in
Washington, D.C. ``It will signficantly cut off public debate on
issues of national security. If the decision stands, it may
criminalize much of what is printed daily in newspapers on national
security matters.''
   Defense attorneys contended Morison was trying to educate the
public about a Soviet naval buildup and that the photos told the
Soviets nothing they had not learned already from a 1978 incident
in which the spy satellite's operations manual was sold to a Soviet
agent.
   The defense also said the espionage prosecution violated
Morison's right to free speech and would intimidate low-level
government employees from leaking information which would embarrass
their superiors.
   ``The mere fact that one has stolen a document in order that he
may deliver it to the press, whether for money or other personal
gain, will not immunize him from responsibility for his criminal
act,'' said Judge Donald Russell in the main ruling.
   ``To use the First Amendment for such a purpose would be to
convert the First Amendment into a warrant for thievery.''
   In a concurring opinion, Judge J. Harvie Wilkinson III said the
constitutional interests were significant, but added that the
manner in which the photographs were released threatened another
important public interest, the security of sensitive government
operations.
   Judge J. Dickson Phillips Jr., in his concurring opinion, agreed
that broadly drawn federal espionage laws ``are unwieldy and
imprecise instruments for prosecuting government `leakers' to the
press as opposed to government `moles' in the service of other
countries.''
   Yet in Morison's case, he said, a jury instruction requiring
proof that the leaked information was either potentially damaging
to the government or might be useful to an enemy was a sufficient
limit.
   Mark Lynch, Morison's lawyer, had not seen the appeals ruling
Monday. He said he had not decided whether to seek a rehearing
before the 4th Circuit or ask for a U.S. Supreme Court review of
the case.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
