<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson 3rdLd-Writethru a0771 04-04 0930</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0771,900</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede MILWAUKEE</HEAD>
<HEAD>Jackson Invokes King's Memory; Defends Panama Letter</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE; picks up 2nd graf pvs, bgng:
``Twenty years</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Jesse Jackson made final appeals
to Wisconsin Democrats Monday on the eve of the state's
presidential primary, saying, ``I've stood with you, and now I want
you the people to stand with me.''
   Jackson campaigned before college students, held rallies in
predominantly black and Hispanic neighborhoods of Milwaukee, and
addressed 4,000 people on the stops of the state Capitol in Madison.
   Thousands filled Milwaukee's Mecca Auditorium for an evening
rally. In Madison, a huge crowd filled the Capitol steps, rising
high on a hill, and spilled over to sidewalks across the street as
Jackson delivered an emotional appeal for support under the setting
sun.
   ``You're looking for a leader to vote for in Wisconsin,'' he
said.
   Earlier, Jackson campaigned among college students on the 20th
anniversary of Martin Luther King Jr.'s death, repeatedly invoking
the memory of the slain civil rights leader.
   ``Twenty years later, we've kept struggling,'' he said.
``Nothing will break our spirit. Reagan says cut back; we say fight
back.''
   Jackson said his goal, like King's, was ``pulling people
together across ancient barriers to common ground.''
   Urging the students to reject ``yuppie-ism,'' Jackson told them
that by voting, ``you have the power to end Reaganomics.''
   Jackson walked through a Hispanic community of Milwaukee, where
he drew only a small crowd, and later spoke to hundreds of students
at the University of Wisconsin-Milwaukee campus.
   He also spoke to a largely black street rally and headed to
later rallies in Janesville and at the state Capitol in Madison.
   Jackson was counting on broad support, beyond Wisconsin's small
minority population, he if is to win the primary, where 81
delegates are at stake.
   A recent Milwaukee Journal poll put him 8 percentage points
behind Michael Dukakis, but the race was still regarded as close.
   As he campaigned, Jackson was embroiled in controversy over his
appeal to Panama strongman Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega to leave
office and a message he sent two weeks ago saying, ``I am anxious
to do whatever I can to help alleviate the suffering.''
   Jackson released a translated letter of response from Noriega,
saying he was not leaving and offering ``to speak with you more
deeply ... whenever you are available.''
   Jackson said he had no plans to visit Noriega. He repeated his
call for Noriega to leave, asked for a congressional investigation
into U.S. dealings with the accused drug smuggler, and called for
international relief agencies to provide ``humanitarian'' aid to
the people of Panama.
   At the State Department, deputy spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley
signalled displeasure over Jackson's communications with Noriega.
   ``In our view proliferation of channels is a tactic that Noriega
likes to use to buy time,'' Ms. Oakley said. ``We have available
channels of communication with Noriega if and when they are needed.
We think it would be best to continue to use these channels
exclusively.''
   Jackson, however, said he was not attempting to interfere.
   ``It's nothing but a very strong and public appeal,'' he said.
``... The appeal has been very public ... I would hope the whole
world would make a public appeal.''
   Jackson said he did not favor an end to the economic sanctions
applied to pressure Noriega to leave office. But he said they have
caused some people to lack food and medicine, and have not achieved
their goal.
   ``The quick solution of economic sanctions clearly did not
work,'' Jackson said. ``... Now we are in danger of alienating''
the people of Panama. He also attacked what he called a ``policy of
hysteria and military adventurism'' by the Reagan administration in
the region.
   Jackson said he talked by telephone Monday afternoon with two
high-ranking State Department officials and said they offered no
disagreement with his appeal for Noriega to leave.
   Speaking with reporters on his campaign bus in Janesville, Wis.,
Jackson said John C. Whitehead, the deputy secretary of state, and
Michael H. Armacost, undersecretary of state for political affairs,
told him the Reagan administration already has begun providing a
small amount of humanitarian aid because of hardships in Panama
caused by the economic sanctions. He said it amounted to $275,000.
   ``But that is too little, as compared to the serverity of the
crunch on the people,'' Jackson told reporters.
   Jackson said he called the State Department during a stop for a
campaign rally in Janesville. He said Whitehead ``saw abosultely
nothing inconsistent with our very public and moral appeal to get
Noriega to leave.''
   He said the officials made no suggestion that he should tone
down his efforts or be more cautious with dealing with Noriega.
   On another matter, Jackson aides distributed what they said was
an apology Jackson received from Jeanne Simon, wife of rival Paul
Simon. It was in reaction to her saying of Jackson: ``All he can do
is talk. Adolf Hitler made some good speeches too.''
   In her statement to Jackson, she called him a powerful orator.
``Experience is also important in a president and that's the point
I was addressing. I used the most extreme example I could have to
make that point, and I should not have. I appologize to Jesse if
there was any misunderstanding,'' she said.
   Meanwhile, the Jackson campaign _ once strapped for funds _
collected $2.2 million last month. That provides him with some
ready cash for use in big contests like the April 19 New York
primary.
</TEXT>
