<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Mecham-Protest 3rdLd-Writethru a0825 04-04 0695</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mecham-Protest, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0825,0712</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With Each Vote, Morale of Mecham Supporters Sank</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to recast, to make clear it was Mecham
oppenents cheered</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT McCARTNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With each vote, the high spirits of
supporters of impeached Gov. Evan Mecham sank lower and lower
Monday.
   Aye. Aye. Aye. A few Mecham opponents cheered, but most outside
the Arizona Senate building booed and a few shed tears as the votes
continued.
   The carnival-like party, which included a trumpet quartet and a
country 'n' western duo throughout the day, was over.
   ``I feel betrayed by our Legislature. I had more faith in
them,'' said Mecham supporter Millie Pratt. ``I really felt he
would win. It should have been close. I don't know what happened.''
   The crowd, which had dwindled to 200 or so by the time of the
roll call votes, huddled around portable televisions and radios to
listen as the state Senate decided to remove Mecham from office.
   The loudest cheer of the afternoon came when the Senate declined
to invoke the ``Dracula clause'' _ a measure that would have barred
Mecham from holding future offices.
   ``It's not over. It's only beginning. We're not going to quit,''
said supporter Virginia Archer, who predicted Mecham will be able
to run in and win a recall election set for May 17.
   ``It's no surprise,'' said Mecham supporter Andy Cosentino.
``It's a kangaroo court.''
   A few anti-Mecham believers cheered the ``aye'' votes for
conviction on the impeachment charges. ``I'm very happy and
relieved. I think he's a menace, and I think he's clearly guilty of
malfeasance,'' said Barry Gabriel, who carried a sign saying simply
``Guilty. Guilty. Guilty.''
   Mecham waved the crowd and smiled as he left. And the gathering
sang ``God Bless America.''
   Earlier, some 300 supporters staged an 11th hour protest and
mock funeral for the Arizona Constitution, complete with trumpters
playing ``Taps'' and pallbearers toting a black wooden coffin.
   It turned out to be a burial for Mecham's administration.
   ``It's a sad story. These people (anti-Mecham senators) made up
their minds months ago. We all know it. But we have come out to
show support and hope somebody changes their mind at the last
minute,'' said Theo Putnam.
   Lula Crosby, a retired junior high school teacher, held an
American flag high for two hours.
   ``The flag stands for justice, purity and honesty _ all the good
things,'' she said. ``We hope that they (Senators) are on the right
track and they give us justice and not take our vote away from us.''
   Some wore railroad attire and blew a train-like whistle, and
paper train tracks were laid across the plaza because, Mecham
supporters said, the embattled chief executive was being railroaded
by the Legislature.
   They chanted ``We love you, governor'' as Mecham arrived,
looking subdued and giving only a brief thumbs-up sign as he
entered the Senate. A ``Thank Heaven For Evan'' sign was taped to
the building.
   The demonstration was punctuated by a trumpted quartet imported
by supporters from Los Angeles that opened with ``America'' from
``West Side Story.'' A woman passing out Mecham's book, ``Come Back
America,'' danced to the refrains.
   Cindy Biggs woke up her three children _ ages 4, 2, and 9 months
_ at 6:30 a.m. to join the crowd. She wore a T-shirt proclaiming
Mecham ``The best governor Arizona had.''
   ``If they're messing with my governor, I'll be down here to
support him,'' she said.
   Sharon Crandall donned maid-like attire and carried a broom and
a sign saying ``It's time for a good house cleaning in our
Capitol.''
   ``I think they know Gov. Mecham is innocent. If they can
withstand the pressure of the power establishment in Arizona,
they'll vote no and Gov. Mecham will be released,'' she said.
   A seven-car funeral procession circled the Capitol, led by a
white station wagon carrying the coffin. On top of the black casket
was a sign proclaiming ``Herein Lies the Right to an Elected
Governor.'' The crowd also sang songs, including some homemade
refrains that included verse like ``...And we'll all be glad when
Evan comes marching home.''
</TEXT>
