<HEAD>Threats Target Senators After Impeachment Vote, DPS Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Mecham, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some lawmakers were given police
protection Monday night after receiving threats prompted by the
state Senate vote to remove impeached Gov. Evan Mecham from office,
officials said.
   ``A lot of threatening calls had been placed'' to senators'
offices and homes, said Allan Schmidt, spokesman for the state
Department of Public Safety.
   ``They've been all types of intimidating-type threatening
statements ranging from voter response to the ultimate,'' Schmidt
said.
   During the impeachment process, state and local police had
stepped up security for Legislators, Schmidt said. After the vote,
some were receiving protection. ``We felt they'd be more
comfortable,'' he said.
