<DOCNO> AP880404-0192 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 2322EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Mecham 10thLd-Writethru a0823 04-04 1326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mecham, 10th Ld - Writethru, a0823,1362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Arizona Gov. Mecham Convicted and Removed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with eight grafs to ADD supporters singing in Mecham's
honor; PICKS UP 8th graf pvs, `A motion ...'; SUBS grafs 12-13 bgng
`The 192-seat ...' with two grafs with more color; INSERTS one graf
after 20th graf pvs, `The vote ...'; INSERTS two grafs after 25th
graf pvs, `The Senate ...' with comment from Southern Christian
Leadership Conference.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Arizona Senate convicted Gov. Evan
Mecham on Monday of attempting to thwart a death-threat
investigation and misusing funds, making him the first U.S.
governor impeached and removed from office in 59 years.
   Acting Gov. Rose Mofford, a Democrat, became governor the moment
the gavel fell to close the 21-9 vote to convict on the first
charge, obstruction. Two-thirds of the 30-member, GOP-controlled
Senate was needed for conviction.
   The Senate then convicted the first-term Republican 26-4 on a
charge he misused $80,000 from a protocol fund by loaning it to his
auto dealership.
   Mecham, who took notes in the Senate chamber as lawmakers voted,
sat solemnly, showing little emotion.
   ``Well, they don't like my politics so we finished a political
trial,'' said the 63-year-old Mecham as he left the somber Senate
chamber. Asked what he intended to do next, Mecham said, ``We'll
decide tomorrow.''
   He left the building with a smile and a wave to scores of
supporters cheering and singing ``God Bless America.''
   The vote ended a year-and-a-half of controversy that shook
staunchly Republican Arizona and brought ridicule and criticism
from politicians, comedians and the comic strip ``Doonesbury.''
   Mecham, a former auto dealer who was elected in 1986 on his
fifth try in a three-way race with 40 percent of the vote, had
offended blacks, Jews, women and homosexuals with offhand remarks
and official actions.
   A motion to bar him from ever holding state office in Arizona
fell three votes short of a two-thirds majority, with 17 in favor
and 13 opposed.
   The last governor to be impeached and removed from office was
Henry Johnston of Oklahoma, who was removed in 1929.
   Mrs. Mofford, in a statement, declared ``the end of some
difficult times in Arizona,'' and urged residents to purge ``our
hearts of suspicion and hate.''
   ``Today none of us are Republicans, none of us are Democrats,''
she said. ``We are all Arizonans. Let us go forward together as
Arizonans.''
   The 192-seat gallery was nearly full and there was a buzz in the
somber chamber after each vote Monday.
   Outside the building, 200 Mecham supporters and opponents
followed the proceedings on TV sets and radios. Each side cheered
as votes favorable to their side were cast.
   ``I feel betrayed by our Legislature. I had more faith in
them,'' said Millie Pratt of Mesa.
   ``I'm very happy and relieved. I think he's a menance,'' said
Barry Gabriel, who carried a sign reading, ``Guilty. Guilty.
Guility.''
   There are 19 Republicans and 11 Democrats in the Senate. On the
first and decisive charge against Mecham, 10 Republicans and all 11
Democrats voted to convict; nine Republicans voted to acquit.
   On the second count, 15 Republicans and 11 Democrats voted yes;
four Republicans voted no. On whether to bar Mecham from future
office, nine Republicans and eight Democrats voted for exclusion,
10 Republicans and three Democrats voted against.
   ``The citizens of this state will not tolerate this evil
insensitivity,'' said Democratic Sen. Jesus ``Chuy'' Higuera in
voting to convict.
   Republican Sen. Jan Brewer said she felt Mecham ``made a serious
error,'' but she added, ``I do not think it is sufficient to remove
him from office.''
   ``The vote is 21 ayes, nine nos. Evan Mecham is convicted of
high crimes, misdemeanors and malfeasance in office,'' said the
trial's presiding officer, Arizona Chief Justice Frank X. Gordon
Jr., after the vote on the first count.
   ``There's no joy in anyone's hearts today,'' said Assistant
Minority Leader Lela Alston, a Democrat who voted to convict on
both counts. ``I'm heartsick.''
   The combative Mecham drew fire for rescinding a Martin Luther
King Jr. holiday, a move that prompted of boycott of Arizona by
organizations looking to hold conventions in Arizona, and defending
the use of the word ``pickaninny'' for black children. He also came
under attack for appointments deemed unqualified, including a tax
official who didn't file his taxes.
   The House voted 46-14 to impeach Mecham Feb. 5 on the two counts
on which he was convicted and a charge of concealing a $350,000
campaign loan. The Senate dismissed the third charge during the
six-week trial.
   Mecham also faced a recall election May 17 and is scheduled for
trial in court April 21 on felony charges of concealing the
$350,000 loan. The question of whether he may run in the recall
election is likely to be decided in court, said Attorney General
Bob Corbin.
   Corbin said earlier that the recall election would be held as
scheduled whether Mecham was in office or not, and that the
governor in office at the time _ Mrs. Mofford _ would have to run
in the election to remain in office.
   Because the Senate didn't bar Mecham from holding office in the
future, supporters held out hope for a victory in the recall
election. ``It's not over; it's only beginning. We're not going to
quit now,'' said Virginia Archer of Phoenix.
   The Senate, after voting, adjourned for the day and said it
would reconvene Wednesday to hear any motions from attorneys.
   In Atlanta, news of Mecham's removal brought cheers from
hundreds at a banquet held in memory of King by the Southern
Christian Leadership Conference. Mecham's removal came exactly 20
years after the civil rights leader's assassination.
   ``I can't rejoice at anyone's misfortune. I think justice has
been served. I hate to rejoice ... but somehow I feel good about
this impeachment,'' said SCLC president Joseph Lowery.
   Some lawmakers were given police protection Monday night after
receiving threatening phone calls prompted by the vote, said Allan
Schmidt, spokesman for the state Department of Public Safety.
   ``They've been all types of intimidating-type threatening
statements ranging from voter response to the ultimate,'' Schmidt
said.
   The voting by the Senate began after the prosecutor, Paul
Eckstein, beseeched the lawmakers to convict and remove Mecham and
``bring down the curtain on this prolonged, embarrassing and bitter
tragedy.''
   On the obstruction charge, Mecham was accused of telling Ralph
Milstead, the state's top police official, not to cooperate with
the state attorney general's probe of an alleged threat against a
former aide who was about to testify before a grand jury
investigating Mecham's finances.
   The threat allegedly was made by Lee Watkins, a Mecham campaign
fund-raiser and state official. Watkins, an ex-convict, was said to
have warned that Donna Carlson would go on a ``long boat ride'' if
she didn't keep quiet. He denied any wrongdoing.
   Mecham testified he did not consider the alleged threat a
serious matter.
   The governor was also accused of misusing $80,000 from a fund
consisting of contributions raised from Mecham's inaugural.
   The prosecution charged that the funds were public money for use
in promoting Arizona and that Mecham took out the loan because his
dealership was in financial trouble; Mecham claimed that the money
was private and that he borrowed it only to give the state higher
interest than it was receiving.
   ``I urge you to consider that by allowing (Mecham) to return to
office to wreak havoc once again upon this state you will have
redefined in the most shameful way what is acceptable conduct for a
public official,'' Eckstein argued Monday.
   ``Let the people decide,'' said defense attorney Jerris Leonard,
urging senators to acquit the governor and let him defend his
office in the recall election.
   ``I ask you, where's the beef?'' another defense attorney, Fred
Craft, said of the evidence. ``You are being asked to politically
assassinate Governor Mecham, by those who would politically gain
from his demise.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
