<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 1226EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i AM-China-Sterility Adv11   04-04 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Sterility, Adv 11,0510</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv11</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, April 11 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>China Using `Secret' Traditional Medicines to Treat Sterility</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China-Test-Tube Baby, b0494</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY CHARLENE L. FU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARBIN, China (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's first male sexual disorders clinic
treats sterile and impotent men with a secret method used in old
imperial courts. Across town, barren women get the secret
``shuangshuang'' (double-double) treatment, based on other old
remedies.
   Doctors at these clinics in Harbin, the capital of the
northeastern province of Heilongjiang, say they have been markedly
successful with their unique combination of Western and Chinese
traditional medicine.
   At the Center for Treatment and Consultation of Sexual Disorders
of Men, doctors refer cryptically to the imperial cure by the code
name ``8311'' and will only say that it involves herbs, minerals
and animal parts used in Chinese traditional medicine.
   At the Center for Treatment and Consultation of Sexual Disorders
of Women, barren women undergo daily double-double treatments,
which involve injections of a liquid medication into the genitals
and rectum.
   But, once again, the doctors will not divulge detailed
information, saying only that it is a concoction of herbs used in
traditional Chinese medicine.
   ``It is a secret,'' said Dr. Shi Ling, director of the
Obstetrical and Gynecological Hospital of Harbin. ``We have not
published it yet.''
   However, the doctors are happy to talk about their successes.
   Sixty to 70 percent of the 125 sterile or impotent patients who
have been treated with ``8311'' were cured, said Dr. Ma Ran, deputy
director of the No. 4 Hospital of Harbin.
   At least 11 of 33 women given the double-double treatment have
become pregnant, Shi said. However, the clinic has not been to
follow up on all its patients, and Shi suspects the pregnancy
figures might be higher.
   Even more impressive, though, is the claim by Dr. Zhao Tieyan of
the Traditional Chinese Medicine Hospital in Shenyang, in
neighboring Liaoning province.
   According to the English-language newspaper China Daily, Zhao
has treated 90,000 men for sterility and 75 percent of them later
fathered children.
   The report did not give any details about her treatment or the
composition of the medication she developed from her study of
Chinese traditional medicine.
   The double-double treatment was developed by Guo Hengsheng, a
doctor of Western medicine who had also studied Chinese traditional
medicine.
   Its name derives from the two injections and the heating of the
woman's abdomen and back.
   The treatment is supposed to reduce infection and inflammation
in the pelvic area that may be blocking pregnancy.
   Following the injections, the women undergo several hours of
heat treatment, huddling under layers of heavy quilts and on top of
electric blankets.
   The women undergo treatments every day for a week, then have a
week off. The treatment period can be as short as one week or as
long as several months.
   ``We know it works when they get pregnant,'' Shi said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, April 11</NOTE>
</DOC>
