<1ST_LINE>s i BC-APN--Huntington'sDisease Adv17-2Takes   04-04 0930</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Huntington's Disease, Adv 17-2 Takes,0959</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv17</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 17</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR's NOTE _ Huntington's disease is a strange and
devastating affliction that has all but wrecked one small town in
Venezuela. Its lethal, inherited course through one large family
there, however, may help scientists find a treatment and a cure.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By CARRIE FIGDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAGUNETA, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yelitza Margarita Cabrera, like many
budding 12-year-olds, has a crush on at least six boys her age.
   Chuchito, Jose Luis, another Chuchito. She rattles them off on
her rough hands, chipped pink polish on her short nails. A yellow
plastic butterfly clip gathers up her brown hair in a coquettish
tilt.
   Yelitza may have inherited from her father a terminal disease
that could leave her bedridden, unable to speak clearly or chew and
swallow easily by the time she's 50.
   By then, she may have had lots of children _ her grandparents,
Eduardo and Carmen Soto had 14 _ and passed the disease on to many
of them.
   Eduardo and Carmen both have Huntington's disease, formally
known as Huntington's chorea, which they know as Saint Vitus'
dance. It has been passed on through their family's genes for more
than six traceable generations.
   Their family's tragedy has, however, provided the basis for the
first concerted effort to find the cause of the disease and perhaps
learn to treat it or eradicate it.
   It was just this year that Dr. Anne Young, head of the neurology
department at the University of Michigan, diagnosed Yelitza's
father as having Huntington's disease, an inherited degenerative
disorder which affects seven to 10 out of every 100,000 people in
the world.
   American folk singer Woody Guthrie was a victim and his son,
Arlo Guthrie, and Arlo's four children are at risk. Young is very
suspicious about Yelitza.
   ``Her eye movements are a little...bit...off,'' she says with
matter-of-fact intensity. ``She's not...quite...right.''
   Young belongs to a Huntington's disease research team that has
been coming to Laguneta each March since 1981 to collect blood and
give neurological and psychological tests to its inhabitants. The
group is headed by Dr. Nancy Wexler of Columbia University's
neurology department.
   Wexler is also a founder and president of the California-based
Hereditary Disease Foundation, which coordinates Huntington's
research in five U.S. universities and one in London.
   The foundation has a five-year grant of just under $1 million
from the National Institutes of Health for Huntington's research.
   Laguneta and two other poor Venezuelan towns, Barranquitas and
San Luis, are a main element of the research.
   In these three villages live nearly all the members of the Soto
clan, the source of the largest documented family gene pool in the
world.
   Wexler and her associates have drawn up a 9,000-person family
tree that traces the spread of the gene defect that causes
Huntington's from a single woman, Maria Concepcion Soto, who died
of the disorder near Laguneta about 1880.
   The defect causes neurons in a certain part of the brain to
degenerate, resulting in gradual loss of control of voluntary
movement.
   Although disease is always fatal, the defect lives on because
the obvious symptoms of degeneration usually don't show up until
long after childbearing age.
   Eduardo used to be a fisherman, like everyone else in this tiny
village of 16 shacks on stilts 3 feet above Lake Maracaibo. You
reach the place by a four-hour cabin cruiser ride south from the
city of Maracaibo through a slalom course of oil rigs.
   Now he spends his days on the wooden plank floor of a daughter's
8-by-10-foot corrugated tin hut. His arms and legs jerk about
nervously, his head lolls, he can no longer talk.
   Eduardo can somehow make it to his feet and lurch outside to the
tiny porch of rotting logs, only to collapse next to a pile of damp
fish nets, smiling apologetically. Sometimes he falls overboard and
he has to be fished out.
   He is 65. At the rate his disease is progressing, he'll probably
die within a year or two.
   Yelitza's father, Angel Eduardo, one of Eduardo Soto's 14
surviving children, is still a fisherman at 37, as he has been
since the age of 10.
   He goes out every day with a few relatives in a long, narrow
motorized dinghy and brings in about 200 pounds of corvina, bagre
and other local fish.
   Angel Eduardo will be able to do this for five more years, maybe
a bit longer, doctors say.
   Then he won't be able to control his movements enough to fling a
net properly, or navigate. Someone in his family _ maybe Yelitza,
maybe her sister _will have to take care of him until he dies. That
could take 20 years.
   The 14 children of Eduardo and Carmen Soto already have 58 kids
of their own, all at risk of Huntington's disease. Yelitza is one
of them.
   Of the 14, four have double doses of the defective gene _ one
from Eduardo and one from Carmen. All of their children will get
the disease.
   Dr. James Gusella, a molecular biologist at Massachusetts
General Hospital in Boston, examines the family's genes from the
1,500 blood samples Wexler and Young have collected since 1981.
Using the extensive genetic records of the Soto family, Gusella has
developed a test to identify Huntington's disease victims before
symptoms develop _ even before their birth.
   The test involves the use of so-called DNA markers, chemical
signposts on the deoxyribonucleic acid that makes up genes.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880404-0202 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 1253EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-APN--Huntington'sDisease Adv17-1stAdd   04-04 0884</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Huntington's Disease, Adv 17-1st Add,0913</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv17</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 17</NOTE>
<HEAD>LAGUNETA, Venezuela: up genes.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Within a year or two, he may be able to find the defective
Huntington's gene itself, the first crucial step toward a treatment
or cure.
   Other research teams are now using this method to find genes
that cause other hereditary disorders, such as neurofibromatosis
(elephant man's disease), cystic fibrosis, Alzheimer's disease and
manic depression.
   ``The difference in genetic research now and before 1983 is like
night and day, and it's because of this Venezuelan family,'' Wexler
says. ``They showed that the strategy of using DNA markers to find
genes is correct.''
   The current genetic test is up to 96 percent accurate, depending
on how closely related are the patients who give their blood for
genetic analysis.
   A false positive on the test, while unlikely, would prove
painfully significant, especially when it comes to having a family.
   Wexler knows this firsthand. She is at risk herself. Her mother
died of the disease, and Wexler has decided not to have kids and
not to take the test.
   ``I stand to lose a lot if I find I have it, and I stand to gain
very little if I find out I don't, since I'm happy now,'' she says.
``And I wouldn't want to subject my kids to being at risk or giving
them the disease.''
   The Soto clan remains resigned to living with a disease that has
plagued their family for as long as any of them can remember.
   A few of the women at Laguneta have IUD's, but they've already
had several children.
   The majority, however, think of it as something that is passed
on in a mysterious and unavoidable way and which may or may not be
``given'' to them.
   No one in Laguneta really understands why Wexler and her
associates come back year after year to get blood samples, give
them eye tests, and hand out food, medicine and secondhand clothing
and toys.
   They are not always cooperative. Some family members refuse to
give blood, others disappear for days.
   And even though a cure, or at least a test, could be developed
within a few years as a result of research based on the Soto
family, the disease is destroying Laguneta, and it may do the same
to the Sotos.
   As recently as 40 years ago Laguneta was the size of Congo, a
thriving fishing village on stilts about an hour away by motorized
launch.
   The 1,000 inhabitants of Congo have electricity, a school, a
visiting doctor, and a church. Television antennae poke up from the
wood or tin roofs and at least one person has a high-speed outboard
motorboat.
   The people in Congo are quick to point out to visitors that one
thing they do not have is Saint Vitus' dance.
   Laguneta, in contrast, now has only about 150 inhabitants
crammed in its 16 huts and a bleak, empty church with lots of bats
but no priest.
   Two of the huts have electricity. No teachers come, and except
for Wexler's research team, no doctors come either.
   The only dry way to go from hut to hut is with a boat and a pole.
   The boys play baseball, Venezuela's favorite sport, in the salty
water that reaches just above their bellies, bloated from
intestinal parasites. Sanitation is primitive or non-existent.
   ``I give them tons of anti-parasite medicine and in a week it
won't do them any good. What they need is education in hygiene,''
complains Dr. Juan Sanchez-Ramos, a University of Miami neurologist
and a member of Wexler's team.
   And when the disease hits a fisherman, like Yelitza's father, it
means one less breadwinner for the family and one more burden for a
sister or daughter.
   So even though what they earn from fishing is a decent living by
local standards, the Sotos can never quite pull out of their
poverty.
   ``Even the ones in San Luis are still illiterate because they're
too poor to send their kids to school _ they can't afford the
books,'' Young says. ``All their resources and energy go to caring
for their sick elders.''
   And everyone in Laguneta, it seems, wants to leave.
   They all talk of getting off the water and on to dry land, and
going to Barranquitas, where, unlike in Congo, Soto family members
can welcome them.
   San Luis, a poor outlying neighborhood of Maracaibo, is
considered the next step up the ladder.
   Unfortunately, beyond Laguneta the Sotos increasingly will be in
contact with people who know nothing about the disease.
   From a single woman, Maria Concepcion Soto _ whom Wexler
suspects inherited the defect from a European sailor _ the gene has
spread as the Sotos have more surviving children.
   In Laguneta, Barranquitas and San Luis, as in many similar poor
towns worldwide, sex begins at an early age.
   Yelitza is very likely to have her first child by the time she's
15, like her cousin, Yusmary Margarita Soto, whom Young also finds
suspicious.
   ``We know these kids are living time bombs,'' Wexler says. ``We
know when we're testing them that some of them will get sick, and
there is nothing in the world that would make us happier than to be
able to save them.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 17</NOTE>
