<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Devil's Island-Dictionary, Adv 17,0182</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv17</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 17</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-APN--Devil's Island</HEAD>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a Devil's Island dictionary:
   BAGNARD: Inmate of a bagne, a French prison.
   BELOTE: Four-handed game played with a 32-card deck. By convict
custom, a new dealer was selected by a knife fight.
   CAVALE: An escape or prison break; from cheval, French word for
horse. In other words, get on your horse and go.
   ILE DU DIABLE DEUXIEME: Poulo Condore, France's other penal
colony off the tip of South Vietnam.
   MANGEUSE D'HOMMES: Devourer of men, applied to the solitary
cells on St. Joseph.
   MEC: The original underworld meaning was pimp, but by Papillon's
day mec connoted any pal or chum among the inmates.
   PENITENCIER: Penal colony, penitentiary.
   RECLUSIONNAIRE: Convict in solitary confinement at Le Reclusion
Disciplinaire, the dungeons on St. Joseph where total silence was
the rule.
   RELEGUE: Habitual offender, usually a small-time criminal with
at least three convictions.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 17</NOTE>
