<1ST_LINE>s w BC-APN--AIDSAdmiral Adv17-2Takes   04-04 0673</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--AIDS Admiral, Adv 17-2 Takes,0693</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv17</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 17</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ President Reagan's AIDS commission appeared to
be a sinking ship when a retired Navy admiral took the helm last
fall. Adm. James D. Watkins guided the commission through
exhaustive hearings that resulted in recommendations that were
widely praised. The admiral is the first to concede, however, that
the commission has yet to deal with some of the thorniest questions
swirling around AIDS.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Adm. James D. Watkins remembers the advice
that some of his closest friends offered when he asked them if he
should take the helm of President Reagan's embattled AIDS
commission.
   ``James, it's a loser. Stay out of it.''
   That was last October. The commission was sinking fast in a
choppy sea of public ridicule and internal disarray. The first
chairman, a physician unschooled in the ways of backstage
Washington, had resigned. Critics were portraying the panel as a
hopeless collection of doctrinaire, archconservatives sprinkled
with a few doctors who, nonetheless, knew little about AIDS.
   ``I knew it was a can of worms of the first order,'' Watkins
sats.
   But he did not rise to chief of naval operations by doubting his
own abilities. Moreover, he was a Washington veteran.
   As a result, Watkins was more disposed to listen to other
friends who told him: ``I don't know anybody else who could do it.
I think you ought to try it.''
   Still, Watkins knew his commission colleagues would not
automatically salute his elevation to chairman.
   ``I knew I would need their support at the outset, so I made
some calls,'' he recalled in a recent interview. ``I'd say, `What
do you want? Do you want me to do it or not? You've got to let me
run it if I'm going to do it.'
   ``I got a positive response from all the commissioners. I knew
then I could probably make it. There was no divisiveness. They knew
they were in trouble. They all had professional reputations at
stake. They saw in me an opportunity.''
   Run it he did.
   Watkins presented 60 pages of detailed ``chairman's
recommendations'' for the commission's approval on Feb. 29,
including a call for spending an additional $20 billion over the
next decade, most of it on drug abusers. Three days later, in a pro
forma business meeting that took all of 10 minutes, the panel
adopted them unanimously.
   In releasing the interim report, Watkins said, ``We waste a lot
of rhetoric and excessive time on a couple of little issues, while
the forest behind us is burning. We believe some major changes in
course are necessary.''
   The chorus of editorials lauding those recommendations was as
loud as the one writing off the commission as a lost cause six
months and nearly 400 witnesses earlier.
   Rep. Henry Waxman, D-Calif., a frequent critic of administration
AIDS policies, praised the Watkins report as a ``first-rate set of
recommendations that begin to deal with the AIDS epidemic
responsibly and in detail.''
   Dr. Mervyn Silverman, president of the Los Angeles-based
American Foundation for AIDS Research, said, ``I continue to get
more and more pleased as I see what Watkins is doing.''
   Admittedly, the suggestions in the report to the president do
not get at the thorniest questions swirling around AIDS.
   Watkins knows that. He ticks off the remaining ones in shorthand
form: ``Education, testing, confidentiality, discrimination, legal,
liability, pharmaceutical, doctors.''
   ``We're really going to face some toughies,'' he says. ``But
now, we're kind of trained. We've been through the mill together.''
   Watkins concedes that neither he nor the other members of the
original panel knew much about AIDS when they started.
   In retrospect, it is clear that Watkins went about managing the
AIDS commission much the way he operated in the Navy _ by immersing
himself and his associates in a problem until answers floated to
the surface.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
