<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APN--TheaterWeek Adv17   04-04 0869</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Theater Week, Adv 17,0892</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv17</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 17</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amy Irving came to New York from Los Angeles for
only three hours just to see South Africa playwright Athol Fugard.
   The thoughtful, serious actress felt she had to appear in
Fugard's ``The Road to Mecca,'' a three-character play about an
eccentric artist facing the loss of her independence.
   In the drama, an older woman, played by Yvonne Bryceland, is the
object of a dispute. An Afrikaner minister, portrayed by Fugard
himself, wants to put the woman in a nursing home, an action
opposed by a feisty, angry teacher. That was the role Miss Irving
wanted to play.
   The playwright and the actress, who had never met before, talked
about the play and its characters and briefly acted out several
scenes.
   ``I was flying when I left the place,'' Miss Irving said the
other day during a rehearsal break. ``It was a thrilling
experience. Athol has so much energy. By the time I left the
audition, I just said, `So when do we start working?''' She got the
part.
   For ``A Road to Mecca,'' now playing at off-Broadway's Promenade
Theater, its journey to New York wasn't accomplished so quickly.
The play's premiere took place at the Yale Repertory Theater in
Connecticut in 1984. The following year there was a production in
London by the National Theater.
   But a New York production was stymied by casting problems,
particularly over whether Miss Bryceland, a South African, should
be allowed to appear here. Actors Equity felt the role should be
played by an American actress.
   Miss Bryceland finally did appear on an American stage nearly a
year ago when ``The Road to Mecca'' was mounted at the Spoleto
Festival U.S.A. in Charleston, S.C. Miss Irving was in none of
those productions.
   ``That was part of the appeal to me, the challenge,'' she says.
``Working in a three-character play in a situation where the others
have pretty much found their characters.''
   But she discovered during rehearsals that there were very few
moments when she was aware that Fugard and Miss Bryceland had done
the play before.
   ``That's because they have a new set to work on and there's
completely different blocking,'' Miss Irving says. ``So it is new
for them as well, and besides, they are always finding new values
in the play.''
   The actress also had the pleasure of being directed by the man
who wrote the words.
   ``It's easier being directed by the author because so often
you're not quite sure what the writer meant,'' she says. ``With
this production, you can just turn to the director and say, `What
did the writer mean?' Sometimes he'll remember and sometimes he
won't. And sometimes he'll remember but be open to other
intrepretations.''
   Miss Irving, wife of filmmaker Steven Spielberg, has been able
to move easily between the very different worlds of television,
movies and theater. Filmgoers remember her best as the spiteful
high school student in ``Carrie'' or as the love interest in
Barbara Streisand's ``Yentel.''
   ``It's nice being able to alternate,'' she says. ``After I
finished being a location wife for a while, I went to the
Williamstown Theater Festival and did `Three Sisters' and then went
right into a movie called ``Crossing Delancey' and then this.''
   The theater is Miss Irving's mainstay and she has impeccable and
lengthy stage credentials. She has been in the theater since she
was 9 months old, carried on stage by her mother, actress Priscilla
Pointer. It was a production of ``Rumpelstiltskin'' at the San
Francisco Actors Workshop, a group started by her father, Jules
Irving, in 1954.
   Irving then became artistic director at the Lincoln Center
Repertory Theater in New York. Theater inundated Miss Irving's life
and the lives of her brother and sister. She knew she would have to
make it her profession but was unsure what her parents would say.
   ``After they saw me in my first off-Broadway production, they
breathed a sigh of relief and encouraged me,'' Miss Irving says.
``But they also said, `Just because you've been in theater all your
life, doesn't mean you know everything about it.' They encouraged
me to get classical training.''
   A year at the American Conservatory Theater in San Francisco and
three years studying in London provided the foundation.
   ``My parents taught me a great respect for the theater,'' Miss
Irving says. ``You don't just go and do it. You learn your craft
first, such as the exploration of the text and your responsibility
to the other people on stage.''
   That's what she's doing at the time of the interview, getting
ready for the opening of ``The Road to Mecca'' and putting on stage
what Fugard the playwright and Fugard the director wants.
   ``I haven't got a clue how this comes across to an audience,''
she says. ``I have talked to several people who have seen the play,
including my mother, and they were very excited by it. I hope
they're right.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 17</NOTE>
