<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 1238EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-DrugsScourge-Bolivia Adv10   04-04 0798</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Drugs Scourge-Bolivia, Adv 10,0819</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv10</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 10, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>U.S. Agents Battling Bolivia's Cocaine Traffickers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-World Drugs Scourge, b0701-b0702</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER McFARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VILLA TUNARI, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roadside spotlights flashed on as
the 10-year-old truck, loaded with foodstuffs and silent peasants,
rumbled down a dirt highway in the midnight darkness near this
jungle crossroads.
   From behind the blinding beams stepped four U.S. Border Patrol
agents and a group of Bolivian police. They stopped the truck,
inspected it and found beneath bundles of food a costly cache of
sulfuric acid, which is used to make cocaine paste.
   Once unheard-of, such spot checks are becoming more and more
common in the Chapare, a semi-tropical lowland region where 90
percent of Bolivia's huge coca crop is produced.
   Helping direct the effort are the four U.S. agents, who
volunteered to transfer from the U.S.-Mexican frontier to train
Bolivian police officers in drug interdiction.
   Before their arrival in October cocaine traffickers controlled
the roads around Villa Tunari, about 60 miles northeast of the city
of Cochabamba. Now, the drug dealers move warily, sometimes falling
into police traps.
   On March 28, the Bolivian police and the border agents snared
two trucks carrying an estimated $80,000 worth of
cocaine-processing chemicals at Paracti, a control point on the
main road to the Chapare.
   Paracti is the agents' base. They rough it there in a
12-by-9-foot guardhouse filled with supplies, clothing, weapons and
other equipment and an electrical generator.
   There's room only for two bunk beds, so the four agents take
turns sleeping. The guardhouse has no running water.
   Nevertheless, Darryl Brown, a bearded 40-year-old Californian,
said he would volunteer for a second tour when his current
four-month stint ends.
   ``Here we can have an impact,'' he said.
   The work sometimes can be hazardous.
   One February night, Brown was among a force of Border Patrol
officers, U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration (DEA) agents and
Bolivian police who took over a stretch of jungle road used as a
landing strip by traffickers. At dawn when a small plane landed and
inside the group found 963 pounds of cocaine paste.
   The pilot offered them $50,000 to let him fly on with his cargo.
A hostile crowd of hundreds of farmers and peasants, many of whom
are employed in cocaine-paste production, gathered.
   A woman stepped forward with bundles of U.S. dollars to offer as
a bribe but was arrested. The crowd then started throwing rocks and
sticks of dynamite at the officers. Barricades of burning tires and
lumber were thrown up, trapping the officers until reinforcements
could arrive and disperse the mob with gunfire.
   Brown suffered a cut on his cheek; two of the protesters were
killed.
   The agents are part of a 60-man U.S. force trying to help stem
drug production in Bolivia. About 30 U.S. Army Special Forces
members are training a special Bolivian police anti-drug unit,
called The Leopards, and 25 to 30 DEA agents help coordinate in
cocaine interdiction. The U.S. Army has thrown six Huey helicopters
into the effort.
   ``We want to make it so expensive to produce cocaine that it is
no longer cost effective,'' said one DEA agent, who asked not to be
identified. ``Bolivia has the potential, and probably is the most
successful program in South America.''
   The efforts in the Chapare, which is about the size of New
Jersey, has made it difficult for cultivators to sell their
harvested coca leaves to drug processors, according to Col. Nicolas
Anaya Camacho, the regional Leopard commander.
   A 100-pound sack of coca leaves, the raw material for cocaine,
sells for $25 to $30. It sold for $200 three years ago. In July
1986, when 170 U.S. troops flew in to assist in a special two-month
operation, the price plunged from $125 to $40, which is about what
it cost to grow the crop.
   With prices sinking below the cost of production, many coca
farmers are joining a government program to eradicate coca acreage.
About 3,400 acres of coca have been voluntarily destroyed by
farmers, who receive $2,000 for each 2.5 acres eradicated.
   The money is intended for crop substitution. The United States
contributes $350 of the total, and the rest comes from the Bolivian
government.
   The U.S. government has earmarked $33 million a year for crop
substitution and development programs, according to the U.S.
Embassy in La Paz. But coca farmers, and many Bolivian officials,
say more is needed.
   ``We need at least $300 million over a three-year period to
combat the cocaine industry effectively,'' Foreign Minister
Guillermo Bedregal said recently. ``We are at war with the cocaine
mafia, and if we don't defeat them, forget democracy and be
prepared for the violence found in Peru and Colombia.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 10</NOTE>
</DOC>
