<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 1239EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s p BC-Candidates-Israel Adv10   04-04 1256</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Candidates-Israel, Adv 10,1289</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv10</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 10 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Democrats Divided Over Israeli Handling of Palestinian Unrest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr. is seeking to establish
his differences with the Middle East policies of Democratic
presidential rivals Jesse Jackson and Michael Dukakis in the weeks
before the crucial New York primary.
   Nowhere does the issue of U.S. policy toward Israel and the
Middle East loom larger than in New York, where Jews cast 22
percent of the votes in 1984. The state holds its presidential
primaries April 19.
   Many Jews remain wary of Jackson, who on a 1979 trip to the
Middle East embraced Palestinian Liberation Organization leader
Yassar Arafat and called Israel a ``state of oppressors.'' He also
described the PLO as ``not merely a terrorist organization, even
though it has engaged in some terrorist acts. It is a government in
exile.''
   Jackson's relations with the Jewish community were further
exacerbated in 1984 when he called New York ``Hymietown.''
   Gore, of Tennesse, has said he was ``dismayed by (Jackson's)
embrace of Arafat and Castro,'' and that he has profound
differences with Jackson on Middle East issues.
   Gore also criticized Dukakis for endorsing a letter that 30 U.S.
senators sent to Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir criticizing
Shamir's opposition to an exchange of occupied land for recognition
by Arab states. He said Shamir's objections to Secretary of State
George Shultz's peace plan deserved more consideration.
   The Associated Press asked the presidential candidates to spell
out their proposals for dealing with the Palestinian unrest,
including who should control a new homeland and how they would
protect Israel.
   Every candidate except Jackson specifically mentioned United
Nations Resolutions 242 and 338, which establish the right to exist
of all the states in the Middle East, as the basis for a settlement.
   Here is what the Democrats said:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>JESSE JACKSON</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``The current unrest is founded on a Middle East policy that is
fatally flawed. ... (It) has left Israel with false security and
Palestinians with no security _ and the United States helpless.''
   ``We need an alternative policy in the Middle East which moves
the process that began at Camp David to the next progressive step.
... Mutual recognition is the key to security in the Middle East
for Israel and for our other allies.''
   ``This policy should be built on several principles: the right
of Israel to exist; the right of the Palestinian people to
self-determination, including an independent homeland; the right of
Lebanon to sovereignity and freedom from imposed partition;
normalized ties between the U.S. and all Middle East nations ...
and demilitarization of the region and increased humanitarian aid.''
   ``An international conference on the Middle East, involving all
the parties concerned, including the chosen representatives of the
Palestinian people, will be a giant step towards peace.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ALBERT GORE JR.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``The issue is both the Palestinian people and the Israeli
people. There cannot be a solution for one and not the other. I
believe that U.N. Resolutions 242 and 338 must be the basis for a
settlement. This means a willingness on the part of Israel to
exchange land for peace. It also means a firm and unequivocable
commitment on the part of the Palestinians and the Arab states to
live up to peace-for-land. ...
   ``Our role is to facilitate the peace process but not to dictate
the terms of a peace settlement. The final status of the
territories is a matter to be decided through direct negotiatons
between the parties themselves. But I will say that my
administration will not recognize the PLO, or negotiate with it,
until and unless it fully and credibly accepts U.N. Resolutions 242
and 338, eliminates its call for the destruction of the state of
Israel and ends its support of terrorism.
   ``In the Gore administration no one will ever have reason to
doubt the American commitment to the survival and security of the
state of Israel. ... I will continue to supply Israel with the
military aid necessary to deter its enemies.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>MICHAEL DUKAKIS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``The Israeli authorities have a legitimate right to restore
order in response to violent demonstrations and attacks on Israeli
security forces. But it is clear that in several instances military
personnel have used excessive force. ...
   ``There is an urgent need to get the peace process moving again.
Tragedy has produced a unique opportunity to begin the first steps
toward resolving the future of the territories. ...
   ``Direct negotiations between the parties are necessary to
determine the ultimate status of the territories; a solution cannot
be imposed on the region. The negotiations must be based on the
principles of U.N. Resolutions 242 and 338, which include
recognition of Israel's right to exist within secure borders, and,
must also in the words of Camp David, recognize the `legitimate
rights of the Palestinian people and their just requirements.'''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>PAUL SIMON</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``Until very recently, the Reagan administration sat by
passively and did not pursue a Middle East peace accord. We have to
show that the United States is willing to play an active and
involved role in getting the parties together. Palestinians who
favor Israel's right to exist in peace, who accept U.N. Resolutions
242 and 338, should be welcomed into the process. As president, I
will make face-to-face, direct negotiations between Israelis and
Arabs a top priority.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   Among the Republicans:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>GEORGE BUSH</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The Bush campaign did not submit a written reply to the AP
questions. But Stephen Hart, press secretary for Bush, said, ``The
vice president is fully in support of Secretary Shultz's peace
plan, which is built upon the Reagan peace iniatives and in which
is embodied U.N. Resolutions 242 and 338. We believe the process
has to result in direct talks between Israel and the
Jordanian-Palestinian delegation.''
   The question of who should control a new territory ``is
something that would have to be determined as a result of the
negotiatons,'' said Hart. ``He would continue to protect Israel and
support Israel. ... He believes the peace process has to take into
account the aspirations of the Palestinian people, and at the same
time has to ensure the security of the state of Israel.''
   Bush, in response to a questionnaire that the American Jewish
Committee put out two months ago, said, ``My commitment to Israel's
security is unshakable.'' He added, ``I reject the possibility of
dealing with the PLO until it renounces terrorism and violence and
accepts U.N. Resolutions 242 and 338.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>PAT ROBERTSON</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``I strongly support a Middle East settlement that would be the
result of direct negotiations between the nations of Israel, the
Hashemite Kingdom of Jordan, and the legitimate representatives of
the Palestinian people who would agree to abide by United Nations
Resolutions 242 and 338.
   ``I agree with Prime Minister Shamir that any talks concerning
territorial adjustment should first be preceded by a period of
Palestinian self-rule in the West Bank. I reject the concept of
trading territory for peace. ... I do not believe that there will
be lasting peace in the Middle East until Iran, Syria, Saudi
Arabia, Jordan and other Arab nations cease belligerency toward
Israel and acknowledge the right of Israel to exist as a sovereign
state in the Middle East.
   ``Given the current climate of hostility against Israel on the
part of her Arab neighbors, any surrender of territory in the near
future would seriously imperil the ability of Israel to defend
herself.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 10</NOTE>
