<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 1230EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--FilmReview Adv00   04-04 0722</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Film Review, Adv 00,0732</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00
^For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>At the Movies: ``Bright Lights, Big City''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Jay McInerney's novel of redemption in the fast lane of the
1980s is a slim, ultra-hip volume set in the dimly-lighted
discotheques and cocaine-dusted bathroom stalls of New York City.
   The film by James Bridges, equally slender, is so true to the
book it seems that McInerney, who adapted it for the screen, could
have handed in a copy of the novel in lieu of the final draft of
the script.
   But what might have been a pedestrian exercise in book
illustration is, in the hands of Bridges, a simple, artistically
told story that illuminates the spiritual themes in McInerney's
novel instead of trivializing them.
   The movie could as easily have been nothing more than a star
vehicle for Michael J. Fox, a dubious choice to play the narrator
(called Jamie in the film), but he nevertheless takes a pretty good
shot at his most demanding movie role. He could have just come off
as Alex Keaton on an all-night binge in the Big Apple.
   As we meet Jamie, an aspiring writer toiling as a fact checker
at stodgy Gotham magazine, he has recently been abandoned by
Amanda, his ambitious, vacuous fashion-model wife. Haunted by
visions of the mother who abandoned him by dying, he loses himself
in shallow temptations of the flesh provided by Tad Allagash, his
world-class bar-crawler best friend.
   Keifer Sutherland simply is Allagash. Phoebe Cates is blinking
perfection as Amanda, who is more an idea than a character in the
movie as in the book. Tracy Pollan plays Tad's down-to-earth cousin
who represents Jamie's salvation.
   Jason Robards steals scenes as an alcoholic has-been editor at
Jamie's magazine. His son, Sam, has a small part as a club-goer.
Swoosie Kurtz is the good-hearted co-worker who tries to help
Jamie, but has her own agenda, and Frances Sternhagen as Clara,
Jamie's boss, turns the villainess of the book into a palpable
visage of authoritarian disapproval, even while welling up with
tears when forced to fire Jamie for incompetence.
   Dianne Wiest, as Jamie's beloved, dying mother, is swathed in an
almost Christ-like glow for her brief but pivotal role. In
flashback on her death bed, she earnestly asks him what it's like
being a young man _ Does he sleep with many girls? Does he like it?
Is it fun? Since the entire story turns on the believability of
their love for each other, these moments are especially demanding
on actors and director, and they work wonderfully.
   The movie starts just like the book and ends just like the book
and contains much of the dialogue exactly as in the novel. Bridges
has gone with an odd, literal translation of a dream scene inspired
by Jamie's obsession with the blaring tabloid-headline story of a
``coma baby'' imperiled inside its dying mother's womb.
   In the book, Jamie dreams of talking with ``coma baby'' through
its mother's transparent belly. The scene is rendered unto ``E.T.''
in the movie by way of special effects, which is OK since it is a
dream, after all. Otherwise, Bridges' direction is unobtrusive and
often quite lovely. Many of the shots _ Gordon Willis was the
cinematographer _ would stand alone as photographs.
   Those who have read the book will leave ``Bright Lights, Big
City'' satisfied. Those who haven't will have to work a little
harder to see beneath the surface.
   ``Bright Lights, Big City'' went through several writers and a
director before producers Sydney Pollack and Mark Rosenberg
reverted to the basics of the book and put Bridges (``Urban
Cowboy,'' ``China Syndrome'') on the job, under severe time
constraints because of Fox's TV schedule. Despite those problems,
the movie is a nice piece of work.
   Rated R for language and drug use.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
