<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 2255EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews Adv00   04-04 0649</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, Adv 00,0678</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   Michael Murray and the Organ of the Cathedral of St. John the
Divine (Telarc)
   
   Michael Murray's program is designed to show off some of the
special qualities of the organ of the Episcopal Cathedral of St.
John the Divine in New York City, one of the world's largest
churches. The organ is likewise immense, with 143 ranks of pipes,
and Murray gives pride of place to some of the solo stops for which
organ builder E.M. Skinner was famous.
   Where else, but perhaps in this recording of ``The Emperor's
Fanfare'' by Padre Antonio Soler, will your hear a tuba major, a
cornopean and an ophicleide in full cry?
   The cathedral's distinctive herald trumpet, mounted under the
west rose window a good 500 feet from the rest of the organ, is
also shown off in John Dunstable's ``Agincourt Hymn'' and Henry
Purcell's ``Trumpet Tune.''
   Still, the recording can only hint at the feeling of being
within that enormous unfinished space, 200 feet wide and 12 stories
high.
   _ By Robert Barr, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Pontiac'' (MCA) _ Lyle Lovett
   
   With a bone dry sense of humor and a touch of classy 1940s
swing, Lyle Lovett is molding country music into his own personal
expression of wit, love, cynicism and occasional touching despair.
   ``Pontiac,'' his second album, establishes Lovett as an
important country and western crossover artist.
   An East Texas boy who relocated to Nashville, his influences are
more Townes Van Zandt and Guy Clark than Jimmie Rodgers and Hank
Williams. And with his sharply chiseled face, pencil-thin suit and
rooster-combed hair, he looks more like a caricature from a Deco
design than a country-western singer. But he can kick you-know-what
with the best of 'em.
   Hear the echoes of Bob Willis in ``Give Back My Heart'' _ ``I
said oooh, give back my heart, you kicker-redneck woman, take your
boots and walk out of my life.'' Yee-hah!
   Then he turns around on the title track, a somber ballad Lovett
fantasized about an old man in Austin who parked his Pontiac in the
same spot each day: ``And the girl there across the street, she
sits on her front porch swing. She never realized what I told her
with my eyes, how back in the second war I killed 20 German boys
with my own bare hands.''
   The album opens with ``If I Had a Boat,'' wherein Lovett
combines fantasies about being a cowboy and a sea captain. On this
cut, his creamy smooth voice is most reminiscent of Jesse
Winchester.
   Like Winchester, much of Lovett's material is whimsical. At a
recent appearance at the Bottom Line in New York, he felt obliged
to note at the outset, ``I'm only kiddin'.''
   Take ``She's No Lady (She's My Wife)'' _ please! ``I can't
remember how I met her. Seems like she's always just been hangin'
here off my right arm.''
   He's not kidding, though, about the three-piece horn section,
backup singers and cello that now accompany him.
   Lovett notes wryly that he seems to write a lot of songs about
marriage, even though he's never been. But one of these is the most
stunning cut on the album, ``L.A. County,'' which manages to be a
haunting ballad set to a quick Texas two-step.
   Lovett said he had attended the wedding of a friend and thought
``the sensitive thing to do was to write a song about it.'' What a
sensitive boy: ``And they kissed each other, and they turned
around, and they saw me standing in the aisle. Well I did not say
much. I just stood there watching, as that .45 told them
good-bye.'' Yes, in the song at least, he shoots them.
   _ By Kathryn Baker, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
