<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 0934EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Gardening:Children     04-04 0715</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Gardening: Children,0729</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>GARDENING: Children</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL ARONSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Introducing youngsters to the marvels of plant life is one of
the educational benefits of a children's garden, which also
stimulates a sense of wonder and a respect for living things.
   That's the view of the Brooklyn Botanic Garden, where for 74
years more than 15,000 children have cultivated the same patch of
city land in the world's oldest continuous program of its kind.
   ``The success of the crops is only one of the rewards the
children reap,'' says Betsy Jacobs, the garden's associate director
of education, children's programs. ``Of equal importance are the
lessons they learn _ self-discipline, first-hand experience,
dignity of labor, generosity, respect for the rights and property
of others, respect for the environment, responsibility, and giving
of one's self.''
   Gardening is an acceptable way for youngsters to get dirt under
their fingernails and learn something valuable they will hold dear
for the rest of their lives. Even the difficult child can respond
with innocent wonderment to the miracle of growing things.
   How do parents or teachers involve youngsters in home gardening?
Here are some suggestions from specialists:
   _ Start small: 5 square feet is a large responsibility for a
child. Begin with seeds, because if you buy plants, your child will
miss out on the cycle of seeds, soil, sun and water. The best way
for a child to learn is by watching, so keep the coaching to a
minimum. Let them watch you for a while before you turn them loose
to plant.
   _ Never water or care for the plants yourself, except when
helping very young children. Don't lay a guilt trip on the child if
flowers or vegetables die of neglect. Say nothing; the child
learned a lesson that may stick.
   _ Put a low wire edging around the child's garden, which may be
a separate area in the home garden or a bit of separate land. The
wire is intended to keep out siblings, household pets and adult
feet. It also gives the child a sense of ownership. Let your young
gardener pull up some flowers if he or she wants to and to make
bouquets in vases or foil-lined cans.
   _ A simple device to help children water plants is a roller
paint tray with holes perforated with a nail. Plant seeds in rows
parallel to the tray about 6 inches away. The tray can be filled
with a small bucket and will act as a reservoir. A water hose in
the hands of a little one tends to wash away seeds and knock over
seedlings _ and soak the child.
   _ Manure water or a weak solution of fertilizer can be used
occasionally to demonstrate that plants can benefit from extra
feedings. Explain what plant foods do for flowers and vegetables.
   _ Let the child be a part of the process of selecting what to
plant, but remember that ease and dependability are big factors.
   It would be difficult to find an easier-to-grow, more dependable
and spectacular plant than annual sunflowers. Children will get a
kick out of growing such enormous plants. The seeds are easy to
handle and quick to sprout. Few insects bother sunflowers. Beans
and summer squash seeds also are easy to handle.
   Climbing vines such as morning glories also make good first
flowers, but you should string these plants up a fence or sturdy
pole. Easy flower varieties include marigolds, zinnias and cosmos.
   Another idea is to buy mixtures of flower seeds ready-made for
children. Some are sold as ``Annual Flower Mixture,'' ``Cutflower
Mixture,'' or ``Wildflower Mixture.'' Any of these can produce
beautiful species and curiosities. These mixtures thrive even if
not thinned much, fed, or watered for a while.
   The idea is to get the child's attention and hold interest with
projects that get quick or spectacular results.
   First show children the dry or ``sleeping'' seeds and how they
``wake up'' when moistened or planted. Line the inside of a clear
glass or jar with seeds a few inches apart. Put a lid on, leave the
jar on a kitchen counter, making sure the towel remains wet. In a
few days, seeds will swell and burst open, roots will grow down
while stems and leaves grow up.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880404-0225 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 0936EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Gardening:WithChildren-Radishes     04-04 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Gardening: With Children-Radishes,0263</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>GARDENING: With Children-Radishes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The Brooklyn Botanic Garden, whose Children's Garden was
initiated in 1914, says it has never produced a satisfactory answer
to ``the radish question,'' explaining:
   ``Every year, there has been a Saturday in late April when
packets of seeds are given to several hundred city children. The
soil is carefully worked and the seeds dropped into rows according
to arrangements meticulously worked out on graph paper during
classroom sessions weeks before.
   ``The first harvest comes in about six weeks. The first harvest,
inevitably, is radishes. The child, never having produced a miracle
before, bears them home in triumph.
   ``Then comes, for a mother, the supreme test of her nurturing
ability. How do you respond to this peculiar prize without
diminishing the young gardener's enthusiasm and self-esteem?
   ``The lettuce and tomatoes are still weeks and months away,
respectively, so you can't make a salad. To fry a radish is out of
the question. A little bit may punch up a casserole, but there's no
way it can be a main ingredient. The child wants everyone to make a
meal of the first crop, which is indeed a miracle given the
circumstances.
   ``What's a mother to do?
   ``It is estimated that each child, on a certain Saturday in
June, takes home an average of 73 radishes. As this has been
happening since 1914, it means that the heroic mothers or Brooklyn
and other New York City boroughs have had as many as 2 million
radishes to deal with.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880404-0226 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 0937EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Gardening:GiantVegetables     04-04 0689</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Gardening: Giant Vegetables,0704</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>GARDENING: Giant Vegetables</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY702</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   There's no guarantee that you'll break any giant vegetable
growing records _ such as the 671-pound pumpkin and 595.5-pound
squash _ but you can try.
   Here are a few suggestions to help you on your way to fame, fun
and not much fortune.
   The record pumpkin, 12-feet-11-inches in circumference, won top
prizes at 1986 World Pumpkin Confederation Weigh-Offs for Robert
Gancarz, a Jacobstown, N.J., vegetable farmer. The squash was grown
by his brother, Edward.
   The previous record pumpkin, grown in 1984 at Chelan, Wash.,
weighed 612 pounds and the top squash had been 513 pounds.
   At the competition in Collins, N.Y., it took 12 men to move the
giant pumpkins from a forklift to a truck scale. The pumpkins were
so big and heavy that they grew flat on one side and each ridge was
wider than a man's foot.
   The first step in growing a giant vegetable, says a Michigan
State University horticulturist, is to pick a giant variety in
buying seeds. Major seed companies often offer a number of large
varieties.
   When it comes to big vegetables, the secret really is genetic.
If you plant seeds of ordinary-size vegetables, no matter how much
fertilizer, water, sunlight and care you provide, you'll still have
ordinary-size vegetables. But if you plant seed for giants and
provide all those growing aids, you'd better have a lot of growing
and storage space.
   For instance, Atlantic Giant pumpkin seed produces fruit big
enough to hold a person and the variety has weighed in at 495.5
pounds. Big Max seed often produces 100-150 pounders.
   For giant winter squash, try Hungarian Mammoth or Mammoth King,
which may tip the scale at 400 pounds (not unusual at 250 pounds).
An edible huge squash is Pink Banana, 3 feet long and 8 inches in
diameter, weighing 50-60 pounds.
   Give your plants a head start to gain big size by planting the
seeds very early indoors in large containers. You want six-week-old
transplant to put into the garden after the soil warms in spring.
   Prepare the garden area as soon as you can work the soil. A high
spot has better drainage and a longer growing season than a low
place where cold air collects and frost comes early.
   Remember that a giant squash vine will be 30 to 40 feet long, so
plant where it will be out of the way. Give plants about 10 square
feet in which to straggle. Bush-type pumpkins and squash are being
developed.
   After you work the soil, add fertilizer at the rate recommended
for general vegetable gardening and cover with black plastic mulch
to warm the soil. The mulch also helps minimize the shock of
transplanting, discourages weed growth and conserves moisture.
   Set the plants in the ground through slits in the plastic mulch
as early as feasible, being careful not to damage roots. Shield
plants against cold with a hot cap or other covering, removing the
cover in the morning to protect it from the sun's baking heat.
   Pick all female flowers until the vine is about 8 feet long. The
female flowers are those with miniature fruit at the stem end. The
others are male. This will give the vine growth needed to support
big fruit. Let the second or third female flower set fruit and pick
off all other female flowers that follow as soon as they appear.
   Examine the vine and pick flowers at least three times a week.
To keep vines healthy, an insect and disease control program and
weekly watering in dry periods are necessary. Extra fertilizer
isn't necessary unless obvious nutrient problems appear.
   To improve the shape of your giant vegetables, roll the fruit a
quarter of a turn every week or 10 days. You can do this, however,
only while the fruit is small and the stem is not yet woody. After
this, rolling fruit is apt to break it from the vine.
   For maximum size, let your pumpkin, squash, watermelon or other
giant vegetables grow until the vine is dead or at least nearly dry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880404-0227 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 0947EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Gardening:Begonias     04-04 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Gardening: Begonias,0475</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>GARDENING: Begonias</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY701</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   For a shaded spot in the garden, on the patio, window box or
hanging basket, the exquisite tuberous begonia will bring brightly
colored flowers often 5 to 6 inches across.
   Begonia tuberhybrida produces spectacular blooms, just right for
terraces. Drooping or pendulous varieties are known as hanging
basket types but flowers are smaller _ and more numerous.
   Getting a good head start indoors in spring is the secret of
getting a season-long display outdoors.
   The tubers generally are priced according to size but you don't
have to have the biggest tubers to get the best results. Buy firm
tubers. Soft ones indicate rot.
   If sprouting eyes are not visible, put the tubers on a mixture
of peat moss and sand in equal parts and water them. Cover the
tubers with sphagnum peat, moisten it and keep the pot (with one or
two tubers) or the flat in 70-degree temperature. In two weeks or
so, tiny pinkish eyes should appear.
   Plant the tubers, inverted side up, in regular potting soil or a
mix of sand peat or perlite and garden loam (one third each).
Begonias need a well-drained medium and lots of moisture.
   In planting tuberous begonias in individual pots, set the top of
the tuber with the sprouting eyes an inch or two below the surface.
A fairly wide pot is recommended since roots form around the sides
of the tuber and spread outward. Begonias are shallow-rooted so the
pot need not be very deep. A pot 7-8 inches across is adequate for
one tuber.
   For good growth indoors, set pots in a sunny window or
supplement with artificial light 12-16 hours a day. Poor light
means elongated and spindly steams. Because begonias are heavy
feeders, fertilize every two weeks with liquid nutrients at
recommended rates.
   After frost danger ends, set plants outdoors, directly into the
ground or sink their pots in well-drained soil. Avoid soggy
conditions.
   It will be helpful to set stakes, such as 2-foot tall slender
bamboo poles, beside each growing stalk when the plants are set
out. Large flowers will need support. Stalks may break otherwise on
windy or rainy days.
   A light mulch of peat moss on the soil around begonias will
conserve moisture. Feed regularly to encourage good flower
production throughout summer.
   Begonia flowers, red, white, pink yellow or bi-colored picotte
have been called mimics of the plant world because they resemble
roses, camellias and carnations, but are odorless.
   Putting potted plants in wire baskets lined with sphagnum moss
will conserve moisture.
   Lift begonias from the garden or containers before heavy frost
and let them cure in a cool place in perlite or peat or in the same
pot, for replanting next season.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880404-0228 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 0948EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Gardening:Fertilizers     04-04 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Gardening: Fertilizers,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>GARDENING: Fertilizers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Soils must do more than provide a home for plant roots. They
must also supply nutrients for growth, such as nitrogen, phosphorus
and potasium, plus micronutrients including copper, zinc,
manganese, iron and molybdenum.
   Garden fertilizers thus are a fine investment when you know the
correct elements and quantities to apply.
   In their natural state, soils rarely contain enough nutrients
for the best growth of plants. Generally, it is necessary to
supplement the earth's store of plant nutrients for the most
vigorous lawn, abundant flowers or the greatest yield of tasty and
nutritious vegetables. Plants use large amounts of nitrogen,
phosphorus and potassium, so these nutrients are most likely to be
deficient in the soil.
   The best way to know what fertilizer is needed is a soil test.
Your county Cooperative Extension Service can help with this.
   Soil experts advise that it is usually wasteful, perhaps even
harmful, to use the wrong fertilizers. A soil test allows you to
give your plants what they need in the most useful proportions.
   How can you tell the proportion of each element in a fertilizer
from the numbers on the bag? A mixture labeled 5-10-5, for
instance, contains 5 percent total nitrogen, 10 percent available
phosphoric oxide, and 5 percent soluble potash.
   Most ordinary farm fertilizers are granulated or pelleted
material. Some may be available in powdered or concentrated forms.
Powdered types may not be desirable because they are too dusty.
However, fertilizer concentrates in liquid form are readily
available to the plants and can be applied to the foliage if
diluted 100 times by volume with water.
   Organic fertilizers also help. What are they? They are any
biodegradable refuse such as animal manure, compost, leaves, weeds,
straw, sawdust, wood chips, garbage, even paper. While organic
matter is an excellent ingredient, it has a low plant nutrition
content and a large amount is needed to correct a soil nutrient
deficiency.
   Fertilizer application is only one step in effective soil
management. For best growth, lawns, vegetable and ornamentals also
need suitable soil acidity, soil structure and moisture.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880404-0229 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 0949EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Gardening:Water     04-04 0570</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Gardening: Water,0581</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>GARDENING: Water</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY700</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL ARONSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Gardeners know nature is forgiving when their flowers and
vegetables flourish despite their errors. Yet there's one gardening
mistake nature won't forgive: watering plants too little or too
much.
   ``There's nothing more important to plants than water,'' says
gardening authority Dorrie Sillman. ``The main day-to-day problem
facing gardeners is delivering the right amount of water to the
soil.''
   Seeds will not germinate without water, she says. Without it, a
plant's biological processes cease. Water also gives plants their
shape and stiffness. Nutrients must dissolve in water before plants
can use them. At the same time, a plant cannot obtain sufficient
nutrients in waterlogged soil.
   In her garden in Holland, Pa., Miss Sillman tests power tools _
including a tiller, portable sprayer and chipper _ designed to
assist suburban gardeners with their year-round chores.
   ``Irregular, insufficient watering is the biggest mistake,
particularly during hot, dry summer weather,'' she says. ``You must
provide enough water to penetrate the soil to the level of a
plant's roots. Surface water will evaporate in the heat of the
sun.''
   Miss Sillman, who counsels users of Mantis Manufacturing Co.
equipment on planting and maintaining small-plot gardens, offers
these tips:
   _ How to tell if soil requires water: Pick up a handful of
topsoil and squeeze it into a ball. The soil has sufficient
moisture if the ball holds its shape. If the ball crumbles easily,
the soil needs water. Ideally, water when half the moisture the
soil can hold has dried out.
   _ How much water the soil needs: Water should soak into the soil
at least 6 inches to a foot deep to reach plant roots. In general,
this means applying about an inch of water over the entire area of
your garden. The lighter, more sandy your soil, the deeper this
amount of water will penetrate. Mere surface sprinkling encourages
shallow roots which are vulnerable to scorching in the hot sun.
   _ How to water the soil: Early in the season, when plant root
systems have not developed, hand watering will not take much time.
With a hose spray attachment that breaks the force of water, it's
healthier for the delicate plants, too.
   As root systems develop, however, you will need to find a more
efficient way to distribute water.
   Sprinklers attached to hoses or sprinkler hoses (perforated
plastic hoses) will provide a constant even supply of water to your
garden from above the soil. You can place a tin can with a 1-inch
mark from its bottom in the path of a sprinkler to easily tell when
the sprinkler has delivered sufficient water to penetrate the soil
to the right depth.
   _ How often to water: Soil conditions, weather, the kinds of
plants you grow affect the frequency of watering. Vegetables, in
general, need twice as much water as flowers. Newly planted trees
and shrubs require frequent watering, especially in dry weather.
Plants sheltered by walls or hedges may need watering even after a
rainstorm, but they will not dry out as fast as plants in the open.
Plants high on a slope will dry out faster than those at the
bottom. Plants growing in light, sandy soil need water more often
than those growing in heavier soil.
   A good rule of thumb: make sure your garden gets 1 inch of water
per week throughout the growing season.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880404-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 0949EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Gardening:Compost     04-04 0615</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Gardening: Compost,0632</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>GARDENING: Compost</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY703</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL ARONSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A compost pile is a beneficial way to dispose of household
refuse, crop residue and autumn leaves, while producing your own
supply of organic matter for the garden.
   Almost any family can develop a compost pile that also offers
environmental advantages. Starting and maintaining a compost pile
is not complicated. There are special attractive, sophisticated
bins made for this purpose but really all you need is a bottomless
receptacle of boards or chicken wire in which to collect material.
   The size of the bin will depend on the size of your garden, with
an average dimension of about 6-feet-by-6-feet. It can be hidden
behind trees, at the edge of the garden, or near an outbuilding.
   My compost bin is fashioned of heavy wire with six sides which
help support tomato plants that are fed nutrients by the pile's
contents.
   Rather than adding to a community's waste disposal burden,
composted refuse becomes a valuable fertilizer and soil
conditioner. Apply it to the garden at a rate of at least a pailful
to the square yard each year. Mix the compost thoroughly with the
topsoil to a depth of 6 to 10 inches, or apply it as a ulch on the
soil surface.
   A major garden problem is poor soil, not so much the fertility
but the structure. Compacted loam, sandy and clay soils discourage
plant growth even when fertilizer is added. Compacted soils lock up
nutrients; sandy soils leach away, clay soils restrict freedom of
root growth.
   The most effective remedy in such a situation is compost, with
its fibrous structure and pockets of air allowing plant roots
freedom to breathe.
   Compost not only improves soil texture, it adds beneficial
micro-organisms that manufacture plant nutrients and help fight
soil diseases.
   Frequent questions about compost and answers:
   _ Does compost have any value as a fertilizer?
   Yes, if it is made from materials that contain essential plant
nutrients. Animal manures and green wastes such as grass clippings
and green leaves are a source of nitrogen; bone meal and rock
phosphate are a source of phosphorus, and wood ashes (in limited
quantities) are an excellent source of potash. Compost also
conditions the soil, improves the moisture-holding capacity of
sandy soils and breaks up sticky, cold clay soils.
   _ What materials are best for composting?
   From the house: fruit and vegetable peelings, shredded
newspapers, eggshells, coffee grounds, tea bags, wood ashes, cotton
and wool rags. From the garden: grass clippings, hedge trimmings,
weeds, shredded leaves, animal manures, including poultry. Leaves
and fibrous weed roots are best shredded with a lawn mower to speed
decomposition.
   _ How long does it take to make compost?
   That depends on the method used and time of year. Warm
temperatures hasten decomposition. With a compost bin, which
prevents waste materials from drying out or becoming waterlogged,
it's possible to have useful compost within six weeks.
   _ Do compost heaps need turning?
   With an exposed compost pile the sides have a tendency to dry
out and so turning the heap will ensure thorough decomposition.
Turning an exposed heap also aids aeration. With an enclosed bin,
ventilation from below and along the sides provides adequate
aeration without the need for turning. Also, the protection
provided by a bin extends fermentation to all areas of the heap.
   _ Can compost feed lawns?
   Yes, and the time to apply it is in fall. Spread it evenly over
lawn areas and during winter the compost will work its way into the
existing soil. By spring it will be all gone, absorbed into the
upper soil surface helping the grass to grow thick and healthy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880404-0231 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 0955EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Gardening:Evergreens     04-04 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Gardening: Evergreens,0392</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>GARDENING: Evergreens</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   In most parts of this country, September is a good time to plant
evergreen trees to enhance the landscape _ but which varieties best
suit your purposes?
   First, make up your mind what should be their ultimate height
and general shape. Then study your catalogs or visit your favorite
nursery.
   If you want a large tree, consider the pines, spruces and firs.
These include the white, red and Scotch pines, all making
broad-headed trees eventually. Among the spruces, the Colorado blue
is familiar and beautiful, and the Norway is popular. Also well
known are the white, Black Hills and Englemann (especially in the
West) spruces. Among the first, consider the blue-tinted white fir,
the whitish-barked Arizona fir and the Douglas fir (the latter not
a true fir). Soft and graceful are the hemlocks, both eastern and
western.
   For trees of moderate-size and less spreading there are red
cedars (often called junipers) for dry places, arbor-vitae for wet
areas, and plume cypress (retinosporas) often used in foundation
plantings. The red cedars and arbor-vitae come in various forms and
color tones, such as Rocky Mountain juniper. The plume cypress
offers large variety _ fan foliage, plume, feathery and threadlike.
All three species grow quite tall _ to 30 feet or more in time.
   Rarer varieties are the Japanese cryptomeria and the umbrella
pine or sciadoptiys, both fairly narrow trees. Even narrower are
the Irish, Columnar Chinese, Italian or Arizona junipers.
   For hedges, yews are excellent and for low, flat forms there are
spreading junipers of a number of kinds.
   All of these may be planted in early and mid-fall. Prepare the
soil well. Dig holes two to three times the size of the root ball.
The soil to go around the roots should be made water-retentive by
adding 10-20 percent peat and fertilized with half as much dried
cow manure before shoveling the mixture in. Wait until growth
starts in spring before adding a chemical fertilizer.
   In all cases, water well, stake if support is necessary, and
mulch with 2 inches of peat, leaves, shredded bark or any similar
organic product.
   Finally, at the onset of winter and again in February, spray
trees with an antitranspirant (such as Foli-gard or Wilt-Pruf) to
hold in moisture.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880404-0232 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 0955EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Gardening:Vacation     04-04 0212</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Gardening: Vacation,0215</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>GARDENING: Vacation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Don't worry about your plants if you are going on a short
vacation, say four to five days or a week.
   Set a group of plants on thoroughly soaked bath towels in the
bathtub, kitchen sink or laundry tub, exposed to some light, but
not direct sunlight. Then open the water faucet so that one drop of
water falls every few seconds on the towels. (Leave the drain
open.) The towels will conduct the moisture to the plant's soil,
keeping plants in good condition until you get home.
   If you have leftover vegetable and flower seeds and want to
store them for next season, keep them cool and dry. Store them in
tightly closed glass jars in a cool, dark place such as a dry
basement or garage. Under these conditions, they should keep well
and germinate when you plant them next spring.
   If your African violets appear a bit sickly, examine them for
small white specks on the leaves and stems. These probably are
scale insects or mealybugs that suck the juice from the plants.
They eventually will kill the plants if not stopped.
   Most garden shops have specially prepared sprays for delicate
plants such as the African violet.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880404-0233 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 0955EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Gardening:CityGardening     04-04 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Gardening: City Gardening,0586</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>GARDENING: City Gardening</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PRUDENCE HELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Air, light, space, soil, water. Work and greater
or lesser amounts of money. These basics for gardening have their
own dimensions in cities.
   Take air _ and pollution. Perhaps it's not as bad as one might
think, experts say. Wind carries some of it away. And nowadays,
industries are often located in industrial parks outside towns. The
rooftop gardener may have another air problem, though _ too much
wind. A bit of fencing or a windbreak of bushes can help this
situation.
   Light can be quirky in the city. Apartment windows, terraces,
patios, backyards and rooftop gardens hemmed in by tall buildings
may get most of their light from only one direction, or little
light at all except in mid-summer when the sun is most directly
overhead.
   But if the sun does strike one section of a terrace or walled
garden, white paint or reflecting material on that area will pitch
the light to the opposite side.
   In the case of little light, the city gardener will have to
settle for shade-loving plants. But he can still have a green sea
of ferns, myrtle, ajuga and hosta lilies, and colorful caladiums,
impatiens, begonias, astilbe, bulbs and the like, with ivy draping
his walls.
   In rooftop gardens, meanwhile, the sun may blaze down. Again,
the key to success is choosing the right plants. Zinnias and
tomatoes will love that sun.
   Garden books, seed catalogs, nurserymen and garden stores can
help one choose suitable plants.
   Precious space in the city can be stretched. Plants can be hung
from walls and ceilings and placed on shelves. Tomatoes, cucumbers
and other vining vegetables can be grown upward instead of outward.
   Most city gardening is done in containers. What soil should one
use?
   Many experts advise against soil dug up from a country friend's
garden. Soils become compacted more easily in limited space and may
not drain well.
   Some suggest mixtures _ for instance, equal parts of commercial
potting mix, compost or vermiculite, and common garden soil; or two
parts of compost and one part of garden soil with enough builders'
sand (or vermiculite) added to give the mixture a gritty feeling.
Some favor a soilless mix.
   Many gardeners agree that there's no set rule for watering
plants except not to let them get too dry or too wet and that one
thorough watering is better than several shallow ones. Different
plants have different water needs. But a rule of thumb for many
plants might be: if the soil is dry to a depth of one inch, water
it. Poke a finger into the soil to find out. Rooftop gardens may
need extra waterings.
   One way to water indoor plants thoroughly is to soak the
containers in a few inches of water in a bathtub.
   Just about anything will do for a container, it seems _ plastic
tubs and wastepaper baskets, bushel baskets, old wine cases and the
like. Just be sure they have drainage holes very near the bottom of
the container. Or one can pay big bucks for terra cotta, redwood
and decorative stone containers, or make one's own window boxes.
   Seed is an inexpensive way to start plants, but it takes time
and work to grow it, and the conditions may not be right. In that
case, buying plants may be the best bet.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880404-0234 </DOCNO>
