<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 0956EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Gardening:CommunityGardens     04-04 0656</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Gardening: Community Gardens,0676</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<BYLINE>GARDENING: Community Gardens</BYLINE>
<HEAD>(EDITORS: Guerillas cq in 2nd and 13th grafs; GreenThumb cq in
last graf)</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY704</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PRUDENCE HELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A garden with grape arbor and a lily pond on New
York's Bowery ... a children's fantasy garden on Chicago's North
Side ... a Laotian garden in Bridgeport, Conn. ... a garden plot at
a detoxification rehabilitation facility in Knoxville, Tenn.
   They all have one thing in common: they are community gardens,
as often as not the greening of a vacant lot in an underprivileged
neighborhood of an inner city. The people of the neighborhood dig,
prune, plant under the guidance of people who help with equipment
and know-how _ New York City's Green Guerillas, for instance, the
U.S. Department of Agriculture's Cooperative Extension Service,
Knoxville County's Green Thumb.
   The American Community Gardening Association counts more than
260 member organizations. Its president, Brenda Funches, says it
plans to expand its membership, education and training of
professionals in the entire field of ``community greening.''
   The vacant lot for a community garden is often rented from the
city or other owner for a token dollar-a-year. So it may be ``here
today, gone tomorrow.'' Developers have sharp eyes for vacant lots
and big bucks to pay for them. However, progress toward longer-term
leases is reported in some cities. And if one site goes, others may
be found.
   In Bridgeport, more than 11,000 adults and 900 youths were
involved in the Urban Gardening Program last year. About half were
black, with Hispanics, whites, Asians and Pacific islanders, and
American Indians making up the rest, in that order. On a total
garden area of less than 8 acres, about $234,000 in produce was
grown. And, as its report pointed out, that does not include
``increased personal education and food skills, self-esteem,
neighborhood pride and cooperation, better public health and safety
from cleaned open space areas, better diets, community involvement,
and satisfaction in accomplishment.'' One garden is the work of
about 15 families of Laotian refugees.
   In Michigan, the Wayne County Senior Citizen's Gardening and
Greenhouse Association gardens more than 1 million square feet of
land and 9,000 square feet of greenhouse space. It is listed in the
``Guinness Book of World Records'' as the largest community garden
project in the world.
   Philadelphia Green, run by the Pennsylvania Horticultural
Society, works with more than 600 inner city groups on more than
1,000 gardening projects.
   The U.S. Agriculture Department, through its Cooperative
Extension Service, sponsors community gardening programs in 21
cities.
   In Knox County, Tenn., community gardens are part of the
Nutrition Project, designed to make more and better quality food
available at lower prices to low-income families.
   Children can be enthusiastic gardeners.
   In Graceland West, on Chicago's North Side, a garden blending
each of 13 children's ideas of a fantasy garden includes a shooting
star, cloud-9, a castle on a hill and a green caterpillar _ all
made of flowers and field weeds. The National Gardening Association
has a grant program that helps thousands of young gardeners each
year. Philadelphia Green helps indoor and outdoor gardening
projects in public schools.
   Meanwhile, New York's Green Guerillas have a special project at
a shelter for homeless men on Wards Island. Last year, they got
them to garden. This year, they plan to give the men horticultural
training in hopes some may get jobs.
   Then there's the garden on New York's Bowery that had a bumper
crop of apples last year _ and has beehives to produce honey.
   Local artists have been drawn into community gardening _
creating murals or sculpture to enhance the plots.
   ``Community garden is a metaphor for community development,''
says Jane Weissman, who heads New York's Operation GreenThumb. The
gardens become social centers, she says. Parties and barbecues are
held there. And people working together in the gardens decide to
tackle other projects in their neighborhoods.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880404-0236 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 0957EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Gardening:Herbs     04-04 0495</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Gardening: Herbs,0514</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>GARDENING: Herbs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PRUDENCE HELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rosemary stands for constancy and remembrance _
as Ophelia recalled in ``Hamlet.''
   The ancient Greeks used thyme as a temple incense and it is
prized today as a honey plant.
   Fennel, in literature and legend, is a symbol of flattery, a
remedy for failing eyesight and an aphrodisiac.
   To many of us, these and other herbs with equally intriguing
backgrounds are just those small containers of dried stuff on the
spice rack in the kitchen. And yet they had to grow somewhere. Why
not in one's own garden, or on the window sill?
   Herbs are not difficult to cultivate, take up little room, can
be grown indoors or out, in natural sunlight or under artificial
light. They are decorative and smell good as well as being edible
both fresh and dried. Relatively low in sodium, they're touted
these days as a way to give pizazz to salt-free or low-salt diets.
And there's the satisfaction of having produced something oneself.
   Some herbs are well-known _ basil, marjoram, oregano, thyme,
parsley. Somewhat less known, perhaps, are dill and fennel, savory,
chervil, horsemint, tarragon. Catnip is an herb (cat owners take
note).
   One of the largest families of herbs is basil: holy basil (it
smells like cloves); lemon, cinnamon and licorice basils (smelling
like what their names suggest); purple ruffles basil and ball
basil, as well as what we generally eat as plain basil.
   Not all herbs are used for eating. Some are dried and used as
air fresheners and sachets for drawers and closets (lavender and
lemon balm, for instance). Some are used in dried bouquets
(ambrosia and artemesia); some as decorative garden plants (catmint
with its aromatic silver foliage and lavender-blue flowers,
tricolor sage, with violet flowers and leaves marked in red, green
and white, gold edge thyme).
   Most herbs like lots of sun (basil is an exception, liking only
moderate amounts). Thalassa Cruso, in ``Making Vegetables Grow,''
says herbs have the strongest flavor if grown in rather sweet soil.
In the case of acid soil, add ground limestone. Some herbs are so
low they're used as ground covers, some can grow two or more feet
high.
   Herbs can be mixed with the flowers in a garden, used as borders
for flower beds, planted on the fringes of vegetable plots, given a
garden patch all their own, grown indoors on a window sill or on
shelves with fluorescent light. The ambitious gardener can create
an elaborate, decorative ``knot'' of herbs, as was popular in
Elizabethan times.
   Some herbs are perennial, some annual. Most can be grown from
seed, but in the case of some slow growers _ rosemary, for instance
_ buying plants is often recommended.
   Many botanic gardens and other public gardens have areas devoted
to herbs, where one can get ideas.
   As for using herbs, there are recipes and ideas galore, in
newspapers, books and magazines.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880404-0237 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 1001EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Gardening:Therapy     04-04 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Gardening: Therapy,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>GARDENING: Therapy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   At the Shepherd Spinal Center in Atlanta, spinal-injured
patients develop gardening skills in garden beds specially designed
for wheelchairs.
   At the Perkins School for the Blind in Watertown, Mass., the
visually impaired get the same sense of accomplishment, physical
exercise and self-reliance in growing their own food as any other
gardener. Their planting can be done with pelleted seed, seed tape
or self-wrapped seeds.
   It's all part of an apparently growing interest in horticulture
as therapy for the mentally and physically disabled, senior
citizens and other people with special needs. More than 23,000 such
people are served daily by members of the American Horticultural
Therapy Association, which was formed in 1973.
   Working with plants is a form of therapy at about 300 hospitals,
the AHTA says.
   The Institute for Rehabilitation Medicine at New York University
Medical Center opened a horticultural therapy greenhouse in 1959
for victims of strokes and other physical disabilities. And
horticultural therapy is a program at the Florida Alcohol Treatment
Center.
   At the University of Nebraska Medical Center, gardening is part
of the therapy for older patients.
   ``Many nursing home residents, many from farm backgrounds, know
more about plant care than some of their caretakers,'' says Elaine
Matthis, of Elkhorn, Neb., who works with the elderly at the center.
   ``The problem with older adults is that sometimes there is a
sense of lost productivity. So maybe they can't work behind a
tiller, but they may be able to work with container gardening or at
a raised garden,'' she says. ``For people getting confused, who
need to resolve feelings of the past, who need to reminisce, it's
important to facilitate their thinking of the past.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880404-0238 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 1004EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Gardening:Misconceptions     04-04 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Gardening: Misconceptions,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>GARDENING: Misconceptions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   How does your garden grow?
   Not with silver bells and cockle shells, despite the nursery
rhyme.
   It takes know-how to be a successful gardener and correcting
common misconceptions can make the difference, according to plant
care experts Jack Peters and Jim Knauss.
   The amateur gardener can increase the health potential of plants
throughout the year by knowing more about age-old assumptions that
aren't necessarily so, they say.
   ``In most of these cases, the amateur gardener tends to err on
the side of excess,'' says Knauss, who is manager of technical and
analytical information services at W.R. Grace & Co.'s Peter Plants
Food division. ``The healthiest plants are those that have the
benefit of simple, consistent attention.''
   One misconception, he says, is to always keep the soil surface
moist. ``A common practice,'' says Knauss, ``but one that can keep
plants and gardens from getting the air they need. The tell-tale
area is deeper within the soil. Before bringing out the watering
can, put a finger about 1-2 inches beneath the soil to test the
dryness. ... When watering, the liquid should go far beyond just
the surface, making sure the roots are fully moistened.''
   Another common idea to reassess is that selecting plants with
the lushest, greenest foliage at the garden center will ensure easy
care survival, says Peters, producer manager for Peters Plant Food.
   ``People tend to feel that a lush, healthy plant will remain
that way with a minimum of care and attention,'' he says. ``What
they don't see is the extent of the care that plant had been
receiving at the greenhouse or nursery. That particular plant may,
despite its looks, be quite difficult to maintain and keep healthy.
   ``Knowing about the variety and maintaining consistent
environments are the important determinants of long plant health,
not simply the original plant's appearance.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880404-0239 </DOCNO>
