<DOCNO> AP880404-0242 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 1005EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Gardening:Mowing     04-04 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Gardening: Mowing,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>GARDENING: Mowing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   When mowing the lawn this season, dress for safety is the
reminder from equipment manufacturers.
   ``Loose clothing can snag on controls or get caught in moving
parts, so tuck in shirttails and avoid dangling jewelry and flowing
scarfs,'' says Bob Tracinski, consumer information specialist for
John Deere, manufacturers of lawn and garden equipment.
   ``Wear slacks and hard shoes with non-slip soles to protect your
feet against hidden glass and sharp stones,'' he says.
   Other safety guidelines come from the Outdoor Power Equipment
Institute, a national trade association of manufacturers of gas and
electric-powered lawn and garden maintenance products:
   _ Review the operator's manual on how to set up equipment, how
to operate it safely and how to maintain it properly. Know where
the controls are and what they do.
   _ Handle gasoline carefully. Store gas in an approved container,
away from the house. Fill up before you start, while the engine is
cold.
   _ Before mowing, inspect the lawn for stones, sticks, wires,
toys and such. Be sure children and pets are a safe distance away.
   _ Mow in daylight. Don't mow wet grass.
   _ Mow in a forward direction; avoid cutting grass by pulling the
mower toward you. (If you must shift into reverse, make sure to
stop and check behind you, then back up slowly.)
   _ Keep hands and feet away from moving parts.
   _ Turn off the engine and remove the key if you need to leave
the equipment, even for a moment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880404-0243 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 1006EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Gardening:Eyes     04-04 0257</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Gardening: Eyes,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>GARDENING: Eyes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Gardeners who wear broad-brimmed hats, coveralls, and heavy-duty
gloves while using an electric hedge clipper to trim bushes are
displaying common sense _ but not enough of it, says the American
Optometric Association.
   The garb protects the face from the sun, and clothing and hands
from the wear and tear of yard work, but the eyes are left exposed
and vulnerable to flying twigs, leaves and other debris.
   Nearly 3,400 Americans suffer eye injuries from lawnmowers and
home gardening equipment each year, according to the industry trade
group, which says most of the injuries could be prevented by the
use of proper safety eyewear.
   The optometrists warn that lawnmowers, other cutting tools and
garden chemicals can turn a seemingly harmless pastime into a
vision-endangering activity, one in which regular eyeglasses or
contact lenses do not provide enough protection.
   By federal regulation, eyeglasses are impact-resistant but they
still can be shattered by rocks or twigs thrown by power tools, and
spray or dust from weed killers and fertilizers can get around them.
   Inexpensive plastic safety goggles _ some of which even fit over
regular eyeglasses _ will meet most home gardeners' eye safety
needs, according to the association, which also notes that
protection from the sun's harmful rays and clear, comflettuce, New Zealand
spinach and a variety of
herbs are suggestions.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Climbing plants may be supported by wrapping sphagnum or peat
moss around a broom handle and covering with meshed hardware cloth.
The pole should be anchored firmly in a sturdy, tip-proof clay or
other pot.
   Climbing foliage or other plants also may arrive from the
florist with supports made of bark, cedar, redwood or bamboo cane.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   If the lower leaves on your African violets appear to be rotting
and falling off, the problem may be petiole rot.
   This happens when the lower leaves rest on the pot rim. They get
droopy, then turn brown and soft and eventually shrivel. This
happens when fertilzier salts build up and injure the fragile
stems. Remove drooping leaves and cover pot rims with foil or tape
to prevent further problems.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
