<DOCNO> AP880404-0245 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 0848EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Japan-US-Trade     04-04 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-US-Trade,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan to Decide on Beef, Citrus Issue by May 4</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita said Japan will
decide its position on the beef and citrus dispute with the United
States by May 4, a report said Monday.
   Takeshita met with Agiculture Minister Takashi Sato at the Diet
building and complimented him for his work in dealing with the
Americans even though the talks broke down, Kyodo News Service said.
   Takeshita said the United States had expressed interest in
continuing talks, Kyodo reported.
   No officials could be reached at Takeshita's ruling Liberal
Democratic Party or at Diet (parliament) offices to confirm the
report.
   Sato held talks with U.S. trade and commerce officials last week
on increasing American access of these products to Japan, but the
negotiations broke down after Japan refused to do away with import
quotas. A four-year, bilateral agreement on quotas limiting
American beef and citrus imports to Japan expired last Thursday.
   The United States has said it will take the issue to the General
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade in Geneva, the 95-nation
international forum that can rule on trade disputes among its
members.
   May 4 is the day GATT convenes a special panel to hear the
American grievance.
   Earlier this year, another GATT panel ruled that Japanese import
quotas on beef products were illegal. A similar ruling is expected
if the GATT panel acts on the U.S. demand next month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
