<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   04-04 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0389</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn and soybean futures prices advanced while
wheat prices were mostly lower in early trading today on the
Chicago Board of Trade.
   Government reports on prospective spring plantings and grain
stocks sent soybean contracts to new highs and encouraged traders
to hedge by buying corn and beans while selling wheat, analysts
said.
   The Agriculture Department's annual report on farmers' spring
planting intentions, released Thursday, predicted about a 1 percent
increase in soybean acreage to 57.9 million acres. That figure was
well below the average pre-report estimate of 59.1 million acres.
   Buying also was encouraged by the the department's quarterly
report on grain stocks. The report estimated soybean stocks at
almost 1.15 billion bushels as of March 1, slightly below the
pre-report estimate.
   The reports showed corn planting intentions at 66.9 million
acres, up 2 percent from last year but slightly below expectations.
That figure was offset by the corn stocks estimate of 7.6 billion
bushels, slightly above estimates.
   The reports were ``bullish for beans, neutral for wheat and in
corn the stocks figure was bearish and the acreage figure was
bullish,'' said Victor Lespinasse, an analyst with Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc.
   In early trading, wheat was 1{ cent lower to 1 cent higher, with
the contract for delivery in May at $2.98{ a bushel; corn was 1
cent to 3\ cents higher, with May at $2.10} a bushel; oats were 3
cents to 5{ cents higher, with May at $1.64{ a bushel; and soybeans
were 13 cents to 15} cents higher, with May at $6.67{ a bushel.
   Cattle and hog prices rallied in early trading at the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .47 cent to 1.10 cents higher with the contract
for delivery in April at 75.37 cents a pound; feeder cattle were
.45 cent to .80 cent higher with April at 81.50 cents a pound; hogs
were .70 cent to 1.50 cents higher, with April at 46.25 cents a
pound; and pork bellies were 1.48 cents to 2 cents higher with May
at 57.60 cents a pound.
   Cattle and hog futures prices were mostly lower and pork bellies
were mixed in trading Thursday, the last day of trading before the
three-day holiday weekend.
</TEXT>
