<DOCNO> AP880404-0255 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 2306EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-Japan-ForeignMerchants Adv09-10   04-04 0762</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Foreign Merchants, Adv 09-10,0787</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 09</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 10</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions April 9-10 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Some Foreign Businessmen Get Help Cracking Japan's Markets</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN K. PAULSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When David Jackson of New Zealand packed up his
rugby shirt display to bring to Japan, he tossed in a sweatshirt
made from brightly colored scrap materials gathered from the shop
floor.
   Unfortunately, that's the one Japanese retailers liked.
   ``We did it as a joke,'' he said. ``Now they've ordered 2,000 of
them _ exactly the same as this one. These were one-of-a-kind
items,'' he said ruefully. ``I don't know how we're going to be
able to duplicate them.
   ``It just goes to show you that you can't second-guess the
Japanese market. We have to be ready to accept what the market
tells us.''
   Jackson was one of more than 200 exhibitors invited from 16
countries to display their sports products at a recent trade fair,
with help from the Japan External Trade Organization (JETRO).
   The fair is one way the Japanese government is trying to ease
friction with other countries after piling up a trade surplus of
$82.7 billion in 1987.
   Japan and the United States, for instance, have argued over
Japanese restrictions on beef and citrus imports as well as
American access to big Japanese construction projects. Still, there
are areas in which Japan is spending its own money to encourage
imports.
   Masahiro Suzuki, assistant director of the JETRO trade fair
department, said this _ the fifth such fair held since 1985 _ was
an important means of showing foreign businessmen they can compete
against Japanese products.
   The fair cost 200 million yen, or about $1.6 million, to produce
and exhibitors were charged $1,000 each, which means the Japanese
government paid more than $5,000 for each of the exhibits, Suzuki
said.
   ``Newcomers don't know how to approach the Japanese market. We
have to help them,'' Suzuki said.
   Other items featured at the five-day fair included pool tables,
gliders, surfboards, automatic golf tees, lawn bowling games,
crossbows, skateboards and puzzles. The Japanese were particularly
curious about the ``Hog Hair Pork Rind Bait'' available at the
California state booth, the guide to 750 American golf courses, and
the $3,700 electronic dart board set.
   Stefan Schinzinger, president of the San Francisco Hat Company,
said he received three invitations from the Japanese to attend this
year's trade show, and he finally accepted. He said it will take
him months to sort out the business prospects the show produced.
   Schinzinger said he also had to make adjustments for the
Japanese markets. One product was a sock with leather soles used by
space shuttle astronauts to keep their feet warm.
   ``The Japanese don't use leather on their slippers. They
suggested it might sell better without the leather, and be cheaper
to make. It just shows you can't force-fit an American product to
the Japanese market,'' he said.
   Schinzinger praised the Japanese government for taking steps to
help foreign businessmen sell their products, and said it was
impossible to get help on trade matters from the American
government.
   ``My experience with the U.S. government commercial office is
that they are there to help the large multinational companies. The
service I get (from the American government) is non-existent,'' he
said.
   Schinzinger said the fair on sports items was extremely popular
because there is little competition from the Japanese.
   ``The Japanese in the past haven't had any leisure time. They
worked six days a week, and spent one day at home with the family.
Now, they're being encouraged to work a five-day week, and sports
are becoming very popular.
   ``Now, everyone is going at it with the typical enthusiasm of
the Japanese. When they get into a sport, they want all the
knicknacks that go along with it.''
   Those attending the show included the public, retailers,
wholesalers and manufacturers.
   Schinzinger said many of the foreign participants were angered
at the visits by Japanese manufacturers.
   ``We know we're helping them develop new businesses,''
Schinzinger said. ``They come to the show, see what's popular, and
they'll make it themselves.''
   However, he said participants were promised six months of
product protection after the show, during which time they will have
an exclusive right to sell their products in Japan.
   ``That's enough time to file for a patent if you think your
product will do well here,'' he said.
   However, just to be sure, he took out an $800 patent on his
company's name before he left the United States.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions April 9-10</NOTE>
