<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     04-04 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0316</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market retreated today, faced with
rising interest rates and renewed uncertainties about
stronger-than-expected economic statistics.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 5.47 to 1,982.59
by 2 p.m. today on Wall Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by more than 2 to 1 in the overall
tally of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 425 up, 1,022
down and 427 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came 143.15 million shares with two
hours to go.
   A big chunk of the activity stemmed from trading strategies in a
few high-yielding stocks based on their impending dividend payments.
   The Dow Jones industrial average would have shown a considerably
wider loss but for the preformance of one of its components _ F.W.
Woolworth, which jumped 8[ to 53]. The company said it had received
notice that a group headed by Herbert Haft was seeking regulatory
approval to buy up to 15 percent of its stock.
   Otherwise, analysts said, stocks and bonds were giving a cool
response to the Labor Department's report that payroll employment
continued to grow at an unexpectedly fast pace in March, expanding
by 262,000.
   The figures were issued on Friday, when the markets were closed
for the Easter and Passover holidays.
   In the first bond-market trading since then, interest rates rose
today. Prices of long-term government bonds fell more than $10 for
each $1,000 in face value, putting their yields in the neighborhood
of 8.9 percent.
   Losers among the blue chips included International Business
Machines, down ] at 107\; Exxon, down | at 41], and American
Telephone & Telegraph, down { at 26{.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell
1.16 to 145.44. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down 1.31 at 295.12.
</TEXT>
