<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Woolworth-Dart Bjt   04-04 0751</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Woolworth-Dart, Bjt,0777</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woolworth: Hafts Intend to Acquire Retailer's Stock</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will be led with closing stock price</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   F.W. Woolworth Co. said Monday it received
notice that Dart Group Corp. intends to acquire a substantial
amount of the retailer's stock in what could be the beginning of a
takeover bid for the nation's 13th largest retailer.
   Woolworth, which built its reputation in the five-and-dime store
business before expanding into specialty retailing, responded to
Dart's move with the adoption by its board of a ``poison-pill''
takeover defense.
   The retailer said in a statement it was notified a partnership
controlled by Dart Chairman Herbert Haft had filed with federal
antitrust officials documents indicating the group intended to
acquire $15 million or more of Woolworth's stock.
   Less than a month ago, the Haft family dropped a $1.03 billion
bid for Stop & Shop Cos. after their target agreed to a leveraged
buyout by Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co.
   Wall Street expected the Hafts to make a bid for Woolworth. The
retailer's stock shot up $8.25 to $53.50 in late afternoon on the
New York Stock Exchange.
   The Hafts have said in the past they are serious about buying
and operating a retailer, but doubts linger about their intentions.
Dart's string of unsuccessful but profitable takeover attempts in
recent years has given Herbert Haft and his son, Dart President
Robert Haft, reputations as corporate raiders.
   Robert Haft was not available when a reporter called for comment
Monday.
   A source close to Dart confirmed that the partnership had made a
filing on March 18 with the federal government in compliance with
the Hart-Scott-Rodino antitrust act.
   Under the act, parties seeking to acquire a substantial stake in
a company must notify the government of their intentions.
   The source declined to say whether a takeover bid was in the
offing.
   Karen Sack, a retail industry analyst with Standard & Poor's
Corp., said Woolworth has been mentioned recently as a possible
target for a takeover attempt.
   Edward Johnson, an analyst with Prescott Ball & Turben Inc.,
said Wall Street believes Woolworth stock would be worth about $67
under a buyout. The low stock price and Woolworth's low-rental
properties and successful specialty store formats make it an
attractive target, he said.
   If the Hafts do make a bid, Woolworth would be expected to fight
it. In the company's statement, it said the retailer's board had
adopted the poison pill ``to deter coercive or unfair takeover
tactics and to prevent an acquirer from gaining control of the
company without offering a fair price to all shareholders.''
   The pill adopted by Woolworth's board would allow the company's
shareholders to buy its stock at a steep discount. It would go into
effect when a person or group acquires 20 percent of Woolworth's
stock, on the commencement of a tender offer for 30 percent or more
of the retailer's shares, or when an adverse party acquires at
least 15 percent of the company's stock.
   Joseph Carroll, a Woolworth spokesman, declined to comment when
asked what steps the company might take if and when the Hafts make
a takeover bid.
   Johnson said the company might consider going private under a
leveraged buyout.
   Other options open to the retailer include making an acquisition
itself or spinning off one of its units to shareholders.
   Woolworth, founded 109 years ago by Frank W. Woolworth as a
five-and-dime store, has grown to an empire of more than 6,300
general merchandise and specialty stores worldwide. In recent
years, the company has shifted its focus from its well-known
Woolworth stores to its specialty operations, which include Kinney
shoe stores and Foot Locker and Lady Foot Locker athletic footwear
stores.
   Ms. Sack said Woolworth ``has done very well'' as a result of
its restructuring.
   For the fiscal year ended Jan. 30, Woolworth earned $251 million
on sales of $7.14 billion.
   Before their unsuccessful attempt at taking over Stop & Shop,
the Hafts began a hostile bid for Dayton Hudson Corp. that they
were forced to end when the stock market crashed. Their previous
targets include Supermarkets General Corp. and Safeway Stores Inc.
   Dart has made hundreds of millions of dollars from their
takeover forays by selling their stock at a higher price after the
companies successfully defended themselves.
   Johnson said that if the Hafts are serious about buying a
retailer, Woolworth, with its specialty operations, would be an
appropriate target. Dart operates two specialty chains, Crown Books
and Trak Auto.
</TEXT>
