<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   04-04 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0289</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices soared and set new
contract highs while grains were mostly higher in trading Monday at
the Chicago Board of Trade.
   The Agriculture Department's reports on spring planting
intentions and grain stocks sparked a flurry on buying in the
soybean pit, where traders saw indications of tight soybean
supplies in the coming year.
   The department's annual report on farmers' spring planting
intentions, released Thursday, predicted about a 1 percent increase
in soybean acreage to 57.9 million acres _ well below the estimate
of 59.1 million acres.
   The department's quarterly grain stocks report estimated
soybeans at almost 1.15 billion bushels as of March 1, slightly
below the pre-report estimate.
   New contract highs were made in soybeans, but buying slacked off
amid heavy profit-taking later in the session, said Victor
Lespinasse, an analyst with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   Buying in new crop corn for delivery in deferred months was
sparked by the report showing spring planting intentions at 66.9
million acres, up 2 percent from last year but well below
expectations, Lespinasse said.
   But more bearish news came from the corn stocks estimate of 7.6
billion bushels, slightly above estimates.
   Wheat prices rose ``in sympathy with strength in the beans,''
Lespinasse said.
   At the close, wheat was } cents to 3 cents higher, with the
contract for delivery in May at $3.00\ a bushel; corn was } cent
lower to 3\ cents higher with May at $2.09 a bushel; oats were 2{
cents to 4} cents higher with May at $1.64 a bushel; and soybeans
were 15{ cents to 18} cents higher, with May at $6.69 a bushel.
</TEXT>
