<1ST_LINE>u f AM-ScotusRdp-Business Bjt   04-04 0558</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus Rdp-Business, Bjt,0578</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High Court Lets Libel Award Stand; Agrees to Review Liability
Rulings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Monday let stand a $3
million libel award won by cigarette maker Brown & Williamson
Tobacco Corp. against CBS Inc. and a television anchorman in
Chicago.
   In another significant case, the high court agreed to review
rulings limiting Korean Air Lines' financial liability for a 1983
disaster in which 269 people died _ the shooting down of a KAL
passenger jet over Soviet airspace.
   The justices also agreed to examine the authority of federal
judges to second-guess decisions by pension and welfare plans that
deny benefits to workers.
   In other decisions announced Monday in business-related cases,
the high court:
   _Refused to block the Federal Trade Commission from
investigating allegedly anti-competitive practices of state
agencies that license and regulate professionals.
   _Gave federal agencies more leeway in dealing with labor unions
representing their employees, and
   _Rejected a challenge to New York City's rent control law.
   In the tobacco libel decision the court, without comment,
rejected arguments that the $3 million award _ one of the largest
libel verdicts ever upheld on appeal _ violated the rights of CBS
and its newscaster.
   Brown & Williamson, which makes Viceroy cigarettes, accused the
network and WBBM-TV anchorman Walter Jacobson of libeling it in a
Nov. 11, 1981, broadcast. The Chicago station is owned and operated
by CBS.
   Jacobson was accused of libeling the cigarette company in a
nightly feature called ``Walter Jacobson's Perspective.''
   He said there was a Viceroy advertising strategy to attract
young people to smoking by relating cigarettes ``to pot, wine, beer
and sex.'' He said the idea was to present cigarette smoking as
``an initiation into the adult world ... as an illicit pleasure.''
   His remarks were based in part on what he said was a
confidential report prepared by the Federal Trade Commission.
   The Korean Air Lines case stemmed from the September 1983 air
disaster in which a Soviet military plane shot down KAL Flight 007
en route from New York City to Seoul, South Korea. The Korean
airliner had flown more than 300 miles off course after leaving
Anchorage, Alaska, and had entered Soviet airspace over the Sea of
Japan.
   The Supreme Court justices said they will study arguments that
Korean Air Lines should have to face more than $75,000 in damages
for each death.
   In the pension case, the court said it will hear an appeal by
Firestone Tire & Rubber Co. in a case stemming from the sale of its
plastics division in 1980.
   Firestone sold the division to Occidental Petroleum Corp. The
sale affected some 500 workers at Firestone plants in Pennsylvania,
New Jersey, Maryland and Louisiana.
   The workers then sought certain benefits from Firestone,
including early retirement and severance pay, that were included in
the company's pension and welfare plan.
   The company denied the benefits. It also refused to give the
workers information they requested about the benefit plan on
grounds they no longer were employed by Firestone.
   The workers sued in federal court, charging that the company
violated the federal Employee Retirement and Income Security Act of
1974 (ERISA).
   A judge threw out the suit on grounds that Firestone did not act
in an arbitrary and capricious manner. The 3rd U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals reinstated the suit, however.
</TEXT>
