<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Penney-EEOCAppeal     04-04 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Penney-EEOC Appeal,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Upholds J.C. Penney Co.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court Monday upheld J.C.
Penney Co.'s defense of a company policy which permits medical and
dental insurance coverage of a Penney employee's spouse only if the
spouse earns less than the employee.
   A three-judge panel of the 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
ruled 2-1 that the ``head of household'' provision of Penney's
insurance plan is lawful under Title VII of the federal Civil
Rights Act of 1964.
   The appeals court's majority ruled that the requirement is legal
because it is not sex-based, but is instead conditioned on a ``head
of household'' status.
   The court ruled against the Equal Employment Opportunity
Commission, which argued that the policy amounts to unequal
treatment of Penney's female employees and was therefore illegal
discrimination based on an employee's sex.
   U.S. District Judge Robert DeMascio in Detroit ruled at trial
that the policy did have an unequal impact on female employees, but
he said the EEOC had not proven that J.C. Penney Co. had a
discriminatory motive in adopting the requirement.
   The appeals court's majority ruled that DeMascio correctly
dismissed the EEOC's complaint because Penney's policy does not
violate federal civil rights law.
   The appellate majority found that Penney adopted the head of
household requirement in order to provide spouse insurance only for
employees who most needed the coverage _ those without more highly
paid spouses. The requirement also is an efficient administrative
tool for avoiding providing coverage of spouses most likely to have
coverage from their own employers, the appeals court's majority
said.
   ``This is a legitimate business justification for choosing this
method of supplying an insurance coverage benefit,'' the majority
ruled in an opinion written by appeals Judge Danny Boggs.
   In a minority dissent, Judge Douglas Hillman said he would have
reversed DeMascio's ruling. Hillman said he did not find Penney's
defense of its insurance coverage policy legitimate.
   ``Title VII's prohibition against compensation practices that
discriminate against women employees does not vary with the type of
compensation chosen by the employer,'' Hillman wrote.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
