<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 1548EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Carbide-Bhopal Bjt   04-04 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Carbide-Bhopal, Bjt,0476</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Union Carbide Ordered To Pay $192 Million in Bhopal Relief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DANBURY, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union Carbide Corp. said Monday it would
study a decision by a court in India before deciding whether to
appeal the court's order to pay $192 million in interim relief for
victims of the 1984 Bhopal gas disaster.
   But Carbide said from its headquarters in Danbury that the
ruling by the High Court in the central Indian state of Madhya
Pradesh ``will not serve the real needs of the Bhopal victims.''
   ``The high court judge is holding Union Carbide liable and this
can only result in additional litigation while the genuine victims
remain in the wings,'' said Robert M. Berzok, a Carbide spokesman.
   The court ruled Monday on Carbide's appeal of an earlier
decision in which a district judge ordered an interim relief
payment of $270 million. Union Carbide had argued that the interim
relief could prejudice a decision in the Indian government's $3
billion suit against the company.
   The ruling by the Madhya Pradesh court, which can be appealed to
India's Supreme Court, reduced the size of the interim award by $78
million and ordered Carbide to deposit the sum within two months.
   High Court Judge S.K. Seth said he made the reduction after
considering ``the needs of the victims.''
   Berzok said Carbide has about $192 million in insurance to cover
an interim relief payment.
   ``The fact that the court reduced the amount to Union Carbide
Corp.'s insurance coverage does not change the basic failure to
provide a trial showing the cause of the tragedy and the real
extent of the damages,'' Berzok said.
   In trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Union Carbide common
stock slipped 50 cents a share to $22.75.
   One analyst said Monday's ruling ``doesn't mean too much'' to
Carbide.
   James Wilbur, who follows Carbide for the investment firm Smith,
Barney, Harris, Upham and Co., said Carbide will probably appeal to
the Supreme Court.
   He said even if the Supreme Court rules against Carbide, Indian
authorities ``have to get approval from a U.S. court in order for
funds to be paid.''
   He said Carbide and the Indian government agreed before the
court proceedings began that a U.S. court would have the authority
to approve any final decision reached in India.
   The leak of toxic gas on Dec. 3, 1984, came from a pesticide
plant run by a company subsidiary, Union Carbide of India. It was
the world's worst industrial disaster, killing more than 2,800
people and injuring at least 20,000 around the plant in Bhopal,
capital of Madhya Pradesh.
   The Indian government sued Union Carbide in September 1986,
contending the leak was caused by negligence. The company has said
it resulted from sabotage by a disgruntled employee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
