<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Farmers-Batus     04-04 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Farmers-Batus,0597</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Company Approaches Farmers' Stockholders Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Batus Inc. approached stockholders of
Farmers Group Inc. on Monday with a proposal hinting at a possible
increase in the $63 per share bid for the nation's seventh largest
insurer.
   Batus said it would consider paying more ``in a friendly
transaction supported by the board of Farmers Group.''
   Batus has been trying since January to win control of the Los
Angeles company, but its directors have refused to negotiate with
Batus, the American subsidiary of the London-based BAT Industries
Inc. PLC.
   ``We saw their full-page ad in The Wall Street Journal and there
will be no comment,'' said Tom Welch, director of corporate
investments for Farmers.
   Wall Street reacted to the latest move by sending Farmers' stock
up 62{ cents per share to $59.62{ per share in over-the-counter
trading. Batus shares closed down 25 cents per share at $7.75 per
share on the American Stock Exchange.
   Batus, which also made its appeal by mail, accused Farmers'
board of failing to tell shareholders what would happen to the
price of their stock if Batus' $4.5 billion offer was defeated.
   The letter said the board has not offered any firm proposal
``designed to provide you with $63 or more for your stock. Instead
of writing to you, the board set forth its opinion that the company
should maintain its existence as an independent corporation.''
   Batus further charged the directors had been talking with a
third party about a possible leveraged buyout of the company.
   ``Don't you think it strange that they have failed to contact
Batus, the only company that has made a public offer for their
shares?'' Batus asked the stockholders.
   Batus described its current bid as a 47 percent premium over the
$43 market price just before the merger was proposed.
   Batus first approached stockholders last month, seeking proxies
in support of a non-binding resolution it intends to present at
Farmers' annual meeting May 20.
   The resolution would give stockholders an opportunity to express
their support for the sale and encourage Farmers' board to
facilitate such a sale, Batus said.
   Nine states would have to approve any takeover, said Gene
Russell, manager of communications for Batus.
   The California insurance commissioner has scheduled public
hearings May 4-6, with a decision expected by May 13, and the
Kansas Insurance Department has set up a hearing on proxy
solicitation on April 20. Earlier, the department reported that the
proxy solicitation might be illegal and may have to be halted.
   Farmers also operates in Arizona, Idaho, Illinois, Ohio, Oregon,
Texas and Washington.
   Russell said Monday that Batus was successful in challenging a
19-year-old Nevada law allowing stockholders only 60 days to decide
whether to take advantage of a tender offer from a hostile or
friendly bidder.
   A federal judge ruled the Nevada Takeover Act violates both the
supremacy and the commerce clauses of the Constitution and ordered
Nevada not to enforce it.
   The challenge was heard in Nevada because Farmers is incorported
there.
   Batus has extended the expiration date of its bid to April 27
and announced that as of March 29, approximately 3,570,000 shares
had been tendered.
   Batus owns tobacco, retailing and paper goods companies in the
United States, including Brown and Williamson Tobacco Corp., Saks
Fifth Avenue and Marshall Field's.
   Farmers, with about $11 billion in assets, is the nation's third
largest home and auto insurer and the seventh largest property and
casualty insurer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
