<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ConsumerConfidence     04-04 0188</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Consumer Confidence,0196</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Consumer Confidence Dips in March, Conference Board Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer confidence dipped slightly in March
amid concern about unemployment, according to a survey released
Monday.
   The Conference Board reported that its Consumer Confidence Index
slipped to 112.8 from 114.9 last month. The index has a 1985 base
of 100.
   ``Despite recently favorable employment figures reported by
Washington, virtually all of the decline in consumer confidence was
due to growing concern about jobs,'' said Fabian Linden, an
economist with the business research organization.
   The Conference Board said consumers are confident about general
business conditions, but 29 percent of the survey's respondents
said jobs were plentiful, down from 31 percent in February.
   ``It is too early to tell whether this is a temporary aberration
or if consumers know something the U.S. Labor Department has yet to
learn,'' Linden said.
   The government reported last week that unemployment declined to
5.6 percent in March, largely because of a drop in the total work
force.
   The Conference Board survey questioned 5,000 households across
the country. It was conducted by National Family Opinion Inc. of
Toledo, Ohio.
</TEXT>
