<1ST_LINE>r f AM-MooreMcCormack     04-04 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Moore McCormack,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moore McCormack To Meet On Offers, Recapitalization</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moore McCormack Resources, Inc., the target of a
$512 million takeover bid from Southdown Inc., said its board will
meet Tuesday to consider the offer and any other proposals it may
receive.
   In a statement Monday, Moore McCormack acknowledged it is
``engaged in negotiations concerning the acquisition of the entire
company.''
   The Stamford, Conn.-based cement and energy company said it has
provided ``certain third parties including Southdown'' the terms
under which it would agree to be acquired.
   Houston-based Southdown, which initially offered $35 a share for
Moore McCormack, sweetened its bid in late March a day after Moore
McCormack unveiled a defensive recapitalization plan.
   Southdown's latest offer would pay $35 in cash plus debt
securities valued at $5 for each of Moore McCormack's 12.8 million
common shares outstanding, an indicated total value of $512
million. Southdown also has offered to acquire Moore McCormack
preferred stock and subordinated debt.
   In trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Moore McCormack rose
$1.125 to close at $40.50 a share.
   Under terms of Moore McCormack's recapitalization plan, the
company would borrow up to $420 million and sell assets to finance
a special dividend to shareholders of $24.60 per share in cash and
debt securities with a face value of $6.62 per share.
   Moore McCormack said in a statement that in addition to
reviewing any acquisition proposals it may receive, its directors
also would consider whether to proceed with the recapitalization
plan.
</TEXT>
