<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 2033EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Foreign-Bearings     04-04 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Foreign-Bearings,0323</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Torrington Co. Files Anti-Dumping Petitions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORRINGTON, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Torrington Co. has filed petitions with
the federal government charging that foreign manufacturers are
dumping anti-friction bearings in the United States and hurting
domestic manufacturers.
   Torrington, the largest broad-line bearing maker in the United
States and a subsidary of Ingersoll-Rand, filed anti-dumping and
countervailing duty petitions last week against a number of
European and Asian nations exporting anti-friction bearings to the
United States.
   Countries named in the unfair trade petitions are Japan, West
Germany, Italy, France, the United Kingdom, Sweden, Singapore,
Thailand and Romania.
   Imports of bearings covered by petitions amounted to roughly
$500 million in 1987. The petitions claim that the ``dumping'' had
reached significant levls, with foreign manufacturers selling
bearings in the United States at prices as low as half their fair
market value.
   ``Torrington is committed to taking positive action to stop the
dumping of bearings in the U.S. market,'' said Thomas E. Bennett,
company president. ``Our industry continues, unnecessarily, to be
the victim of unfairly low pricing by many of our foreign
competitors.
   ``These unfair trade petitions are intended to neutralize the
dumping and subsidization that have distorted conditions of
competition in the United States market.''
   The company's petitions were filed last Thursday with the
International Trade Commission and the U.S. Department of Commerce,
the two government agencies responsible for investigating charges
of unfair trade practices.
   Preliminary findings are anticipated from the International
Trade Commission by mid-May and from the Commerce Department
sometime between late June and late fall.
   Dwight Keeney, a company spokesman, said government figures
indicate that from 1980 to 1985, employment in the domestic
bearings industry declined 24.7 percent, from 52,600 to 39,600.
   Loss of production jobs in the industy for the same period was
26.5 percent, from 42,300 jobs in 1980 to 31,100 jobs in 1985.
Keeney said the decline continues.
</TEXT>
