<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 2035EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-FTC-Belzbergs     04-04 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FTC-Belzbergs,0352</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Belzberg Firm Agrees to Pay $400,000 Fine in Ashland Stock Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A holding company controlled by the Belzberg
family of Canada has agreed to pay a $400,000 fine to settle a
lawsuit charging its 1986 purchase of Ashland Oil Co. stock
violated an anti-takeover law.
   The settlement between the Federal Trade Commission and First
City Financial Corp. Ltd. of Vancouver, British Columbia, was made
public in court papers filed last week in U.S. District Court here.
   The FTC charged in a lawsuit filed Friday along with the
proposed settlement that First City violated the Hart-Scott-Rodino
antitrust law by failing to notify the government of Ashland stock
purchases exceeding $15 million.
   The complaint charged that First City and its parent, Roxboro
Investments Ltd., had also violated the law by continuing to
purchase more than a $15 million stake in Ashland without notifying
the FTC and observing a 30-day waiting period.
   First City said in a statement it ``did not violate the
Hart-Scott-Rodino Act'' but ``agreed to settle to avoid the expense
of singlehandedly litigating a longstanding interpretive dispute
between the FTC and the investment community.''
   The settlement must be given final approval by U.S. District
Judge John H. Pratt.
   The oil company's stock rose 10 percent following a March 25,
1986 announcement that the Belzbergs had acquired 9.2 percent of
Ashland stock and offered to pay $60 a share to buy a controlling
interest in the Kentucky-based refining company.
   On April 2, 1986, the Belzberg companies sold their 9.2 percent
stake in Ashland for $134.1 million under an agreement with the oil
company.
   First City is also a defendant in a parallel action brought in
federal court here by the Securities and Exchange Commission
arising from the transaction.
   The SEC suit charges that First City arranged for its brokerage
house, Bear, Stearns & Co., to buy and hold shares of Ashland stock
so that the Canadian firm could avoid the pre-merger notifcation
requirements.
   First City has denied there was any understanding with Bear,
Stearns.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
