<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Ben&Jerry'sSubway     04-04 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ben & Jerry's Subway,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ice Cream Makers Having Trouble With Subway Philanthropy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ben & Jerry, those irrepressible Vermont
ice-cream makers, conceded Monday that it may be easier to make
Coffee Heath Bar Crunch than to make a New York subway station
shine.
   It was about a year ago that Ben Cohen and Jerry Greenfield,
whose Ben & Jerry's ice cream has become a favorite of the upscale
ice cream set, proposed to spruce up and maintain a subway station
in Manhattan. The company is based in Waterbury, Vt.
   Their choice was the 72nd Street IRT station, which Cohen, just
down from Vermont, found ``really disgusting.'' Most New Yorkers
would say it's better than most, but that's another story.
   Cohen and Greenfield offered to spend their entire New York
advertising budget for the year _ $200,000 to $250,000 _ cleaning,
painting and maintaining the station.
   The Transit Authority said yes. The Transport Workers Union said
no.
   The problem was that Ben & Jerry wanted to use some non-union
workers on the project. ``Our position,'' said union spokesman Jim
Gannon, ``is that we'll cooperate but the people who do the work
have to be TA employees.''
   Negotiations dragged on and Ben & Jerry finally set a March 31
deadline. That passed too; the matter went before an independent
arbitrator who is expected to rule soon.
   So on Monday, Ben & Jerry set up an ice cream wagon and a van at
a park across the street from the subway station and began doling
out free ice cream to anyone who wanted it. It was supposed to be a
consolation prize for subway passengers emerging from the filthy
station. Ben & Jerry were there to promise that they'd keep trying
to spruce it up.
   Nobody seemed to care about the station, though _ not while
there was free ice cream to be had.
   ``I love the fact that the homeless people keep going back for
seconds,'' mused Ben & Jerry's sales and marketing director, Allan
Kaufman.
   ``It doesn't look like they're getting the message,'' said Ben,
breaking into gales of laughter.
   ``It's OK with me,'' said Jerry.
</TEXT>
