<1ST_LINE>u f AM-IBM-Chips 1stLd-Writethru   04-04 0606</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-IBM-Chips, 1st Ld-Writethru,0625</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IBM Confirms Private Offers Of Chips To Other Companies</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs headline and 1st graf to change description of offers
from secret to private.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. confirmed
Monday it has been privately offering to sell computer chips to
other companies for about two years.
   But IBM denied that its aim was to prevent the U.S. electronics
industry from becoming overly dependent on Japanese chip suppliers.
Instead, it said, it was trying to test the quality of its own
chips by seeing if anyone else would want to buy them.
   IBM is the world's largest maker of semiconductors but consumes
almost all of its own output. The company said it never had the
intention of entering the merchant chip market on a large scale.
   It said it had offered ``limited quantities of semiconductors to
a very small number of companies internationally.'' It declined to
confirm it had actually made any sales.
   ``The goal is to sharpen ourselves competitively by having these
companies (customers) assess price, function and performance
against the best chips in the world available from other vendors,
which of course includes the Japanese,'' IBM spokesman Peter Thonis
said.
   The first report that IBM had offered to sell chips to
competitors came last month in a new book, ``Trading Places: How We
Allowed Japan to Take the Lead,'' by Clyde Prestowitz, formerly the
Commerce Department's chief trade negotiator.
   Details were reported Monday by the New York Times, based on
anonymous sources and an interview with Jack Kuehler, an IBM vice
chairman.
   The offers were apparently kept undisclosed at the request of
the potential customers, which did not want it known that they were
considering buying chips from IBM.
   ``Testing of chips in actual business conditions provides the
best gauge of how IBM's technology stacks up,'' Thonis said Monday.
``In some cases we found we were not as competitive, and in those
instances we've worked to correct it. In other areas we found we
were true industry leaders.''
   IBM said it was offering only its chips, not its underlying
designs or process technology. It declined to comment on how many
companies had bought chips, if any; the value of the purchases; or
the names of any customers.
   IBM would have to increase its chip production vastly to become
an important alternative source of chips for U.S. or European
electronics companies, and the company said it did not have that in
mind.
   ``We're neither accepting orders for semiconductors nor
increasing capacity,'' Thonis said.
   IBM officials have said the company's own health depends on
maintaining a strong domestic ability to produce chips, training a
large number of microelectronic engineers and sustaining a strong
semiconductor equipment manufacturing business so IBM will not need
to depend on Japan for the most up-to-date technology.
   Along those lines, IBM has been a major backer of Sematech, the
industry-government project to improve the quality of chip
manufacturing technology in the United States.
   In his book, Prestowitz said Digital Equipment Corp., IBM's
biggest rival, was one of the companies that held talks with IBM on
chip purchases. Digital's president, Kenneth Olsen, seemed to
confirm that in a New York Times interview.
   But Mark Fredrickson, a Digital spokesman, said Monday the
company could not confirm the discussions. He also denied
suggestions that Digital was in danger of becoming overly dependent
on Japanese chips.
   ``We think that the amount of value we add from capabilities
within our own organization is so pervasive that to suggest that
there is a dangerous dependence on anyone from outside doesn't make
sense,'' Fredrickson said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
