<FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 2104EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-BankBid     04-04 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bank Bid,0484</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Irving Sues Bank Of New York; Makes Earnings Forecast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Irving Bank Corp. predicted Monday that it would
earn a profit of more than $200 million in 1988, and it urged
shareholders again to reject as inadequate Bank of New York's
hostile $1.08 billion tender bid.
   Meanwhile, the banking concern said it filed a lawsuit in state
court attempting to block a proxy solicitation of Bank of New York,
which began its tender offer last month and is seeking to gain
control of Irving's board of directors.
   In a letter to shareholders sent over the weekend, Irving
forecast 1988 net income of $234 million, or about $11.78 a share,
on revenue of $1.14 billion.
   Last year, Irving reported a loss of $193.3 million, compared
with a net profit of $128.1 million, or $6.83, in 1986, largely due
to its increased loan-loss provision to cover shaky Third World
debt.
   Irving attributed the projected improvement, in part, to
continued strong performance in its domestic and community banking
businesses.
   ``Your company is performing in line with the 1988 forecast
based on the results of the first two months of 1988,'' the letter
said. ``Book value per share is projected to increase to
approximately $50 from $40.91 at Dec. 31, 1987.
   ``Bank of New York's offer ... represents a multiple of only 1.2
times Irving's forecasted book value,'' it said.
   Bank of New York spokesman Owen Brady said, ``We don't know the
basis on which the calculated projections were made. We can't make
a meaningful comment.''
   Bank of New York's current offer _ of $15 in cash and 1.575
shares of its own stock for each of Irving's roughly 18.1 common
shares outstanding _ has been denounced as inadequate by Irving's
board.
   Last month, Bank of New York began its tender offer after
receiving the go-ahead from the Securities and Exchange Commission,
and the company assembled a slate of 16 nominees to Irving's board.
Bank of New York currently holds a 4.83 percent stake in Irving.
   Irving has repeatedly stressed its desire to remain independent
and has taken a number of steps to spurn Bank of New York's
advances, including instituting an anti-takeover ``poison pill,''
intended to make any hostile buyout prohibitively expensive.
   Irving's lawsuit, filed in state court, seeks damages in excess
of about $350 million.
   It claims that Bank of New York's proxy material is false and
misleading, particularly in the way it valued Irving's portfolio of
Third World debt. Irving claimed the portfolio was overstated by
about $208 million.
   The suit was filed late last week and mentioned in a filing with
the Securities and Exchange Commission, said David Santos, an
Irving spokesman.
   Brady called the suit ``without merit,'' and said the banking
concern would seek a dismissal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
